<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Bristol &amp; West chief quits suddenly
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK and VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRISTOL &amp; West, the UK's 10th largest building society, yesterday announced
the abrupt departure of Mr Tony FitzSimons as chief executive.
The society suffered a sharp rise in lending provisions last year, following
what industry analysts regard as over-ambitious lending in the south of the
UK between 1989 and 1991. .
Bristol &amp; West said Mr Fitz-Simons was resigning 'with immediate effect'.
His departure follows the appointment four months ago of Lord Armstrong of
Ilminster as chairman.
Since Mr FitzSimons's appointment in spring 1989, Bristol &amp; West has
suffered particularly high levels of bad debt during the housing recession,
while pursuing expansionist policies.
The society's pre-tax profit fell to Pounds 39.1m last year, from Pounds
67.4m, as lending provisions nearly tripled to Pounds 74.1m from Pounds
24.5m. However, a recovery had begun in the first half of this year, with
interim pre-tax profits more than doubling to Pounds 20.4m, total mortgage
arrears falling 19 per cent and the ratio of cost to income substantially
reduced.
Mr FitzSimons could not be contacted yesterday. In a prepared statement, he
said: 'I have a number of interesting avenues I have wished to pursue and
hope that they will see fruition in the not too distant future.'
Bristol &amp; West said there were no immediate plans for a change of strategy
and stressed that it was financially strong.
Lord Armstrong said: 'Our first priority is to manage out the arrears, make
sure we maintain high quality and bring our costs down.' He added that the
society was 'looking for the possibility of mergers'.
Two long-standing Bristol &amp; West executives change positions as a result of
the resignation. Mr John Burke, business development director, becomes chief
executive and Mr Jeff Warren, finance director, becomes his deputy.
The society's most recent figures showed that 5.1 per cent of its mortgages
were more than 12 months in arrears, considerably above the industry norm.
While its competitors were reducing their number of branch offices, Bristol
&amp; West was investing heavily. Its total number rose from 171 in 1988 to 186
in 1991, before falling to 178 last year.
The 1992 report and accounts show that Mr FitzSimons, who was the
highest-paid director, received a salary of more than Pounds 195,000.
Mr John Wriglesworth, building society analyst at UBS, said: 'He was
considered deal hungry and many investors have been worried that he could
'bet the bank' with some future deal.'
</TEXT>
