<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / No backtracking on 'open skies' policy, says Brussels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Commission told the 12 EC member states and European flag
airlines yesterday there would be no going back on the Community's 'open
skies' regime, agreed last year to deregulate and promote greater
competition in air transport.
At a special meeting in Brussels last night where EC transport ministers
discussed the financial crisis in civil aviation with industry
representatives, Brussels stood on its EC treaty rights to police
competition and took an uncompromising line.
'There is no question of backtracking, and I've made that absolutely plain,'
said Mr Karel Van Miert, EC competition commissioner. 'What some of (the
airlines) are after apparently is a price cartel,' he added, 'and that we
cannot and will not allow. We won't accept a fare cartel or a capacity
reduction cartel.'
On the table at the meeting was a working paper from the Belgian presidency
of the EC, calling for the reintroduction of passenger capacity-sharing
between airlines, and suggesting for the first time EC funding for airlines
in trouble and for air transport infrastructure.
But a return to collusion on passenger quotas between airlines was ruled out
by a big majority of member states, as was co-operation on price-setting. Mr
Van Miert ruled out the possibility of EC funding. He remarked on 'a certain
nostalgia' among airlines for the cosy, state-bankrolled cartels that
existed before EC liberalisation.
On the day that the French transport ministry announced it was earmarking
FFr5bn (Pounds 581m) for a further recapitalisation of Air France, the
troubled state-owned airline, Mr John MacGregor, the UK transport minister,
said he was encouraged that all airline industry representatives at the
meeting condemned state aids as adding to overcapacity.
Mr Van Miert, who as transport commissioner until this year approved big
cash injections into Sabena, the Belgian state carrier, Air France, and
Iberia, the Spanish flag airline, reaffirmed the doctrine that these were
'last-chance' agreements.
The Belgian Socialist commissioner said the criterion was that 'there has to
be a credible plan for returning the company to viability', and that if
those plans turned out badly, there would be no second chance.
Mr Van Miert said pending rulings on state aids for Aer Lingus, Olympic
Airways, and Air France, were the responsibility of the transport
commissioner.
Editorial Comment, Page 19
</TEXT>
