<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / The Lex Column: Grand Metropolitan
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Yesterday's statement from Grand Metropolitan at least showed the market was
wrong in worrying about a Guinness-style disappointment on the trading
front. But there is a bitter-sweet message in the accompanying disclosure
that the group is to take a Pounds 175m charge for restructuring. The
positive aspect is that it is getting to grips with Green Giant, the
vegetable business acquired as part of the Pillsbury deal. GrandMet also
appears to be dressing up Pearle for sale.
That will help ease gearing pressure when it eventually happens. But the
provisions will eat into cash flow meanwhile. Nor does it help that the
company has given no details of how it will use Pounds 50m of yesterday's
charge. Perhaps it must slim down other businesses before they can be sold
at a reasonable price.
Some reorganisation spend was inevitable to shield Green Giant from the
effects of vegetable price fluctuations. GrandMet's slowness in grasping the
commodity nature of this business will hardly have counted in favour of Mr
Ian Martin, who was responsible for the Pillsbury acquisition but lost the
contest for the chief executive's job. Separating the two announcements by
just a weekend does little to dispel the idea that they were in some way
connected.
</TEXT>
