<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / The Lex Column: European Airlines
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
On the surface, the decision of Mr Jan Carlzon, SAS's president, to step
down in order to work on the proposed pan-European alliance looks like a
rescue mission. The delay in signing an agreement with Swissair, KLM, and
Austrian Airlines suggests some fundamental stumbling blocks, and Mr Carlzon
has staked particular credibility on the project. Austrian is still being
openly courted by Lufthansa, so there must be a chance that at least the
junior partner will drop out.
But losing Austrian need not scupper a deal among the remaining three.
Framing an agreement to satisfy four airlines, six national governments and
innumerable trade unions always looked likely to take longer than the
original timetable allowed. Decisions over job losses and where to site head
office are politically charged. There is scope for disagreement over
ownership. With the strongest balance sheet and newest fleet, Swissair in
particular may feel entitled to more than the 30 per cent share originally
envisaged.
The main reason for optimism is that all three larger airlines badly need a
deal. A strong balance sheet does not compensate for Swissair's lack of
critical mass. SAS has the largest and most secure home market, but
geography makes it weak in international markets. Burdened by debt - and
with the memory of its abortive attempt to link with BA still fresh - KLM
wants safety in numbers. Mr Carlzon's prophecy that there will be five
European airlines by the turn of the century still looks correct.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Scandinavian Airlines System.
    Swissair.
    KLM Royal Dutch Airlines.
    Austrian Airlines.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>SEZ  Sweden, West Europe.
    NOZ  Norway, West Europe.
