<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Leading Article: Clouds in EC open skies
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE IS an air of the predictable, as well as of the melodramatic, in the
dispute among EC governments and airlines about solving the financial
problems of the European aviation industry. On the liberal side of the ring
are the UK and the Netherlands, champions of airline free enterprise, and
critics of subsidies and restrictive practices which help make scheduled EC
air fares on many routes 50 per cent higher than US levels. In the opposing
corner is a larger group of member states with loss-making national
carriers, proposing extra regulations and government cash to alleviate the
hardships of the recession.
The gap in attitudes extends beyond the sector's specific difficulties. In
statements which appear to advertise the UK government's reasons for not
signing the EC social chapter, British Airways' continental rivals say that
relatively low UK social charges diminish their ability to compete.
In a European industry with a diverse structure and history, beset by the
common handicap of inadequate airport infrastructure, and facing likely
consolidation into a smaller number of large global carriers, the search for
a common policy is fraught with difficulty. However, unless the EC avoids
the dangers of fragmentation and diversion along its path to liberalisation,
the ultimate beneficiaries of the process - consumers - will not reap full
advantage.
This month's Brussels hearings by the EC's committee of 'wise men' into
airline problems have illustrated the nature of these challenges. Three
agreements on EC air liberalisation during the past six years have generated
a level of competition which, along with over-capacity induced by the
late-1980s aircraft order boom, is forcing less efficient carriers to carry
out slimming and lay-offs.
Rightly rejected
Yesterday's proposal by Belgium, the current EC president, to reintroduce
passenger capacity quotas runs contrary to the spirit of EC airline
liberalisation. The suggestion was rightly rejected last night by the EC
Commission. Yet the political will on the continent to tone down what are
viewed as the effects of untrammelled deregulation should not be
underestimated.
Belgium's initiative was given tacit support by other countries, including
France. Several airlines are mounting requests for fresh state aid,
including Belgium's financially troubled Sabena, as well as the Spanish and
Portuguese carriers. The Irish government, a traditional liberalising force
in aviation, is seeking approval to grant Aer Lingus IPounds 175m in extra
funds, in a package involving extensive job cuts.
Counter-attack
Meanwhile Mr Bernard Attali, the Air France chairman, has stated that the
British liberalisation crusade is partly based on hypocrisy, claiming that
the UK's 1977 air traffic agreement with the US gives Britain unfair
advantages. Mr Attali's claim deserves study. The old airline accords by
Germany and France with the US allowed American airlines much greater access
to Frankfurt and Charles de Gaulle airports than allowed to Heathrow by the
1977 agreement. Yet Mr Attali's counter-attack also illustrates the
difficulty of looking at European airlines' predicament in anything but a
global context.
The drive towards international airline partnerships and mergers is so
advanced that a retreat to the previous system of national protection would
be unfeasible and unwise. As a centrepiece of its competition policy, the EC
has no choice but to encourage loss-making airlines to carry through further
restructuring. Although this will require some smaller European airlines to
merge or close in coming years, the industry will be in a better shape to
face the next business cycle.
Difficulties caused by variations in EC airlines' economic environments can
best be tackled through privatisation. This path can be trodden only after
restructuring decisions of the sort taken by Lufthansa and Air France are
implemented. Over the longer term, to prevent US airlines from winning undue
advantage, the EC should work towards taking over responsibility for
transatlantic air traffic accords. That goal, however, will require a great
deal more EC harmony than is currently evident; it can be reached only at
the end of a struggle which has just begun.
</TEXT>
<XX>
