FT  28 SEP 93 / Observer: On bended knee
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Successful overseas industrialists could be forgiven for asking why Britain
tarried well into the final decade of the 20th century before setting up a
Foundation for Manufacturing Industry (FMI). Observer merely wishes to point
out that almost everything else has been tried to breathe life into the
country's ailing widget-makers.
The idea for the FMI, which dovetails neatly into the current Lord Mayor's
City and Industry in Partnership campaign, in fact stemmed largely from
Kenneth Adams, former Comino Fellow at the Royal Society of Arts. Three
years ago Adams wrote about the 'nonsense' that Christians cheerfully pray
for farmers at harvest festival but 'do not pray for successful production
in manufacturing and extractive industry or for successful achievement in
commerce'. His campaign to involve a higher being having yielded
insufficient results, he was obviously forced to turn to the earthly powers
of FMI's new chairman, Sir Trevor Holdsworth.
</TEXT>
