<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Observer: Maurizio who?
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
After almost two years of trading insults, Investcorp and Maurizio Gucci
have struck a deal, the most intriguing part of which has Gucci emerging as
an adviser to the Bahrain-based merchant bank.
In July, Investcorp, which had 50 per cent of the shares in the luxury goods
company, instigated legal action against Gucci, who had management control
and the remaining stake; it alleged mismanagement and breach of contract by
dint of his having pledged his shares to a bank.
Not the most propitious start for an enduring relationship, so the post may
therefore simply be a face-saving exercise.
So, if Gucci is not to be too preoccupied achieving synergies between
Investcorp's growing clutch of luxury goods companies, what will he do now
that he is some Dollars 170m the richer?
Callers to Gucci's plush Milan headquarters yesterday could be forgiven for
thinking they had been misrouted. Barely 48 hours after the ink was dry, the
former chairman appeared little more than a memory at the firm which bears
his name.
The persistent might now try St Moritz, that repository of idle
multi-millionaires, where Gucci maintains a home.
While the skiing may not have started yet, it's not a bad place for counting
banknotes.
</TEXT>
