<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Hong Kong's one for the road: A superhighway link with China
is a symbol of growing confidence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HARGREAVES and SIMON HOLBERTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The map on Gordon Wu's wall says it all. A floor-to-ceiling projection of
Guangdong's Pearl river delta shows the path of a 305km motorway Mr Wu is
building between Hong Kong and Macao via Guangzhou, the capital of China's
most dynamic economic region.
Although much delayed, mostly by bureaucratic hurdles, the road's 123km
first phase should be carrying traffic by the end of the year, according to
Mr Wu. Fresh from a 120mph spin on the newly laid asphalt - there will be no
speed limit - he says: 'I can't wait to do it in a Corvette.'
Mr Wu's 'superhighway' is, however, no pleasure-run. Apart from being a
crucial link between China and its gateway to the west, Hong Kong, the road
 -and its developer - symbolise the confidence with which business is
betting on China's future as a market economy. It is also a case study of
how things get done in China.
Viewed from a political angle, however, it is precisely this enmeshing of
Hong Kong's economy with the mainland that is undermining governor Chris
Patten's efforts to promote democracy in the colony before the handover to
China in 1997.
The governor says this autumn will be crucial in resolving Britain's impasse
with Beijing over Hong Kong's political development. On Friday, Mr Douglas
Hurd, UK foreign secretary, holds an important meeting in New York with Mr
Qian Qichen, his Chinese counterpart.
But what is clear is that, apart from Beijing's opposition to his plans for
more democracy in the colony, Mr Patten faces a corrosive rebellion by the
Hong Kong business class if Britain and China fail to agree a way forward.
Business, which has pervasive influence in Hong Kong, thinks Mr Patten has
got it wrong.
Mr Wu, reflecting the predominant view in the Chinese business community,
states bluntly the case that expatriates prefer to whisper in private. 'Mr
Patten is a nice guy and he means well, but he should be a bit more
patient,' he says. 'A small place like Hong Kong cannot fight communism with
guns or words. Our biggest and only opportunity is to work with them gently
and concentrate on the economy, saying to them: 'That's the way you will get
the goodies.' '
The road that Mr Wu is building goes right to the heart of these issues. He
says the idea first occurred to him on a visit to Guangdong in 1979 - a year
after Deng Xiaoping, now 89, assumed power in China and began the process of
opening up the country.
The decisive moment, however, was the Tiananmen Square massacre of June
1989, which led to a foreign investment freeze and made China's top leaders
eager to encourage projects such as Mr Wu's road. It was only then that
anyone paid serious attention to his financial and traffic projections,
enabling him to raise Dollars 800m from a consortium of banks to stand
alongside the Dollars 200m of equity supplied by his own company, Hopewell
Holdings, a construction conglomerate with interests ranging from house
building to power stations. The banks were offered an eight-year pay-back,
on the basis of traffic projections rising from 15,000 to 35,000 vehicles a
day over that period.
In China every stage of this process required months of negotiation with
provincial officials. Mr Wu tried holding out for total control over the
construction work but eventually conceded that the Chinese would take
responsibility for two stretches of the first phase. He did, however, win
the argument in favour of a six, rather than four, lane highway, arguing
that an extra two lanes would add only 19 per cent to the cost of a
four-lane road.
On tolls, he agreed a figure of 10 US cents per car per kilometre, only for
the Chinese authorities to change their minds and ask him to raise the
figure to 12 cents. Mr Wu did get his way on quality standards, using
British engineers and importing steel, cement and asphalt from around the
world. China supplied the labour.
The result is a road capable of bearing trucks with maximum loads of 16
tonnes an axle, greater than anything required by existing commercial
traffic.
Financially, phase one of the deal looks like a winner. Mr Wu is now
confident that 30,000 vehicles a day will be diverted from the dusty,
truck-choked roads of the Pearl river delta. He calculates that the banks
will have their loans repaid in only four years. In the first decade, net
profits after maintenance - for which Hopewell has the contract - are to be
divided 60:40 between Guangdong and Hopewell. For years 11 to 30, the split
is 70:30.
But for all of Mr Wu's high-level political contacts, he has not had his way
on phase two. Having been unable to agree a satisfactory work split with his
partners, he has conceded the original route to the Chinese and mapped out a
rival route about 30km to the east.
For this road he expects land acquisition to be completed by the end of this
year. Though riskier, the potential returns to Hopewell are commensurately
higher. He will earn 100 per cent of any net return in the first decade and
50 per cent thereafter.
The political pitfalls are obvious, perhaps explaining why Hopewell shares
have missed out on Hong Kong's bull market since 1992. In stockbroker
language, Hopewell is seen as a 'medium-term China infrastructure play', not
the sort of stock to yield short-term rewards for investors.
According to businessmen, political calm is required to transform China
through economic contact. Mr Wu adds that the key to a successful project is
support at the right level, which in China still means Beijing. That is how
he has navigated his way through the obfuscation and corruption for which
the Chinese bureaucracy is notorious. 'Corruption is everywhere,' he says.
The villains, he claims, are at the middle levels of the bureaucracy, where
he has found himself under pressure to procure materials of questionable
quality and provenance. 'I get ahead in China because I have the support of
top people and because they think what I do is good for the country. I don't
pay, so I don't get much help from the middle guys.'
Corruption, he maintains, is petty by some standards; a matter not of Swiss
bank accounts, more of providing cars and overseas study opportunities for
the children of Communist party officials. Mr Wu does, however, think that
the Chinese authorities are starting to crack down. 'I would not be
surprised to see executions,' he says.
He is not squeamish about China's system of law and order. But it would be
wrong to dismiss Mr Wu as an Asian tycoon ignorant of western political
concepts. Educated at Princeton, he named his son after Thomas Jefferson,
author of the Declaration of Independence. Arguing for a slower pace of
political change in Hong Kong, he rattles through two centuries of US
history since Jefferson's declaration: the emancipation of the slaves in the
1860s, women's suffrage in the 1920s, and the civil rights movement in the
1950s.
'Democracy is a very nice word and I believe in it,' he says. 'But these
changes should take place over time and not overnight. Mr Patten should be
more patient. The House of Lords is still an appointed body after 700 years;
why should people worry about functional constituencies being made up from
select groups of people?'
This is a reference to the complex internal mechanics of the colony's
Legislative Council, its 60-strong law-making body, only a third of which
will be popularly elected by 1997. Mr Patten faces a battle this autumn to
push through a timetable for enhanced accountability, having already watered
down his proposals to a point where one important faction of LegCo, headed
by lawyer Mr Martin Lee, says that democracy has been betrayed.
No one can yet tell whether, or how, London and Beijing will settle their
differences. But anxiety is growing that they may not do so this year or
perhaps at all, leaving the colony to lurch into Chinese ownership without a
sustainable advance in democratic procedures.
The point, still difficult to grasp for spectators in western democracies,
is that most business leaders view the 1997 handover with equanimity. It is
for this reason that many in the business community have ceased trying to
persuade Mr Patten to change course.
Asked what is his biggest concern about the fateful date, Mr Wu replies:
'Nothing, really. I don't believe China will revert to the communist planned
economy thing.'
Nor does he accept that Beijing's accession will import the corruption he
has wrestled with in Guangdong. Not many in Hong Kong would agree with him.
Indeed, spreading corruption is the main fear of a Hong Kong middle class
that does not have high-level Beijing connections or the financial resources
of top business people.
Mr Wu says that within 15 years China will resemble, but on an enormous
scale, Taiwan, which has moved in recent years from a plainly authoritarian
to a recognisably plural society. The key to this development, he says, has
been the influence of young Taiwanese educated abroad, who now have seats in
the commanding heights of politics and the economy. The same process is
under way throughout China.
Not even the death of Deng is seen as altering this course. 'Deng will be
sadly missed: he's a great man. Deng and Gorbachev are the great guys of the
century. But for China the die is cast.'
This leads the conversation back to Thomas J Wu. Fresh from graduation at
Princeton - where he has capped his father's grade Cs in engineering with a
row of As - TJ, says his father, will probably do a couple of years in the
engine room of someone else's business and then perhaps graduate school. But
his father's idea of his future in post-1997 Hong Kong could not be clearer.
'I would like him to be running this company.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Hopewell Holdings.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>HKZ  Hong Kong, Asia.
    CNZ  China, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P1611 Highway and Street Construction.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>RES  Facilities.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 19
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT933-672</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DI1CRADOFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930928
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / No particular Asian cocktail
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HARGREAVES and SIMON HOLBERTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Chris Patten counters his critics in the Hong Kong business world with
the argument that the colony's economy cannot prosper after 1997 without
some kind of democratic underpinning. He accuses his opponents of
appeasement, write Ian Hargreaves and Simon Holberton.
'I think the divide is much more clearly between those who think we should
actually stand up for Hong Kong and those who think we shouldn't have a
bottom line except to do what China wants,' said the Hong Kong governor.
'But would the business community actually think we'd be better served if I
had to spend my time explaining to interested American pension funds, when
they come through Hong Kong, how a batch of (undemocratic) arrangements for
elections in Hong Kong were really going to enable us to maintain the rule
of law and Hong Kong's values after 1997?'
In an interview in his office at Government House, Mr Patten argued that
democracy and the rule of law are inseparable, disputing the idea that there
is a 'particular Asian cocktail' which delivers prosperity without political
rights.
'I don't happen to believe that,' he said. 'The notion, which is sometimes
advanced by Lee Kuan Yew (former Singapore prime minister) and others, that
somehow democracy helps to blunt economic prospects and growth in Asia and
elsewhere, doesn't seem to be an argument that is applied very obviously to
Japan. Korea and Taiwan are both emerging as much closer to participative
multi-party democracies than the sort of benign authoritarianism that
existed there before.'
An accountable and credible government in Hong Kong would underpin business,
not weaken it, he asserted. 'If we agree to rig the election in 1995, that
won't produce political stability in Hong Kong in 1997 - anything but - and
it is exceptionally short-sighted not to recognise that. Second, it will
harm the prospects of the rule of law surviving 1997. I think that would
open the door to corruption, I think it would open the door for the flight
of capital. If Hong Kong is no different from anywhere else on the (south
China) coast, why stay here, why do business here, why give Hong Kong a
better credit rating?'
Did he not find it remarkable that a former chairman of the UK Conservative
party, appointed to the governorship of a colony built on commerce, should
be so at odds with the business community? Did this not weaken Britain's
negotiating position with Beijing?
'I don't think it makes any difference to our negotiating stance,' said Mr
Patten. 'I'd much prefer it if I had the unanimous support of the business
community. What I'm delighted about is that I still seem to have substantial
support in the community at large. I'd be more worried if everyone in the
business community thought I was doing a terrific job and hardly anyone in
the community thought I was.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
