<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Letters to the Editor: UN must be more even-handed in
sponsoring peace in Angola
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr I SAMAKUVA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, The United Nations Security Council has just imposed, as you reported
('UN imposes sanctions on Angolan rebels', September 17), an arms and oil
embargo on Unita via Resolution 864. Moreover, it has threatened further
sanctions on Unita, covering a trade ban and travel restrictions, if a
ceasefire has not been agreed by November 1. This is a manifestly retrograde
step. It not only serves to delay, even to obstruct, the peace process and
the deployment of humanitarian aid, but poses the question of whether UN
actions are hindering or facilitat-ing a peaceful settle-ment to Angola's
problems.
The UN role in Angola, before, during and after the September elections has
been less than auspicious. The head of the UN mission during the electoral
process, Margaret Anstee, admitted recently that the UN's mandate at the
time was 'woefully inadequate'. A UN report on the elections reinforced her
view by concluding that electoral irregularities were discovered that 'could
have affected the final election result'. In addition, once the process was
derailed, an opportunity for a ceasefire, during the Abijdan talks of
April-May was lost because the UN mission in Angola was told that no 'Blue
Helmets' would be available for six to nine months. It appears that not only
was the UN under-resourced for the task but was also at odds with itself.
The UN secretary-general has recently requested that the security council
allow him more UN staff to help the UN's 'mediation and good offices' but
this has been denied. Instead the security council decided on punitive
sanctions on Unita, combined with a series of deadlines. The UN does not,
however, explain what incentive there is for the MPLA to agree a ceasefire.
If the MPLA knows that a failure to agree a ceasefire will lead to more
sanctions against Unita, clearly it will do all it can to delay agreement.
Unita does believe that the UN has a role to play, but it must be seen to be
even-handed and coherent in its policies, and it must also demonstrate that
it is prepared to commit the necessary resources on the ground to allow a
ceasefire and negotiations to take place. We look forward to seeing evidence
that this is the case.
I Samakuva,
London representative,
The National Union for the Total Independence of Angola,
3 Clifford Street,
London W1X 1RA
</TEXT>
