FT  28 SEP 93 / Letters to the Editor: Late-paying debtors - right to
interest is necessary, but perhaps unenforceable
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   FROM MARTIN CONRADI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Comments on the damage done to small businesses by the late payment of
invoices have abounded in your columns. As a small company working with
customers of all sizes, we have never experienced such problems; indeed, we
have survived the recession with improved cash flow and no bad debts. Our
secret? Simply a bookkeeper who takes the trouble to ring and ask - very
politely and, if necessary, very regularly - for our money.
Legalised interest charges will be unenforceable for most of us. Talking to
our customers about our money is a cultural inhibition; moaning about it, it
seems, is not.
Martin Conradi,
Showcase Presentations,
6 Buckingham Street,
London WC2N 6BU
