<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Letters to the Editor: Late-paying debtors - right to
interest is necessary, but perhaps unenforceable
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr MARTIN E SIMONS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, While Lord Alexander is no doubt informed, many of his UK readers may
not know that German industry usually settles its bills 'X' days, normally
30, after date of invoice.
In the UK, terms of payment are unfortunately normally on the 20th or at the
end of the month following the month of invoice.
The German system allows suppliers to apply sanctions or stop further goods
and services much more promptly when there are payment delays than is
possible under Britain's archaic system.
Another reason why settlement is prompt in Germany is that large companies
have appreciated the importance of their smaller suppliers, some of which
are undercapitalised. Also, companies in Germany are not constantly badgered
by financial analysts, who in the UK calculate asset gearing without regard
to soaring levels of trade creditors.
Martin E Simons,
24 Granard Avenue,
London SW15 6HJ
</TEXT>
