<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Letters to the Editor: Late-paying debtors - right to
interest is necessary, but perhaps unenforceable
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From A J WESTALL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, I read with some interest and approval the article contributed by Lord
Alexander, chairman of National Westminster Bank, on the subject of late
payment of debts and the basic fairness of an interest entitlement on
overdue amounts (Personal View, September 23).
The British Chambers of Commerce has surveyed its membership and has
concluded that late payment of debts, particularly by large organisations,
including government departments, is a major problem to small and
medium-sized enterprises.
However, I would point out to Lord Alexander that I have on many occasions,
particularly over the past two years, in consultation with clients' bankers,
been told by them in no uncertain terms that existing facilities cannot be
exceeded and the only way to comply is by delaying payments to creditors.
I suggest that, as in so many other instances, the banks may be accused of
speaking with more than one voice. The solution surely is, as Lord Alexander
suggests, to change the law so as to oblige debtors to meet obligations on
time.
Perhaps Lord Alexander's campaign can be joined by other persons of
influence to achieve more order and stability in our trading environment.
A J Westall,
chairman,
South West Chamber of
Commerce,
Foliot House,
Budshead Road,
Plymouth, Devon PL6 5XR
</TEXT>
