<DATE>930928
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Letters to the Editor: Dangerous path to advocate for
Yeltsin to safeguard society
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From JEFF SCHUBERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, John Lloyd and Leyla Boulton ('Iron fist and an iron glove', September
25) refer to the dangers of a dictatorship in Russia, the 'supine nature of
the media' and the apparent fact that it was an insult by Ruslan Khasbulatov
about the drinking habits of the president that was 'crucial' in Yeltsin's
move against the parliament.
They also point out that the regions and republics are taking advantage of
the situation to increase their independence.
I would like to make several points. First, Yeltsin himself actively
encouraged the regions and republics in their separatism by attempting to
use them as a tool against the parliament.
Second, the article suggests that Yeltsin 'must' use both the 'iron first
and the iron glove' - echoing a theme in your editorial the previous day
('Next steps for Mr Yeltsin') that a constitution that gives power to the
president is the 'only basis for stable democratic rule in Russia'. In the
face of the comments about a 'supine' media and the importance of the
relatively trivial (in a healthy democracy at least) Khasbulatov insult,
these are dangerous urgings.
Third, if Yegor Gaider, first deputy prime minister, manages to tighten
macroeconomic conditions significantly before the election, unemployment and
the hardship of many will increase. Moreover, the effects of greater
reliance on market forces will vary between regions and republics,
heightening the separatist desire of some.
What will happen if these (and other) factors produce a new parliament that
is not willing to accept either the Yeltsin version of a new constitution or
the Gaider economic policies? Would you suggest that Yeltsin dissolve it?
What should he do about separatist regions and republics that have seen a
constitution torn up? Crush them?
Your newspaper, western governments and international financial institutions
(which have been 'crucial' in assisting Yeltsin to act decisively) have
chosen a dangerous path in encouraging Yeltsin and his men to believe only
they know how to mould a new society.
Jeff Schubert,
43 Kutuzovsky Prospect,
Moscow
</TEXT>
<XX>
