<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Arts: True spirits of the fin de siecle - William Packer
takes a progressive look at the work of the Nabis movement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM PACKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This exhibition of the work of the Nabis continues the Reunion des Musees
Nationaux's fine series, begun more than a decade ago, of major studies of
the great French painters of the later 19th century, this time in
partnership with the Kunsthaus at Zurich. For the first time, however, it is
given not to a single master but to a group or movement that more than any
other, perhaps, represents the true spirit of the 1890s and the fin de
siecle.
It is in the nature of young artists, full of idealistic ambition, to rescue
art from the ever sorry state into which it has fallen, and that the
like-minded should form themselves into a group in order to set it on the
single path of righteousness - of which they alone are sure. It is equally
in the nature of art itself that it should resist such worthy simplicities.
As such artists mature, so inevitably the group falls apart. The Nabis held
together, albeit ever more loosely, for a dozen years, which is unusually
long a time for these things. The natural paradox of this exhibition is that
while it celebrates their commendable community of spirit, its actual
substance is the story of their burgeoning individual talents.
They were all young men, brought together in the summer of 1888 by Paul
Serusier from among his friends associated with the Ecole des Beaux Arts and
the Academie Julian. The founding nucleus consisted of Pierre Bonnard, Henri
Ibels, Paul Ranson and Maurice Denis; Rene Piot, Kerr-Xavier Roussel and
Eduoard Vuillard were brought in from outside, and later on, among others,
Aristide Maillol and Felix Valloton.
The name came a little later. Nabi is the hebrew word for prophet,
enthusiast, seer: and here was this group of young artists in whom, as
Serusier would write in 1889, the state of enthusiasm had become habitual.
They would meet every week, bringing with them an 'ikon' each, a work of to
be put up for general discussion. But their interests were more closely
focused than that might suggest. They were, in Denis' words, devotees of
symbolism, and their importance lies in the link they made in their work,
building on the freer painterliness made available to them by the
impressionists and putting it to the service of a more deeply personal and
metaphysical expression.
Looking back now across a full century, we can see that 'impressionism' for
too long masked other and no less fundamental concurrent influences upon the
course of modernism. Symbolism was one that was at least as important and
enduring, and which, now we choose to recognise it, we may see at once at
work in all of Picasso, in much of fauvism and expressionism, and in all
surrealism. In our own day, the conceptual echoes still reverberate.
The Nabis in their own day knew rather better, and were immediate in
recognising the importance of what Gauguin, Van Gogh and Emile Bernard had
achieved even before 1890, to say nothing of the work of earlier mentors
such as Puvis de Chavannes, Millet, Moreau, and even our own Burne-Jones,
all of whom have been left critically unconsidered until comparatively
recently. Gauguin and his disciples at least gave credit where it was due.
It is a weakness of this exhibition, only marginally corrected in a massive
and splendid catalogue that not everyone will buy, that such antecedents
should not have been made manifest. The rule of this series of exhibitions
has been always to stick to the immediate subject, but with a group rather
than a single artist, especially one that initially was so polemical, the
rule should have been broken.
The omission is all the more odd given the no less reasonable inclusion of
several wood-block prints to illustrate the influence of the Japanese
masters.
Gauguin indeed is the ghost at this feast. Serusier had been with him in
Pont-Aven, considered him an honorary Nabi in any case, and remained in
correspondence with him in the South Seas, regularly urging him to associate
himself with the group. He was simply revered. 'What Manet was for the
generation of 1870', said Denis, 'Gauguin was to that of 1890 . . . He freed
us from all the shackles that the idea of copying brought to our instincts
as painters.'
'How do you see those trees?' Gauguin had asked Serusier. 'They are yellow.
Then paint them yellow; that shadow, rather blue, paint it with pure
ultramarine; those red leaves? make them vermilion.' Serusier's small
Pont-Aven landscape of 1888 is called le Talisman simply because that is
what it became for the Nabis, the true image and touchstone of their
painterly principles. And it is in its very painterliness, rather than any
symbolic intent, that its prescience lies. It is a bridge 20 years into the
future, all the way indeed to the fauves and the expressionists of der
Brucke itself.
For it is in the painterliness of the Nabis that their final dissolution is
foreshadowed: in the love and sensual indulgence in paint almost for its own
sake, and, in the print-making especially, the delicate attention paid to
surface and its formal graphic sophistication. Colour may always carry with
it its own symbolic charge, albeit ambiguous, abstract and unspoken. What we
see in the work of the Nabis as it progresses through the 1890s is openly
symbolic or mystical imagery giving way by degrees to the imagery of the
domestic and the everyday, though always cast at a certain remove in terms
of the decorative and the exquisitely refined.
And how positively these individual talents declare themselves. This is not
the place to dilate upon the greater, familiar talents of such as Bonnard or
Vuillard, but the petits matres are matres still. Valloton and Roussel
especially are as outstanding as they are surprising.
Nabis - 1888-1890: Grand Palais, Place Clemenceau, Paris 8, until January 3:
sponsored by Aerospatiale.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FRZ  France, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8412 Museums and Art Galleries.
</IN>
<XX>
