<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Arts: A Bernstein birthday concert
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAX LOPPERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Leonard Bernstein, who would have been 75 last August, was much loved by the
London Symphony Orchestra, one of the European musical organisations with
whom he maintained a regular connection almost to the end of his life. The
'Bernstein Anniversary Concert' which the LSO and its chief conductor,
Michael Tilson Thomas, gave at the Barbican Hall on Sunday was a way of
reminding us all, players and audience alike, how much the connection meant
and, nearly three years after his death, how vitally it endures.
It was a touching, convincing and for the most part thoroughly enjoyable
way. The mixture of the most familiar of Bernstein's works (West Side Story
in its concert suite) and those less so (the concert suite from his last
opera, A Quiet Place, and the song-cycle Arias and Barcarolles) was nicely
judged. More confidently and completely (I believe) than any other non-US
orchestra, the LSO has gained mastery over the Bernstein idiom, especially
since Mr Tilson Thomas has been at their helm.
Rhythmic articulation is unfailingly spring-heeled. There is no
faint-hearted holding-back in the utterance. The LSO brass, whose
contributions were all evening a source of roof-raising excitement, showed
this particularly in the 1949 Prelude, Fugue and Riffs, with its cunning
interweave of jazz, both the Big Band variety and the bluesy, and
contrapuntal ingenuity. The danger of their overwhelming the clarinet
soloist (the excellent Andrew Marriner) was avoided by only the narrowest of
margins - and the less-than-ideal Barbican acoustics tend anyway to work
their clotting effect on big, loud climaxes - yet the feeling of dangerously
heady exhilaration was, if anything, thereby increased.
Bernstein's musical language still does not appeal to everyone. Arias and
Barcarolles (1988), most of its eight songs on modestly good-humoured texts
by the composer himself, strikes a vein of rueful tenderness - the theme is
love marital, parental and domestic, freely but sometimes questioningly felt
 -that some critics (particularly British ones) still mistake for
sentimentality.
It was originally written for voices and two pianos. A first orchestration
for strings and percussion (1989, by Bernstein and Bright Sheng) had the
effect of enlarging the canvas, not to entirely positive end. On this
occasion a new scoring (by Bruce Coughlin) for full orchestra was given its
first outing: the enlargement process is taken still further, and every
ounce of the soloists' artistry was required to sustain intimate contact
with the audience.
As these were Frederica von Stade and Thomas Hampson, singers with beautiful
voices capable of displaying kaleidoscopic shades of colour and verbal
nuance, contact was indeed sustained. But I hope their success in doing so,
comprehensive and delightful at it was, will mislead no-one into considering
the original, piano version of Arias and Barcarolles now superseded: it
remains infinitely truer to the spirit of the work.
Sponsored by Sema Group plc
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
