<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Icelanders used to be addicted to killing girl babies and were extremely
reluctant to give up the practice on converting to Christianity. In India,
it seems that not only has there always been female infanticide but it is
now hugely on the increase, according to Assignment; Live and Let Die (BBC
2; 7.45).
Ultrasound has been a boon for Indian families, because now they can abort
female foetuses - a decision some parents justify on moral grounds, so
wretched is the quality of life an unwanted female can expect. But as well
as abortion, murder continues to be practised on a wide scale (if you accept
that distinction).
It is a natural transition to the sufferings of Chinese women in Omnibus:
Wild Swans (BBC 1, 10.30). This is the film of Jung Chang's best seller, a
poignant account of the experiences of three generations of the women in her
family.
Tonight's light-hearted moments come with Armistead Maupin's Tales of the
City (C4, 9.00), another writer with a talent for transporting us to an
exotic society, San Francisco in the 1970s.
