<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Business and the Law: Fee of Dollars 4,000 an hour 'not
unreasonable' - Legal Briefs
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Who said Britain's top commercial lawyers were the most expensive in the
world by charging an average of Dollars 585 an hour? The Delaware Chancery
Court has just approved a New York lawyer's fee in a 1991 shareholder action
which amounts to more than Dollars 4,000 an hour.
According to America's National Law Journal, the judge who approved Mr
Arthur Abbey's Dollars 8.5m contingency fee, Vice-Chancellor Carolyn Berger,
said Mr Abbey should not be penalised for achieving an easy victory. The
judge said the fee, which amounted to just over 16 per cent of the sum
recovered for the shareholders, was 'generous but not unreasonable'. The
decision appears to run counter to a 1980 ruling by the Delaware Supreme
Court, which said a fee amounting to Dollars 437 an hour was the highest it
could approve.
