<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / People: The Institute of Management
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Institute of Management, which claims to be Europe's largest management
body, has chosen James Watson (above) as its new chairman. He succeeds Sir
Derek Hornby, who presided over the amalgamation last year of the British
Institute of Management and the Institute of Industrial Managers.
James Watson, chairman of NFC, has long been a member of the IM, and firmly
believes that improving the quality of management is the key to future
prosperity. He sees his main function as chairman of the IM to help ensure
that 'high standards of management education are available to managers'.
Watson is likely to be more 'hands on' than some previous chairmen. Unlike
many of the big names that have preceded him, (Sir Brian Wolfson, Sir Peter
Parker, and Sir Bob Reid have been among more high-profile past chairmen)
James Watson does not have his fingers in many other pies. He holds no other
non-executive positions, and plans to devote about a day a week to the IM.
Watson is a trained accountant who has been at NFC since 1977, where he has
been finance director and deputy chairman. With 30,000 employees, he says he
has insight into what it takes to manage well. 'I believe I'm a good
manager. I wouldn't be doing it otherwise,' he says.
</TEXT>
