<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Business and the Law: Gambling on entry to the UK market -
European Court
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRICK COURT CHAMBERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
No judgments have been delivered by the Community Courts since they returned
to work after the summer vacation on 13 September 1993. The first is
expected on 7 October. But there have been oral hearings in 12 cases.
Last week, there was a hearing in a case which may prove an important test
of the Court's interpretation of the legal principles underlying the
internal market.
The case concerns lotteries and the rights of agents representing
large-scale lotteries run by German Lander to provide their services in the
UK and to import advertising materials and tickets into the country.
Unlike certain small or private lotteries, large-scale lotteries are not
expressly permitted by the UK Lotteries and Amusements Act 1976. Importing
tickets and advertising materials relating to large-scale lotteries is also
prohibited.
According to the summary of the interested parties' arguments prepared by
French judge, M. Grevisse, the Commission drew attention to its recent
report on the EC gambling market.
The report (Gambling in the Single Market - Study of the current legal and
market situation) estimated the value of the EC gambling market, measured by
total stakes, at ECU 46.5bn (Dollars 36bn) in 1989. Lotteries and similar
activities accounted for ECU 16.7bn. National lottery markets were dominated
by state organised and controlled lotteries, except in the UK. Yet
international gambling operators, by using new technologies, are pushing the
frontiers of gambling beyond national borders.
However, the legal questions raised by this case make it likely that the
Court's ruling will be indicative of its approach to the internal market.
The key questions concern the permissible exceptions to the rules on free
movement of goods and services in the internal market, both trade
restrictions expressly exempted by the Treaty and those recognised by the
Court's past decisions as justified in the public interest.
The first question is whether the rules on trade in goods or those on
cross-border services apply. Whatever the answer, similar principles have
been applied in the past to permissible exceptions.
Eleven member countries have urged the Court to give a restrictive
interpretation of the Treaty rules on free movement of goods and services in
answer to questions referred by the London Commercial Court in proceedings
brought by the Customs and Excise. Italy has not commented.
On the other hand, the Commission told the ECJ positive answers must be
given to questions concerning the equivalence of the safeguards enforced
under German law with those applied in the general field of lotteries,
football pools and bingo in the UK.
The Commission added there is no justification for UK rules to be allowed to
go beyond those already applied to the lotteries in question by way of 'home
country control' in Germany.
If the ECJ agrees with the Commission, the UK rules will be unlawful. It
remains to be seen whether the Court will interpret the Treaty in a manner
which will promote rather than delay a genuine single market for business.
C-275/92, HM Customs &amp; Excise v Schindler, hearing ECJ FC, 22 September
1993.
Pending cases.
Recently, the Court has heard argument in cases varying from interpretation
of the 1975 directive on waste disposal (C-236/92 Comitato di Coordinamento
per la Difesa della Cava et al v Regione Lombardia et al, hearing ECJ FC, 14
September 1993) to consideration of the application of the Treaty rules on
free movement of goods to national restrictions on the advertising of
non-pharmaceutical products by pharmacists (C-292/92 Hunermund v
Landesapothekerkammer Baden-Wurttemberg, hearing ECJ FC, 15 September 1993).
In the competition field, the Court of First Instance (CFI) heard an appeal
by Cartes Bancaire against the Commission's 1991 decision imposing a fine on
the Eurocheque network's Helsinki agreement on charges relating to
Eurocheques (Joined Cases T-39/92 and T40/92, Cartes Bancaires 'CB' v
Commission, hearing CFI 1CH, 22 September 1993).
