<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / People: Ombudsman Osmotherly
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Forsaking a career in Whitehall that looked likely to take him to the top
post in a government department is Edward Osmotherly, who becomes one of the
three local government ombudsmen on November 1.
Osmotherly, 51, is currently deputy secretary at the Department of
Transport, where he is Principal Establishment and Finance Officer. Before
that, he was in charge of the department's public transport and research
activities, including responsibility for British Rail and London Transport.
He achieved temporary notoriety in 1990, when a memorandum warning of the
dangers of wholesale privatisation of BR found its ways into the hands of
the opposition.
After leaving Cambridge, Osmotherly joined the civil service in 1963 in the
ministry of housing and local government. He had several periods dealing
with local authorities, notably preparations for the local government
reorganisation in 1974. In 1972-73 he was a Harkness Fellow, studying
federal, state and local government relations in the US.
Osmotherly was seconded to British Rail in 1979, before becoming head of
machinery of government in the old Civil Service department between 1980 and
1982. There he promulgated the rules for civil servants appearing in front
of parliamentary select committees which have born his name since. He went
to the Transport department in 1982 as under secretary.
For Osmotherly, the ombudsman post offers the chance to do a 'thoroughly
valuable job' helping ordinary people find their way through the labyrinth
of local administration to get justice. He succeeds Frederick Laws, and will
be responsible for local authorities in the South West and West of England,
the West Midlands, East Anglia and parts of Southern and Central England.
(See Observer)
