<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Management (The Growing Business): Angels come to the rescue
 -A growing breed of private investors to rival the venture capitalists
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When Iain Johnston joined GB Mailing, a young software company, its founders
had already tried, unsuccessfully, to raise venture capital finance. But
most of the venture capitalists approached did not understand the technology
while the one which did thought the project was too risky. It also wanted
too large a stake in the business.
'We needed a small amount of funding to get our marketing off the ground,'
says Johnston, who is now managing director. Johnston, who had been working
as a management consultant up until the time he joined GB, turned to his
former boss, Robin Davies, for help. Davies put up Pounds 50,000 for a 5 per
cent stake.
Davies, who still heads his own consultancy, says he backed Johnston and GB
Mailing for a mixture of emotional and commercial reasons. 'It was not a
classic City-style analysis,' he says. 'I had an absolute belief that Iain
Johnston could make it succeed and the two other directors were believable
and likable people.'
GB, which sells mail sorting and marketing software, has justified his
faith. It has grown rapidly in the past three years, employs nearly 40
people and expects turnover this year to reach Pounds 2m. Davies is on the
point of exercising an option to double his holding.
Davies says this is the first time he has made an investment of this kind -
he is a non-executive director and has no day-to-day involvement. But he is
one of a growing breed of private investors or 'business angels' which has
emerged in recent years.
The typical angel has a business background. Many have made money by selling
their own business, though most are comfortably off rather than fabulously
wealthy, according to research by Colin Mason of Southampton University and
Richard Harrison of Ulster University.
Angels are more willing to invest on a hunch than the professional venture
capitalist and they are often motivated by a desire to get involved,
part-time or full-time, in the running of the business. They are also
prepared to invest relatively small amounts and to be patient investors at a
time when professional venture capitalists are concentrating on the bigger
deals and are becoming increasingly short-term.
Signs that the economy is beginning to recover have given an added urgency
to the role of angels. There are concerns that the banks will be more
cautious about backing small businesses while the demise in December of the
Business Expansion Scheme, which gives tax breaks to equity investors, will
narrow the funding options open to small firms.
Angels have been recognised for some time as providing an alternative to the
formal venture capital industry but have proved difficult to organise into a
coherent force. Linc, a 'marriage bureau' run by a group of enterprise
agencies, and Venture Capital Report, a newsletter which attempts to bring
together entrepreneurs and investors, have had only limited success. Unlike
the professional venture capitalists, business angels cannot be found in a
business directory.
'Believing in angels is like believing in motherhood - it is self-evidently
a good thing,' comments Lucius Cary, founder of Venture Capital Report
(VCR). 'There does not appear to be a downside until you go into it more
deeply. Then you find there is a large number of angels who cannot find
deals but who, at the same time, are unwilling to subscribe to VCR or one of
the other networks. There have been many initiatives over the years but most
have failed.'
After many false starts, Cary and others involved in backing entrepreneurs
believe that a turning point may now have been reached.
The key is a government-backed scheme to set up pilot marriage bureaux in
five areas of the country. The government gave Pounds 40,000 each for a
two-year experiment to five Training and Enterprise Councils (Tecs) in
Bedfordshire, Calderdale and Kirklees, Devon and Cornwall, East Lancashire
and South and East Cheshire. All five TECs have been asked to bid for a
further year's worth of funding.
The two most successful appear to be the Cheshire and Devon and Cornwall
TECs. The Cheshire programme, known as Techinvest, has brokered six deals
worth Pounds 500,000 since it was launched last February. More than 50
investors with about Pounds 1.5m of available capital have been signed up,
says Vivienne Upcott Gill, Techinvest manager.
Crucially, Techinvest has not only found investors in Cheshire. It has also
attracted angels from outside the region by establishing contacts with Linc
and Venture Capital Report. It believes that this combination of a local
exposure with links into a national network is a key to its success.
Upcott Gill, who had previous experience of investor networks from working
for Cheshire County Council, says a big factor in Techinvest's success is
the work it puts into advising the entrepreneurs on how to present their
proposals and into training sessions for investors on subjects such as
structuring deals and forming syndicates.
Equally important is the work which the angel networks put into selecting
the good propositions for investors and filtering out the 'duds'. Venture
Capital Report, which was founded in 1978 and which now has just over 450
subscribers, provides brief but very thorough descriptions of the business
proposals that it features.
Colin Mason, who has carried out a review of the five pilots, says the more
successful ones share three characteristics. They are based in areas with a
strong regional identity, a reasonable number of wealthy residents and an
entrepreneurial culture; they are run by people with a missionary zeal; and
they have sufficient funding.
'They must have the resources to carry out a continuous promotion campaign
because there will be a constant turnover of business propositions and, to a
lesser extent, investors,' says Mason. Upcott Gill calculates that
Techinvest would need an annual budget of Pounds 100,000-Pounds 150,000 to
perform effectively. 'These schemes need substantial long-term funding,' she
says. 'If they were commercially viable, accountants would be doing it.'
Some accountants do maintain lists of wealthy private clients who might be
prepared to back a business. Blackstone Franks, a London firm, has about 600
clients on its 'private investors list' with no less than Pounds 250m
available to invest. 'That is more than many venture capital companies,'
comments Richard Coon, the partner in charge.
But Coon estimates that few deals have been done in the two years that the
firm has kept this list. 'It is not our primary activity and matching
investors with business proposals is horrendously difficult.'
The growing realisation of the potential of angels - Mason estimates they
may have between Pounds 2bn and Pounds 4bn available for investment
(compared with the Pounds 1.4bn invested by the venture capital industry
last year) - has prompted others to take an interest.
In the UK, National Westminster Bank is researching the possibility of
creating a nationwide register of business angels. Meanwhile, a former
banker, Nigel Lacy, has launched the Capital Exchange, a network of advisers
who will carry out a basic vetting of proposals for publication in a
bi-monthly magazine, the Capital Exchange Gazette.
But the difficulties that relative amateurs encounter in making investments
should not be underestimated. One hopeful angel who began backing small
companies after a lifetime spent making stock market investments for a large
City institution found it a less than rewarding experience.
'I invested in five or six companies but my timing was wrong and virtually
every one had to be written down,' he says. 'It became too demanding and I
wanted more leisure time. This is something that the country needs but it is
a great deal more difficult than it sounds.'
*Linc, 071 236 3000. VCR, 0491 579999. Techinvest, 0606 737009. Capital
Exchange, 0432 342484.
</TEXT>
<XX>
