<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Technology: Research stuck in the pork barrel - Technically
Speaking
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH SHAPLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN 16th century England, farmers identified their pigs by their earmarks.
Likewise, US federally funded research has for some years had small portions
of funds 'earmarked' by powerful members of Congress to go directly to
institutions in their districts.
Now, a critical report by George E. Brown, democratic chairman of the House
committee on science, space and technology, has revealed that the amounts of
earmarked funds have leapt upwards to the point that they 'eat into the base
programmes' that the nation relies on 'to fund our scientific enterprise'.
Brown has been a lonely critic of the practice, which his fellow members
prefer not to talk about. Now, he reveals that in the fiscal year 1992,
Dollars 708m (Pounds 460m) of the Dollars 72bn spent on research was
earmarked, almost double the amount the year before. In 1980 only seven
awards were earmarked, totalling Dollars 10m.
Since then, while some universities decry earmarking, a growing number of
institutions have accepted it or even pay high-priced lobbyists to win large
dollops of federal money without the hassle of raising matching funds or
peer review.
Brown reveals that Wheeling Jesuit College in West Virginia, with only 1,000
full-time students, got Dollars 21m in 1992, and notes that Senator Robert
C. Byrd, chairman of the senate appropriations committee, is from West
Virginia.
Barons in Congress can legally require even the best-run agencies to award
research funds to institutions which all parties know are unlikely to pass
merit review.
The universities receiving the most pork since 1980 have been Iowa State
(Dollars 91.5m), University of Alaska (Dollars 91.2m) and Oregon Health
Sciences University (Dollars 84.9m).
Federal research managers may work closely with the university to draw up a
passable use for the funds. This may lessen waste but also takes up time the
managers need to devote to more important agency work. Or they simply write
a cheque. They dare not refuse because 'to do so would incur the wrath of
the appropriations committees, and that is not a price any executive
department is fully willing to pay', Brown concludes. 'No effective checks
on this power currently exist.' Except possibly embarrassment, a tactic
Brown has adopted by publishing his report.
It hits hard at hospital facilities to be built at 10 universities which
were earmarked in energy research appropriations over four years. As a
consequence, funding for the superconducting supercollider, the crown jewel
of US high-energy physics, was cut.
The amount diverted to medical facilities was Dollars 171.8m - or 60 per
cent of the Dollars 282m withheld from the supercollider. This underfunding
in turn caused schedule slips 'that, regrettably, contributed to the erosion
of support' for the supercollider in the House.
The House appropriations chairman, William H. Natcher, now favours limiting
the practice of earmarking and has banned earmarks for the first time in the
House version of the National Institutes of Health's budget.
President Bill Clinton's science adviser, Jack Gibbons, is on record as
being opposed to earmarks. With Brown's open criticism and Gibbons' stance,
the betting has been that earmarks would be reduced in 1993.
Until this summer, that is, when Clinton's five-year tax and debt-reduction
plan seemed on the verge of defeat and his presidency became hostage to the
demands of individual congressmen. Exactly what was promised to key members
in return for their votes is not known. But Bill Sarpalius of Texas
reportedly left a meeting with energy secretary Hazel O'Leary optimistic
that a nuclear weapons lab in Amarillo, Texas, might expand - and deciding
to vote as the president wished.
Only when Congress finishes with the budget and its massive reports are
published, will we know if 'pork' remains rampant, or if Brown is succeeding
in turning off this source of gold for non-competitive universities.
</TEXT>
<XX>
