<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Labour at Brighton: Pragmatism taxes even the loyal masses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Gordon Brown's comments earlier this week that he intended to reverse the
'unacceptable' gap between rich and poor were met with disbelief by
journalists and commentators. His words suggested he had rejected the
widely-accepted wisdom that the prospect of higher taxes was what lost
Labour the last election.
A large number of delegates at this week's conference would share that view.
It was to them, said Mr Brown's defenders, that he was directing his
comments.
Mr Brown may well distance himself from his comments once conference is
over, but a scan of grass roots opinion reveals why, at least for this week,
he felt the need to tread carefully.
A delegate from Blaby summed up the feeling of many Labour activists at a
meeting of the shadow treasury team yesterday: 'We have got the impression
from Gordon Brown that the very rich in this country will be allowed to keep
all those ill-gotten gains of the past decade.'
Like other delegates, she urged Labour to stick to a policy of raising the
income taxes of the better-off in Britain.
Agreeing on higher taxes for the rich is one thing, but agreeing on who is
rich is another.
One woman from the south-west suggested salaries of over Pounds 100,000
would be a good starting point for higher taxation. A delegate from
Maidstone suggested Pounds 50,000 while a visitor from Scotland said Pounds
36,000 - the point at which Mr Smith's proposals would have started to bite
 -was considered wealthy in Scotland.
Among activists, Labour's now abandoned tax-raising proposals do not feature
highly as a reason for why Labour lost the 1992 election.
'I would campaign tomorrow for higher taxes,' said the Maidstone delegate.
'People would accept them if they knew they were going to pay for better
services.'
'It wasn't the tax. We just didn't get the message across in the South
East,' said another Scottish visitor. 'John Smith's tax proposals didn't
lose us the election in Scotland.'
The mood was reflected in yesterday's economic debate. As one delegate
commented: 'People are not stupid. They know the money has to be found.'
Another pointed out that progressive taxation meant only one thing - income
tax.
If delegates had their way, Labour would march into the next election with
last year's tax proposals intact and more. But their thinking is strongly
out of line with a pragmatic Labour Treasury team.
</TEXT>
<XX>
