<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Labour at Brighton: Support for scrapping of opt-out schools
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONFERENCE yesterday supported a motion to end school opt-outs and the
creation of grant-maintained schools.
It also called for nursery education to be available by right to all
children from the age of four and for financial support for all students
over 16 in full or part-time education.
Mr Graham Lane of the Socialist Education Association, who proposed the
motion, accused the government of 'bribery and corruption' in its eff-orts
to encourage schools to opt out.
Delegates expressed their contempt for the government's education reforms
during a debate in which Ms Ann Taylor, shadow education secretary, said
Labour offered a vision of a learning society where education was not geared
to a privileged minority, 'but where all individuals are empowered to make
real decisions about their own lives'.
Ms Taylor said that the party rejected the 'simplistic, meaningless and
dangerous league tables' which were designed with the purpose of setting
schools against each other.
She also urged reform to post-16 education. 'Conservatives describe A-levels
as a gold standard,' she said. 'Well, it's pretty tarnished gold and it's
just not good enough for today's children, forcing them to make invidious,
narrow and out-of-date choices.'
Mrs Glenys Kinnock, prospective European parliamentary candidate for South
East Wales and wife of the former Labour leader, condemned government plans
for a 'mum's army' of teachers for the youngest primary school children,
dismissing the idea as 'crackpot'.
'Teachers are not insisting on an all-graduate profession because of vested
interests,' she said. 'It is children's interests that they are seeking to
defend.'
Later in the debate Mr Nicholas Russell of the Morecambe and Lunesdale
constituency party complained about government plans to reform student
unions which he said would limit the activities the unions could be involved
in.
</TEXT>
