<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Labour at Brighton: Conference Notebook - No sign of the big
idea
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEVER under-estimate the legacy of the Lady. Thatcherism died in the
Conservative party three years ago with her departure from Downing Street.
Mr John Major is floundering still in the consequent ideological vacuum.
Now the electorate appears also to be disavowing the triumphant
individualism of the 1980s. Society and community have returned to the
lexicon of political respectability. After an economic recession which
ravaged the southern middle-classes, so too has the notion that governments
might have the ambition at least of full employment.
But the Labour party is as uncertain as the Tories how to fill the
philosophical gap. The message from its Brighton conference yesterday was a
curious mix of confidence, complacency and confusion.
On one side the so-called modernisers fretted over the ground they had lost
since the cold shower of last year's fourth election defeat had been
replaced by the warmer climate of the government's disarray. Mr Tony Blair
is in belligerent mood these days.
On what used to be called the soft left, Mr David Blunkett and Mrs Ann
Taylor relied on the well-tried tactic of attacking the Tories over health
and education while offering few clues as to their alternative strategies.
Leaving aside for a day or two the dispute over one-member-one-vote, Mr John
Edmonds of the GMB went on the offensive over the party's economic strategy.
In a thinly veiled attack on Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, he
called for the party to break with the Tories' economic agenda. What was
wrong with spending and borrowing?
With large numbers of the delegates in Brighton convinced once again that
victory at the next election is only a matter of time, it is a seductive
strategy. It is being presented daily and with some eloquence by Mr Bryan
Gould, now the most powerful voice of dissent on the Labour backbenches.
For his part, Mr John Smith sat rather uneasily on the platform, convinced
that Labour cannot abort the process of change but reluctant to abandon the
traditionalist reflexes which sustained Labour in Scotland even through the
wilderness years of the 1980s.
His speech later today will combine an angry denunciation of the 'chaos' of
Mr Major's government with an assertion that wealth creation, full
employment and better public services are all part of the same picture. In
the jargon of the spin-doctors, it will be a put-Britain-back-to-work
speech.
But the pivotal figure for the moment remains Mr Brown. He has spent the
past year clearing the decks of tax and spending pledges made by Labour at
the last election. It has not made him very popular with Mr Edmonds et al,
and his friends say he has been feeling the heat.
So Mr Brown has now adopted a more populist tack. Despite all those prawn
cocktail lunches, he devoted a significant chunk of his speech to an attack
on City boardroom. Financiers, it seems, are to Labour conferences what
social security cheats are to Tory ones.
There was a more important message, though. For all his caution the shadow
chancellor has decided that Labour's economic strategy must be seen to be
expansionist.
He will not suggest tax increases beyond the closing of the lengthening list
of executive loopholes he publishes every other day (unless, that is, Mr
Kenneth Clarke gets there first). But the unifying goal is to be full
employment.
It is an approach designed to solve two problems. It should take some of the
internal pressure off Mr Brown, and it will give Labour a clear basis from
which to attack the government in the approach to the November Budget.
Tactically, it makes sense. The economy remains the government's weakest
point. Nothing could be more potent than unemployment for their
university-educated sons and daughters in shifting the allegiances of the
aspirant classes.
But it does not fill the vacuum. 'Found the big idea yet?' asked one member
of the shadow cabinet yesterday. 'Don't bother. There isn't one.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
