<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Labour at Brighton: Blunkett pledges to end 'two-tier'
health service
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FAIR taxation and not private insurance and charges should ensure that
patients receive adequate treatment under the national health service, Mr
David Blunkett, the shadow health secretary, told delegates.
He announced that later in the autumn a consultation paper would contain
proposals for ending the 'two-tier service' that had resulted from the
government's policy of allowing some family doctors to assume responsibility
for their own budgets.
Mr Blunkett said it would also contain proposals for ending the trust status
which had removed many hospitals from the control of local health
authorities.
He maintained that the internal market introduced by the government had
'failed abysmally', with hospital waiting lists exceeding one million for
the first time.
Mr Blunkett said the NHS was cracking at the seams and only the dedication
of the staff was holding it together.
To applause, he protested: 'The internal market is crucifying the NHS before
our eyes.' Labour's aim would be to put patients at the top of the agenda.
Mr Blunkett said: 'We all pay our taxes and should be entitled to the best
the NHS can give us'. He attacked the government's pay freeze for
public-sector workers, and claimed that the extension of VAT to domestic
fuel would cause illness.
Urging the party to rally to the 'beacon of hope and confidence for the
future' lit by Labour leader Mr John Smith, he declared: 'It's the Tories
that are the party of tax and cut, borrow and squander, sell-off and
sell-short.
'It's we that want decent, well-managed, well-afforded public services.'
He accepted a composite motion urging the next Labour government to restore
the NHS as a service 'free at the point of use' for all citizens.
The motion also pressed for the introduction of a levy on private hospitals
geared to the number of former NHS personnel they employ.
</TEXT>
