<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Labour at Brighton: Social justice body to probe tax and
pension benefits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN INVESTIGATION into integrating the tax and benefit system for pensioners
is to be carried out by Labour's social justice commission, Mr Gordon Brown,
the shadow chancellor, said yesterday.
Mr Brown said that he and Mr Donald Dewar, the social security spokesman,
wanted to see the end of means-testing pensioners to see if they were
eligible for state benefits.
But there was a setback for the leadership when conference defied the
national executive committee and supported a motion calling for equalisation
of the pension age at 60 - by almost 60 per cent of the vote to just over 30
per cent.
Labour's policy is to support a flexible decade of retirement, and the
government is expected to announce shortly plans to equalise the state
pensions age at 65. Labour is certain to be pressed to explain how it would
pay for the earlier pension age for men.
At a fringe meeting later, Mr Dewar urged the refocusing of the social
security system in order to tackle the ways in which it encouraged
dependency.
He said that Labour could not simply defend the welfare system of the late
1970s and argue that it just required better funding.
Instead, it needed to address issues such as the high marginal rate of
withdrawals from a combination of tax and benefits, which acted as a
disincentive to people on income support to take up work.
He added, however, that in his view the social security system was
sustainable in the short-term, and attacked right-wing ministers for using
the immediate problem of government borrowing as cover for bringing in major
changes to the welfare state.
</TEXT>
