<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Lloyd's chief in threat to quit over reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR PETER MIDDLETON, chief executive of Lloyd's of London, yesterday
threatened to resign if his plans for the introduction of corporate capital
into the insurance market were not approved.
He said that he and Mr David Rowland, the chairman, would quit unless Names
 -the individuals whose assets underwrite the market - supported them at an
extraordinary general meeting called for October 20.
The warning came at a regional meeting in London yesterday afternoon of the
Association of Lloyd's Names, the biggest Names group, and was confirmed
last night by officials.
'They (Middleton and Rowland) are there to see the business plan through and
if it fails they are off,' a spokesman for Lloyd's said.
Mr Middleton's threat represents an escalation of the intensifying campaign
by Lloyd's to ensure that its sweeping proposals announced in a new business
plan in April are implemented.
The centrepiece is the introduction for the first time of money pledged by
corporate investors, who would not be subject to the unlimited liability
requirements imposed on Names.
Mr Rowland wrote to all Names last week urging them to support Lloyd's
proposals. 'I believe that access to new capital is necessary to ensure that
we can continue to trade as a significant force in the international market
place,' he said.
Lloyd's announced the extraordinary general meeting last month in an effort
to head off any action by dissident loss-making Names that could delay the
entry of the new 'incorporated Names'.
It did so in spite of a previous egm held in July, which overwhelmingly
endorsed the idea of corporate capital and defeated motions of no confidence
proposed by dissident Names.
All 32,000 Names on the market will be entitled to vote at the meeting,
including many who have become insolvent following recent heavy underwriting
losses.
Mr Brian Garraway, who was deputy chairman of the Council of Lloyd's and
first chairman of its regulatory board since the start of this year, has
died.
</TEXT>
