<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / College leavers find work prospects still gloomy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONLY a third of students funded by Lancashire County Council who left
university or college last year have found jobs related to the subjects they
studied, and one in eight were still unemployed after nearly a year.
Most who found jobs went into large public-sector organisations such as
schools, colleges, the health service, the Civil Service and councils.
Few employers were small or medium-sized companies, a survey of people who
received student grants from Lancashire and sat final examinations in 1991
and 1992 has found. The students went to universities or colleges throughout
Britain.
Unemployment was 7.5 per cent among those who qualified in 1991.
Holders of Higher National Diplomas were almost twice as likely to be
unemployed as those with bachelor degrees. A quarter of final-year students
in 1992 went back to full-time study, many to enhance qualifications and
improve job prospects after failing to find work. Upgrading HNDs to bachelor
degrees was common.
The survey by East Lancashire Training and Enterprise Council analysed
responses from 4,118 people - 39 per cent of those who received funding for
their higher education from the county council.
Those who graduated in medicine, science, law and business administration
found work fastest. Unemployment was highest among those who took art and
design, mass communications, construction or the humanities. Students with
first-class honours were four times less likely to be unemployed than those
with thirds. Job chances were poorest for mature students and those from
ethnic minorities.
Personal and family contacts were important for finding work, the survey
indicated, so that those from more affluent districts tended to do better
because of parental networks.
</TEXT>
