FT  28 SEP 93 / Regeneration scheme opens in Bristol
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A Pounds 1.5m project funded by the public and private sectors was launched
yesterday by Sir George Young, environment minister, to provide training and
jobs in a deprived part of Bristol.
Sir George described the project as one of the most ambitious of its kind
and said it would help restore confidence in Hartcliffe, south Bristol - an
area of high unemployment and the scene of riots last year.
The Gatehouse project, which will provide a centre with enterprise
workshops, training facilities, meeting rooms and a creche, was part of the
city's failed bid for the government's City Challenge scheme.
The Department of the Environment is providing an urban partnership grant of
Pounds 500,000. The city council is donating Pounds 500,000 and providing
the site for a peppercorn rent. The balance is being raised from more than
20 companies. British Telecommunications yesterday donated Pounds 100,000.
The Gatehouse project is being led by Hartcliffe and Withywood Ventures, an
enterprise and community development agency.
