<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Howard to discuss firefighter pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COUNCIL LEADERS will tell Mr Michael Howard, home secretary today, that the
government must take the blame if there is a firefighters' strike. They are
due to meet this morning for talks on the future of the 15-year-old
firefighters pay formula.
'If the government does not agree to honour the formula - which in the past
it has supported - then we will potentially be faced with a serious dispute
entirely of the government's making,' warned Mr Jeremy Beecham, chairman of
the Association of Metropolitan Authorities, and Ms Josie Farrington,
chairwoman of the Association of County Councils, in a joint statement
yesterday. They added that a dispute would result in costs for the provision
of emergency cover. 'We will ask the home secretary who he intends should
pay for this in the event of industrial action,' they said.
'Instead of the Home Office advising fire authorities - possibly at their
own expense - to draw up plans for strike action, the government should be
working with the employers to find a way of averting a dispute. We hope
today's talks will achieve this.'
The employers say the provision of a back-up service for one day, with Green
Goddesses and troops to deal with emergencies, would cost more than meeting
the firefighters' pay formula in full. 'The cost of a strike would outweigh
any benefits achieved,' said Mr Tony Ritchie, chairman of the Metropolitan
Authorities fire committee.
If today's meeting at the Home Office fails to provide employers with room
for financial manoeuvre, there is the strong possibility of a series of
one-day strikes, starting in the second week of November.
The Fire Brigades Union is due to ballot 50,000 firefighters next Monday,
asking for their support for one-day strikes. The result will be known on
November 1.
The union's leaders are due to meet the employers on Friday, when they hope
agreement on this year's pay formula can be reached, as well as a commitment
for next year.
The size of the increase the firefighters could expect in November under the
formula will be known on Thursday when the government's earnings survey for
1993 is published. This provides the basis for the firefighters' award as
their pay is linked to the upper quartile of full-time male manual earnings.
The employers have already intimated they will meet this year's formula in
full.
</TEXT>
