<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Slide in business failures boosts upturn hopes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RECOVERY hopes have been buoyed by the biggest yearly drop in business
failures since the recession started, figures published today show.
Business collapses in England and Wales for the third quarter of this year
were a fifth down on the corresponding period last year. Dun &amp; Bradstreet,
the business information company collating the figures, said they marked a
'turning point' in the economic upturn.
The statistics underline how higher demand from consumers and industry in
the past six months has reduced the financial strain on many companies. The
fall in failures has been most noticeable for big companies, with many small
businesses still being forced under by difficulties in raising cash from
banks.
The latest figures make it unlikely that total collapses for the year will
exceed last year's 51,947, which marked a big jump from the 39,827 failures
in 1991.
Dun &amp; Bradstreet said that 10,320 businesses failed in the third quarter
after 12,867 in the same period in 1992 and 13,235 in the second quarter of
this year. The number of collapses in the third quarter was the lowest for
any quarter in two years.
In the first nine months, 36,203 enterprises collapsed, a fall of 6 per cent
on the 38,550 failures between January and September last year.
Over the same period, liquidations of large registered companies dropped 13
per cent to 14,674 from 16,897. However, small-business bankruptcies dropped
to 21,529 from 21,653, a fall of just 0.6 per cent.
Mr Philip Mellor, Dun &amp; Bradstreet marketing manager, warned that
small-business failures have not necessarily peaked because of their 'lack
of financial resource to provide the working capital for growth'.
Larger companies generally have relatively solid forms of financial support
such as share capital, while smaller groups often rely on bank loans and
overdrafts.
The biggest drop in business failures over the first nine months was in
Wales, which showed a 20 per cent fall on the same period last year. The
next biggest decline was in London, with 12 per cent, while the east
Midlands and the eastern region saw decreases of 8 per cent and 7 per cent.
Third-quarter figures for Scotland were distorted by changes in Scottish
bankruptcy laws which meant that third-quarter bankruptcies totalled only
489 after 2,095 in the same quarter last year.
This distortion means total failures in the third quarter in Scotland are
recorded as just 601 compared with 2,956 in the equivalent period last year
and 3,770 between April and June this year.
In the first nine months failures in south-east England excluding London
declined 4 per cent on the same period last year. The West Midlands and
north-west England saw an equivalent decline in failures, while collapses in
north-east England fell 2 per cent.
Counting England, Wales and Scotland, total business failures for the first
nine months of the year came to 43,369 after 46,545 in the same period last
year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
