<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / FT Financial Reporting Conference: Delay in audit reform
sought
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LEADING British companies yesterday called for delays to proposed auditing
standards reforms until new accounting standards have been developed
further.
Mr Nigel Stapleton, chief finance officer of Reed Elsevier and chairman of
the technical committee of the Hundred Group of leading finance directors,
called for greater focus in financial reporting.
Speaking at the FT Financial Reporting Conference in London yesterday, he
said there were too many initiatives with too little co-ordination under
way.
He called for standards-setters to focus on 'priority issues' and avoid
topics outside the area of improved financial reporting.
'There is a risk of reform overload,' he said.
He also stressed the need for more authoritative guidance on implementing
the Cadbury code on corporate governance, and warned that the guidelines on
internal controls being drafted were too broad.
Mr James Carty, technical partner at accountants Robson Rhodes, criticised
the Accounting Standards Board for acting too slowly, generating standards
which were too confusing and poorly written, and for failing to distinguish
the need for different standards for smaller companies.
Mr Mike Townsend, finance director of Rolls-Royce, said FRS 3, the new
profit-and-loss account standard, 'is not helpful in understanding the real
dynamics and trading position and trends' of his company.
He said there was little consistency in the way in which City analysts
interpreted Rolls-Royce's 1992 results, which were prepared according to the
new standard.
He cited the earnings per share and p/e ratios quoted by five leading City
investment houses following the results, which produced widely varying
figures.
The numbers ranged from a loss per share of 20.9p from Paribas to earnings
of 6.6p from Henderson Crosthwaite. He said that if analysts provided such
varied interpretations, private investors would be even more confused by the
new standard.
Mr Jim McCaughan, managing director of UBS International Investment in
London, defended City analysts. He said much comment related to the
activities of brokers' research departments.
He drew a distinction between these readers of accounts - often accused of
short-termism - and investment managers, whose research is longer-term and
given no publicity.
He said he sympathised with companies' attempts to put 'a positive spin on
events' but said auditors needed to be stronger to ensure this spin did not
go beyond the requirement for accounts to show 'a true and fair view'.
Mr Richard Goeltz, director and group chief financial officer at National
Westminster Bank, said the ASB's proposed clampdown on capital instruments
and off-balance-sheet finance would reduce demand from financial advisers to
produce treatments designed with 'cosmetic enhancement' as their main aim.
But he said there was an 'increasingly aggressive' market among advisers to
devise 'tailored financial instruments to resolve real problems'.
</TEXT>
