<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Akbar was 'chief engineer' on BCCI ship of fraud: John Mason
profiles a central figure in the bank's misuse of Pounds 1.3bn depositor
funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR SAYED ALI AKBAR, the former head of Bank of Credit amd Commerce
International's treasury division, was a central figure in the epic
worldwide fraud perpetrated by the bank, the Old Bailey was told yesterday.
Although he reported directly to Mr Agha Hasan Abedi, the BCCI founder and
chairman, and Mr Swaleh Naqvi, its chief executive, Mr Akbar was the 'chief
engineer' of the bank's dishonest financial manoeuvring which resulted in
the misuse of Pounds 1.3bn of depositors' funds, the court heard.
Mr Timothy Langdale QC presented the case brought by the Serious Fraud
Office after Mr Akbar had pleaded guilty to 16 sample charges of false
accounting involving Dollars 745.8m and an additional Pounds 13.6m in the
early 1980s.
Mr Akbar, who has spent more than two years in French and British jails
since his arrest, will be sentenced today.
During the hearing, the court heard that while BCCI set out to hoodwink both
its regulators and auditors, the Bank of England did not apply its standard
test of an individual's fitness to hold their position to Mr Akbar - the
Bank's supervision division considering his post as head of treasury
insufficiently senior to justify such an assessment. It also learnt that Mr
Swaleh Naqvi, now awaiting trial in Abu Dhabi, had made 'sweeping
confessions' about his role in the bank's affairs.
Although the bank grew quickly since its creation in 1972, its weak balance
sheet and poorly performing loans meant that it was effectively insolvent by
1983 and possibly earlier, Mr Langdale said. To survive, it painted an
entirely false picture of its profitability by inflating profits, making
liabilities look like loans, and artificially creating funds.
Top bank officials behaved less like financiers and 'more like a team of
financial jugglers trying to keep an increasing number of balls in the air
in a desperate effort to prevent their ruinous mismanagement being exposed
to the world'. The frauds were sophisticated and the money movements
designed to avoid detection. Carried out in a number of countries, the
frauds were very difficult to detect. The bank's auditors were never given
all relevant information at the same time.
One example of the fraud carried out by Mr Akbar concerned his handling of
funds deposited by the Saudi Sheikh Abdul Khalil. With no authority and
without the Sheikh's knowledge, Mr Akbar created loans against his account.
Mr Akbar then used much of the money to set up Capcom, a commodity dealer
used in BCCI's dealing activities.
About Dollars 60m had been diverted from BCCI to set up the dealing company,
which still exists and deals in foreign exchange, Mr Langdale said.
After leaving BCCI in 1986, Mr Akbar met the Sheikh and told him how his
money had been misused to help conceal the bank's true financial position.
He advised Sheikh Khalil to withdraw his money from the bank, Mr Langdale
said.
Mr Akbar told the Sheikh BCCI's management would kill him if they learnt he
had passed on this information.
After his departure from BCCI, Mr Akbar worked exclusively for Capcom until
his arrest in 1988 for laundering the proceeds of drug trafficking. He was
later sentenced to 18 months in prison. After his release in 1991, Mr Akbar
fled to France. It was only in April 1993 that the SFO was able to extradite
him to the UK.
The cost of the SFO's investigation and preparation of Mr Akbar's case was
Pounds 3,647,599, Mr Langdale said.
</TEXT>
