<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / West to urge greater verification: Biological weapons
control
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WESTERN nations are to press for a strengthening of the international treaty
banning use, production and stockpiling of biological weapons, following the
conclusion of an expert group that measures to check compliance would be
both feasible and useful.
Government experts from 41 countries last week completed a report detailing
21 types of verification procedure, including on-site inspections, which
they say could help guard against cheating. The report now goes to the 134
signatory states to the 1972 Biological and Toxin Weapons Convention.
European officials said yesterday they hoped to garner support from the
required majority of treaty members to call a special conference within the
next two years which would discuss ways of tightening up the convention.
Some developing countries, notably China, India and Iran, are opposed to
such moves which they fear could be intrusive and compromise military
security.
China and Iran are among five nations - the others being Russia, Syria and
Iraq - thought by the US to possess biological weapons. Other countries
which may have such weapons are Egypt, Taiwan and Libya.
Unlike the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty and the Chemical Weapons
Convention, the biological weapons convention contains no policing or
verification measures. This is partly because verification of toxic arms
production was thought to pose insuperable difficulties.
Biological weapons are much harder to detect than nuclear or chemical arms;
they can be easily produced and stored in tiny quantities and the agents and
equipment often have peaceful as well as belligerent uses.
In its report the expert group admits that even in combination there are no
foolproof ways of detecting whether a country has or is trying to acquire
biological weapons.
</TEXT>
