<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Pakistan raises drug penalties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FARHAN BOKHARI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ISLAMABAD
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PAKISTAN last night announced a new law introducing the death penalty as the
maximum punishment for drug traffickers. The minimum punishment was also
raised from two years to life imprisonment.
The move came ahead of next Wednesday's national elections. At least eight
tribal elders from the rugged Northern Frontier region have been barred from
the contest amid allegations of their involvement in production and
trafficking of heroin. Islamabad has also stepped up an initiative to
extradite at least 16 drug barons wanted in the US on drug-related charges.
A government announcement after a cabinet meeting in Islamabad, chaired by
Mr Moeen Qureshi, the prime minister, said: 'These enhanced punishments
provide the much needed legal framework to effectively deal with the
narcotics traffickers and their associates who have proliferated drugs in
Pakistan and have seriously eroded Pakistan's prestige abroad.'
The campaign against drug barons is a response to concerns from the US,
Canada and Europe that Pakistan has become an important conduit for heroin
trafficking.
Most heroin leaving Pakistan is produced in the semi-autonomous Northern
Frontier tribal belt, from opium grown in nearby Afghanistan.
