FT  28 SEP 93 / Japanese provincial governor held: Bribery alleged in
construction contracts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPANESE prosecutors last night arrested another leading provincial
politician as their investigation into a network of alleged bribery by
construction companies gathered momentum.
Mr Shuntaro Honma, 53, governor of Miyagi prefecture, north of Tokyo, was
arrested for allegedly receiving Y20m (Pounds 125,000), while prosecutors
also took into custody an official of the Liberal Democratic party and two
executives of Taisei, a large contractor based in Tokyo.
The move by prosecutors followed the arrest last week of Mr Teruzo Yoshino,
patriarch of Japan's construction industry and chairman of Shimizu, the
largest contractor, for allegedly bribing a different provincial governor.
Prosecutors are expected to target national politicians in the next few
weeks, and the investigation could be embarrassing for members and former
members of the LDP, which has traditionally had close ties to the
construction industry.
In the Miyagi case, Mr Honma, a former journalist, is alleged to have
received money from the two Taisei officials in January this year in
connection with contracts to build a medical complex and a sports stadium in
the prefecture.
In the past three months, 22 provincial government officials and
construction company executives have been arrested, providing evidence for
US trade negotiators, who are demanding that the Japanese government reform
bidding procedures for public works con-tracts.
At present, only designated companies are allowed to bid, but it is often
unclear why certain companies have been designated and others excluded from
a contract. The US wants open bidding for all public works projects.
