<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / World Trade News: US and EC still split on farm trade -
Negotiators are eager to push Uruguay Round to the fore
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE and FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE TWO top trade officials of the EC and US yesterday made substantive
progress in bilateral talks on the Uruguay Round, but continued to disagree
on the farm trade question.
At a packed press conference in Washington, Sir Leon Brittan and Mr Mickey
Kantor seemed determined to push the Round forward and their dispute over
farm trade to the side. There were only 79 days until December 15, the Gatt
deadline, they said, and urged the world to get back to business in Geneva
to put offers on the table.
'There simply is no time to waste,' said Sir Leon.
They then announced that bilateral talks would continue this week on steel,
aircraft, aluminium and textiles, and that they would meet again in Brussels
on October 13.
Under orders from the EC, Sir Leon, the EC commissioner in charge of trade,
had dutifully and 'forcefully' presented suggestions for 'interpretations,
clarifications, amplifications or additions' to last year's US-EC Blair
House accord on farm trade.
'I responded with equal force that we would not reopen or renegotiate Blair
House,' said Mr Kantor, the US trade representative.
Sir Leon said Mr Kantor needed time to consider his suggestions. Mr Kantor
said the ball was not in his court.
As one official close to the negotiations noted, although Mr Kantor is
showing no flexibility he has a right to believe that a deal signed is a
deal done.
Mr Kantor is under pressure from farm groups and their supporters in
Congress, where he has vowed to be tougher than his predecessors, who often
swapped trade concessions for the sale of cold war solidarity. With the
North American Free Trade Agreement in trouble in Congress it is no time to
be seen buckling under EC pressure.
The pressure could increase later this week, however. Mr Alain Juppe, the
French foreign minister, announced yesterday he was to meet Mr Kantor in
Washington on Friday.
Meanwhile, another key player in Washington yesterday, Mr Peter Sutherland,
director-general of Gatt, pointed out that the farm trade debate was 'not
merely across the Atlantic'. Many Latin American countries have yet to
accept the Blair House deal.
He has called a meeting of top negotiators in the Uruguay Round for next
Thursday. The 116-nation trade negotiations committee is intended to keep up
the pressure on negotiators to come forward with better offers in bilateral
talks, under way in Geneva, on improving market access for imported goods
and services.
These negotiations will have to be largely completed within the next four to
six weeks to meet the Round's December deadline.
Negotiations on services are said to be proceeding well and are putting the
finishing touches to the draft general agreement on trade in services, which
provides a framework of rules for the continued liberalisation of services
trade. The revised draft is due to be presented to negotiators on Friday.
But negotiations on goods remain stuck in areas such as agricultural
products and textiles, where leading traders have allegedly failed to make
adequate offers.
Countries are also hoping to complete talks on revised codes of practice for
government procurement and civil aircraft by mid-December, to coincide with
the Round's deadline.
</TEXT>
