<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / World Trade News: Toyota engine plant for Canada
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS and BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO, TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TOYOTA, Japan's largest carmaker, is to build a Y2.5bn (Pounds 15.7m) engine
plant in Canada next spring, to raise the local content of cars assembled
there, write William Dawkins in Tokyo and Bernard Simon in Toronto.
Under the North American Free Trade Agreement, due to take effect next year,
duties will be charged on cars assembled from imported components. The aim
of the new plant was to avoid such duties, company officials said.
Toyota's Canadian subsidiary currently imports 1.6 and 1.8 litre engines
from Japan for use in Corolla models made at its assembly line near
Cambridge, in south-west Ontario. The new engine factory will be close to
the car plant.
The move also forms part of Toyota's strategy of increasing production
outside Japan to reduce the damage to price competitiveness inflicted by the
yen's long-term rise. Foreign output, which was 5.8 per cent of the total in
1988, rose to 16.3 per cent last year and is estimated to hit 19 per cent
this year.
Toyota has even started to import foreign-made parts for use in its
Japanese-manufactured cars. Engines and engine components were imported from
the US last year, followed by crankshafts and cylinder blocks from Britain
this month.
The Canadian plant, due to open in late 1995, will make 80,000 engines a
year, which almost matches the current production of cars.
</TEXT>
