<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / World Trade News: Joint appeal for global trade deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IN AN attempt to put pressure on trade negotiators, the heads of the
International Monetary Fund, World Bank and Gatt yesterday urged immediate
action to conclude the Uruguay Round.
Appearing together, Mr Michel Camdessus, Mr Lewis Preston and Mr Peter
Sutherland warned that failure to conclude the Round would unleash a cycle
of greater protectionism and loss of confidence which would destroy jobs and
put at risk the new democracies of eastern Europe and the former Soviet
Union.
However, while full of dire warnings, the unprecedented joint statement from
the three did not single out any country or group as causing the current
impasse in the trade talks.
But Mr Sutherland said later that the main responsibility for bringing the
talks to a conclusion lay with the European Community and the US.
Despite a weekend of meetings in which the majority of finance ministers and
senior officials representing the IMF's 178 member countries supported free
trade, Mr Sutherland admitted yesterday morning that there was nothing
specific in the discussions to suggest countries were prepared to change
bargaining positions.
</TEXT>
