<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / World Trade News: A Japanese lure for US carmakers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TOYOTA, the Japanese carmaker, announced during the summer that it would be
working with Ford of the US, a competitor, on the development of cruise
control systems for use in their cars.
The trans-Pacific tie-up is a first for both companies. If US trade
negotiators have their way, there will be more cases of co-operation in
developing components between US and Japanese carmakers.
Car components, like the cruise control system Ford and Toyota will be
working on, are the target of a drive by the US to reduce its trade deficit
with Japan by pressing the Japanese to open specific sectors to more US-made
products.
Last week negotiators from the two countries met in Hawaii to discuss
bilateral trade in car and car parts for the first time under a new
framework for talks aimed at improving the balance of trade between the US
and Japan.
The US in particular is keen to see Japan buy more car parts from US
manufacturers since motor vehicle products last year made up 63 per cent of
the Dollars 50bn (Pounds 32.4bn) US trade deficit with Japan, according to
the US Department of Commerce.
After a surprise show of enthusiasm by the Japanese car industry, which last
year indicated its willingness to buy Y19bn (Pounds 116.5m) worth of US-made
car parts in fiscal 1994, there are moves among US officials to try to set a
similar target for 1995 and 1996.
Their efforts are being supported by a growing interest among US car parts
makers in the Japanese market. General Motors, for example, has set up a
technical centre on the outskirts of Tokyo.
Although it has lagged behind GM, Ford is also beginning to extend its
Japanese customer base beyond traditional business partners such as Mazda in
which it has a 25 per cent stake. It is building a development centre
outside Tokyo - its second in Japan - where it will develop components to
supply all Japanese car makers.
US companies are also becoming interested in Japan as a stepping stone into
the Asian market.
Their greater interest in the Japanese market has even encouraged US
components makers to adapt their business practices in Japan to the Japanese
way. GM, for example, has joined a number of suppliers' associations - a
group of preferred suppliers which work together to serve a customer and
which have been criticised by the US as a symbol of Japanese industry's
exclusive business practices.
In public, the Japanese vehicle industry welcomes such moves by its US
competitors. 'GM and Ford's presence in Japan has made a huge difference in
terms of communication,' says Mr Hisashi Kamoshida, a manager in Toyota's
purchasing planning division. But officials at Japanese carmakers are at
pains to stress it will take time to correct the imbalance in bilateral car
components trade.
For one thing there is a structural reason for that imbalance - the small
number of US cars sold in Japan means there is little demand for replacement
parts.
The absence of US car manufacturing in Japan also means demand for US
components is low whereas Japanese components are in demand from Japanese
carmakers which have set up facilities in the US.
It also takes at least four years to develop components for a new car. In
that respect, the Japanese say they are doing what they can to improve the
chances of US suppliers. 'As far as car parts go we have made efforts that
go beyond normal business transactions,' says Mr Hiroyoshi Ono, deputy
general manager of international public affairs at Toyota. They have held
seminars for US suppliers on 'design-ins' whereby they work with their
suppliers to develop parts for a specific car.
Although the US argues that the yen's appreciation has made US car
components more cost-competitive, Japanese car companies point out that cost
is not the sole determining factor. Quality, development ability, delivery
time and after-sales services are also crucial.
'We can't buy a component just because it's cheap,' says Mr Masatomo
Okahara, deputy general manager of Nissan's international purchasing
department.
US suppliers must show that they can keep up with the development pace of
Japanese car makers and quickly adapt their products to the many changes
made during the development of a car, something which Japanese suppliers do
well.
'We are willing to buy from US suppliers if they meet our needs,' says Mr
Ono. 'But there aren't that many US parts makers that are willing to take
the risk to sell to us.'
If GM and Ford's moves in Japan are an indication of a trend, however,
Japanese carmakers could find that reversed sooner than expected.
</TEXT>
