<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Former president heads Venezuela race
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOSEPH MANN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CARACAS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WITH just over two months to go to Venezuela's presidential elections, Mr
Rafael Caldera, 77, a former president with an ambivalent stance on the
country's continuing free-market reforms, has emerged as the leading
candidate.
Mr Caldera, who founded the Christian Democrat (Copei) party in the 1940s,
is one of Venezuela's most prominent politicians. An expert in labour
legislation and a member of Congress for much of his life, he served as
president from 1969 to 1974 and first ran for the presidency in 1947. For
the current presidential campaign, his sixth, Mr Caldera broke with his
party and is now running as an independent.
Much of his campaign has been based on attacking the free-market reforms
initiated in 1989 by ex-President Carlos Andres Perez, who was forced out of
office this year because of corruption charges. But Mr Caldera and his
advisers have tried recently to convince businessmen and investors that they
back private investment and will not return to excessive government
intervention in the economy.
His adversaries, though, accuse Mr Caldera and his team of saying one thing
in Venezuela and quite another to audiences overseas.
The ex-president, until now a strong anti-communist, has accepted a wide
range of support from more than a dozen smaller political parties, including
the Communist party of Venezuela and other leftist groups. Many of these
enthusiastic supporters of today used to consider Mr Caldera one of the
country's worst reactionaries.
Mr Caldera's strategy of breaking with his former party could possibly pay
dividends. More than ever before, Venezuelans are rejecting the two
political parties that have dominated national politics since the last
military dictator was ousted in 1958. Democratic Action (AD) has captured
the presidency in five out of the seven democratic elections held over the
last 35 years, and Copei has won twice.
Mr Caldera is one of four leading candidates from a pack of 17 contenders,
which includes a spiritualist, a sexologist, a former guerrilla and two
retired military officers.
Second in the polls and representing Copei is Mr Oswaldo Alvarez Paz, 50, a
longtime congressman and twice-elected governor of Zulia state. After
winning a stunning primary victory last April, Mr Alvarez declared he was in
favour of continuing free-market reforms, but added he would seek a wide
political consensus and more effective social welfare programmes.
Mr Andres Velasquez, 40, is a labour organiser who turned to national
politics and was elected twice as governor of Bolivar state. For the third
time, he is standing as presidential candidate for Causa Radical, a small
left-wing party. He has called for a 'peaceful revolution' in Venezuela, and
has proposed a broad mix of reforms.
Representing AD is Mr Claudio Fermin, 43, ex-mayor of Caracas and a
sociologist who has been a party activist since he was 15. Mr Fermin is also
convinced Venezuela must push ahead with economic and political reforms, but
seeks a greater share of social justice for those hardest hit by economic
change.
A national poll in August showed Mr Caldera had 24.8 per cent support: Mr
Alvarez (whose position eroded sharply in comparison with surveys in May and
June) 15.4 per cent; Mr Velasquez 13.4 per cent; and a humiliating 9.8 per
cent for Mr Fermin.
</TEXT>
