<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Vietnam clears path for IMF deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
VIETNAM yesterday jumped its final hurdle before being reinstated into the
international financial community when donor nations completed negotiations
for clearing up the country's Dollars 140m (Pounds 91m) arrears to the
International Monetary fund.
Nine governments led by France and Japan agreed to provide Dollars 55m in
grants to wipe out part of the arrears. A group of banks led by the Banque
Francaise du Commerce Exterieure and the Japanese Eximbank will then provide
a syndicated bridging loan of Dollars 85m.
Once Vietnam is back in good standing, the IMF board is expected to agree
next Wednesday to an Dollars 85m credit under its standby arrangements,
which will repay the bridge loan. The arrangements will also pave the way
for Vietnam to receive financing from the World Bank.
Mr Christian Noyer, director of the French Treasury and co-chairman of
yesterday's meetings in Washington, said Vietnam would also qualify for a
Dollars 20m drawing under the IMF's new Systemic Transformation Facility, a
special loan fund set up to help centrally planned economies such as Russia
make the shift to a market economy.
A similar meeting is planned for today which could arrange for Cambodia to
erase its Dollars 55m arrears to the IMF.
Donor countries are expected to meet in Paris on November 9-10 to work out
aid to help finance Vietnam's balance of payments shortfall over the next
two years.
Mr Noyer said the Paris Club of creditor nations would probably also meet in
November to discuss rescheduling Vietnam's official debt.
</TEXT>
