<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Hosokawa cautious on UN role
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS, UN Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN yesterday called for a strengthening of the United Nations Security
Council, and declared its firm support for the 'crucial role' of the UN in
maintaining peace.
Mr Morihiro Hosokawa, Japan's new prime minister, stopped short of claiming
a permanent seat for Japan in the Security Council, an issue that has
sharply divided his coalition government.
He said that there was a need to expand the Council membership beyond the
present 15 states and it was important to engage 'those countries having
both the will and the adequate capacity to contribute to world prosperity
and stability in that effort.' However, its effectiveness must be
maintained, he said in an address to the UN General Assembly.
Japanese personnel had already joined UN peacekeeping operations in
Cambodia, Mozambique and Angola, he said, and Tokyo intended to continue
this policy.
Echoing remarks by US President Bill Clinton, he called for 'serious reform
efforts' to enable the UN to respond fully to expectations of the
international community.
Mr Hosokawa took the opportunity of his first visit to the UN to voice
Japan's 'sense of remorse over its past actions' - an allusion to the second
world war.
He announced a Dollars 200m (Pounds 130m) aid package over two years for the
Palestinians, including food and medicine grants, and concessional loans for
infrastructure.
Later, Mr Clinton and Mr Hosokawa discussed US-Japanese relations, and in
particular the large US-Japanese trade deficit.
But if the US president had hoped for any precise Japanese commitment for
the reduction of this deficit, he was disappointed.
At a joint press conference afterwards, Mr Clinton emphasised that the
bilateral economic relationship between the US was the most important in the
world, and added: 'We must make progress on our bilateral trade.'
For his part, Mr Hosokawa said only that 'Japan will do its best' in the
framework of the economic policy adopted in July, 'so that favourable
results will emerge as soon as possible'.
Even if he was disappointed, Mr Clinton nevertheless said: 'I was heartened
by our meeting. Mr Hosokawa has a mandate for change, and I think that means
we can work together'.
In an interview televised earlier, Mr Hosokawa said Japan should not go out
of its way to seek a Security Council seat.
'I believe it is necessary for Japan to let things take their course, and if
(Japan is) asked to be a permanent member, then (it would) become a
permanent member,' he said.
'But I don't think Japan should go out of its way to make a campaign to
become a member.'
</TEXT>
