<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Deadline looms on spending bills
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US Congress is likely to have to resort to its habitual stop-gap
measures to keep the government running, after again failing to meet the
September 30 deadline for passing new spending bills.
Without new legislation, federal departments will run out of money when the
US fiscal year ends at midnight on Thursday.
Only one of the 13 spending bills, providing for Congress' own funding, has
been passed, and congressional leaders expect they will have to resort to a
'continuing resolution' providing for spending allocations from 1993 to be
rolled forward for two weeks.
Continuing resolutions are a recurrent tool of Congress, but they always
create a degree of nervousness because they must pass if the government is
not to grind to a halt, and members sometimes try to exploit them by
attaching other measures.
Some spending bills have already passed both chambers of Congress and bills
covering the agriculture and treasury departments, and perhaps also foreign
aid, could pass before Thursday night's deadline.
Delays are expected for the Dollars 240bn (Pounds 156bn) defence
appropriations bill, the only one which has not yet passed the House. It has
been held up as members were reluctant to vote for big military spending
programmes before the Pentagon's own 'bottom up review'.
The transport department's Dollars 13bn spending bill also faces delays and
the interior department bill could be held hostage in the battle by western
senators to block administration efforts to reform the running of federal
lands and raise fees charged to ranchers who rent grazing from the
government.
</TEXT>
