<DATE>930928
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / UN says over 4m face food shortages
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE THAN 4.2m people in the republics of the former Yugoslavia will
experience severe food shortages this winter unless pledges of food aid are
urgently made, the World Food Programme, the UN agency, warned yesterday.
Unless fresh deliveries were made before January, the situation would become
critical, the WFP added, noting that its food stocks for the period after
January were almost exhausted.
The appeal came as the UN High Commissioner for Refugees issued an urgent
warning about the plight of Moslems trapped in the northern Bosnian enclaves
of Maglaj and Tesanj.
Up to 150,000 Moslems, about half of whom were refugees, have been trapped
in the towns by Serb forces who have refused to let any aid enter the region
since early summer, Mr Ray Wilkinson, UNHCR spokesman in Sarajevo said
yesterday.
Although the UNHCR has been carrying out emergency airdrops, aid agencies
have been unable to reach the city for several months, and the situation is
believed to be critical.
'From what we know it seems that it is a situation as serious as Mostar,' Mr
Wilkinson said.
The UNHCR estimates that in Bosnia alone some 2.8m people will require food
aid during the next sixth months, including 260,000 tonnes of wheat flour,
biscuits, oil, fish, meat, sugar and salt, at a total cost of almost Dollars
200m (Pounds 130m).
Although the WFP has enough wheat flour for the next three months, only
50-60 per cent of the money needed to buy high protein foods for that period
has been donated, Mr David Morton, WFP co-ordinator in Zagreb, said.
</TEXT>
