<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Ex-Soviet bloc attracts Dollars 42bn: Large-scale energy
projects boost western investment in the east
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOREIGN investors committed more than Dollars 42bn (Pounds 27.2bn) to more
than 1,700 projects in the 28 countries of the former Soviet empire in the
18 months up to the end of March 1993, according to figures compiled by East
European Investment magazine.
The figures, based on data compiled from 160 publications, include outright
acquisitions, investment pledges made as part of privatisation deals and
investment in greenfield projects. However, they do not distinguish between
actual capital flows and associated investment commitments.
Largely for this reason, Russia emerges as the biggest recipient of foreign
investment, accounting for Dollars 10.56bn, more than 25 per cent of the
total, spread over 402 investment deals, including 106 greenfield projects
and 285 joint ventures. The bulk of such deals are concentrated in a
relatively small number of energy-related projects involving large-scale
investment over many years. Such flows are only likely to materialise when
Russia can give investors the legal and proprietorial rights they demand
before committing funds.
The strong showing of Kazakhstan, which has soared to second place in the
investment league table with Dollars 9.12bn pledged or committed, also
reflects the weighting in favour of big projects like the Dollars 6bn-plus
gas exploration and transport project led by British Gas and Agip of Italy,
and the large-scale Chevron oil involvement in the Tenghiz oil field. The
distorting effect on the figures of such projects is shown most clearly in
the case of Azerbaijan, which has announced only seven foreign investment
projects, all joint ventures, with a total investment outlay of Dollars
2.56bn.
Elsewhere, the biggest share, and by the far the greatest number of
investment deals of all kinds, is concentrated in the former communist
states of central Europe.
Poland has emerged as the most popular target for investment, with 162 deals
over the last 18 months totalling Dollars 5.56bn in foreign equity
disbursements and commitments. It is followed by Hungary, which retains its
title as the economy which has attracted most foreign capital per capita. In
the last 18 months, 334 investment deals involving Dollars 3.16bn were
recorded.
The Czech Republic continued to attract more than 90 per cent of total
foreign investment drawn to the now divided Czechoslovakia.
It attracted Dollars 1.4bn compared with the Dollars 191m which was
attracted to Slovakia over this period.
Heavy involvement by US energy, transport and consumer goods corporations
continues to put the US at the head of the investor country league.
US-based corporations committed Dollars 13.6bn to 469 projects, followed by
Italy, where Fiat's Dollars 2bn commitment to Poland and Agip's JV with
British Gas in Kazakhstan boosted the total to Dollars 7.8bn. Report
available from 13 White Lodge, Castlebar Park, London W5. Dollars 290.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
