FT  28 SEP 93 / French surge in RSI sufferers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Repetitive strain injury (RSI) has become the leading professional health
problem in France, where the number of people claiming social security
compensation has tripled over the past five years, it was reported
yesterday, writes David Buchan in Paris.
An international conference in Nice on health in the workplace was told that
the number of sufferers from stress-related tendonitis reporting their
problems to France's National Office for Health Insurance (CNAM) had risen
from 646 in 1987 to 2,105 last year. This was out of a total of only 5,080
professional illness claims settled by CNAM last year.
