</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ONE OF the most promising advances in a decade in efforts to swing Basque
public opinion decisively against the terrorist activities of the Eta
separatist movement has been shaken by the deaths of two Eta suspects in
police custody and medical evidence alleging the severe bruising of a third.
Mr Jose Luis Corceura, the interior minister, is scheduled to make an
emergency appearance in parliament in Madrid today to explain the background
to a series of incidents which are worrying the Spanish public.
Eta supporters have been quick to accuse the Spanish civil guard and the
Basque police force, the Ertzaintza, of torturing Miren Gurutze Yanci, who
died of heart failure while in custody last Friday, Xabier Galparsoro, who
died on the same day after falling from the second floor of a police
station, and Maria Jose Lizarribar.
