<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Down to one room instead of all Russia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NEVER CLOSE, the two men who lead the defence of the Russian constitution
have now fallen to argument as the relentless pressure of being cooped in a
giant jar in the middle of Moscow strips away their reserves of tolerance.
General Alexander Rutskoi, 46, acting president with no country to govern
and Mr Ruslan Khasbulatov, 51, leader of a parliament abolished by fiat,
insist they will never surrender. But beyond that, they have little to do
with each other.
They have not appeared together before their supporters outside the White
House for days.
Mr Khasbulatov's unequivocal prediction at 2.00am yesterday morning that an
attack would come at dawn was later flatly contradicted not just by events,
but also by Gen Rutskoi - though he thinks an attack is imminent.
One of his advisers, asking not to be named, said yesterday the acting
president was infuriated by Mr Khasbulatov's obvious assumption that the
latter was the leader of the resistance - evinced most recently by a remark
made by the parliamentary leader to the deputies that he would 'tell the
acting president to see to it'.
The acting president has risen much better to the occasion than the
parliamentary leader - the former drawing on his military bearing and
discipline, and a theatrical, occasionally almost absurd, populist style.
On Sunday he vowed to 'stay to the death' after touring the White House with
a megaphone demanding of the indifferent riot troops that they 'remember
their oath to the fatherland and the constitution'. Later, he led a few
thousand of the defenders, a ragged-trousered army, round the building, its
various Soviet, Russian Imperial and St Andrew's Cross flags flying bravely.
Mr Khasbulatov has not so responded. Most effective when commanding the
split and formless parliament, he is not fitted to the public gesture. At a
press conference yesterday, he fell back on repetitions of 'there will be no
compromise - it is not for us to compromise with this criminal regime - the
only compromise is a restoration of the constitution', mixed with irrelevant
anecdotes and bad jokes.
He maintains an impressive calm, but at the expense of coherence.
'I don't know what Khasbulatov and Rutskoi are doing together there in the
dark,' said Mr Yeltsin in a television interview at the weekend, with
confident suggestiveness. Yesterday, his deputy chief-of-staff, Mr
Vyacheslav Volkov, said that 'if the law doesn't judge them guilty of some
criminal act, they can decide their own fate'. President Yeltsin and his
team have already consigned them to oblivion, and that may indeed be the
fate of two men, not old for politicians, who rose dizzily from,
respectively, the positions of an Air Force colonel and a professor of
economics to challenge the president of Russia for power.
For Mr Khasbulatov, sharp tongued and by nationality a Chechen (one of the
north Caucasian tribes), there is little support. For Gen Rutskoi, a
Russian, a decorated Afghan veteran and an obvious patriot, there will be
more. Thus it is to him that Mr Grigory Yavlinsky, a candidate for president
and a self-appointed go-between, went with advice to drop his 'no surrender'
stance and attempt to negotiate himself out of the jam. 'I have asked the
other (presidential) side not to drive Rutskoi into a corner,' said Mr
Yavlinsky. 'He said he would consider my words, but I think he's not taking
his own decisions.'
In Mr Yavlinsky's view - and it is a common one of Gen Rutskoi - he is an
outwardly impressive but shifting figure, with no strong convictions and
thus prey for powerful or unscrupulous advisers.
That cannot be said of Mr Khasbulatov who, whatever his limitations, goes
his own way.
For mixed motives of ambition, belief and hatred, both men had found
themselves ground below the stone of Mr Yeltsin's new-found determination to
be rid of his enemies.
If there is a way out 'with dignity', it is a small one and it is closing
fast.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
</CN>
