<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Raw nerve of Germany's state banks: Privatisation call fires
debate as it challenges core of 'social market' principles
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A DEBATE has flared up in German political and business circles about the
future of the state-owned banking sector after a call by Mr Otto Lambsdorff,
economics spokesman for the Free Democrats, for the Landesbanken -
commercial banks owned to a large extent by federal Germany's state
governments - and Sparkassen - savings banks owned by local authorities - to
be privatised.
His comments prompted criticism from Mr Horst Kohler, the president of the
powerful German savings bank federation, and from Mr Friedel Neuber, chief
executive of Westdeutsche Landesbank (WestLB), the largest and most
controversial of Germany's Landesbanken.
Public sector credit institutions, which enjoy more than half the German
banking market, would seem obvious candidates for a sell-off.
Privatisation could raise DM100bn-DM150bn (Pounds 40bn-Pounds 60bn) for the
cash-strapped German government, economists have calculated. It would also
fit with the government's new-found commitment to privatisation - outlined
most recently in the economics ministry's policy document on securing the
future of Germany's economic base.
Influential economists, such as Professor Horst Siebert, head of the
Institute for World Economics in Kiel, argue that there are no logical
economic reasons why there should be a state-sector banking industry in
Germany. Everything that the Sparkassen and the Landesbanken did could be
done just as well, if not better, by the private sector, Prof Siebert has
said in a spate of articles and interviews.
Mr Lambsdorff went further than this last month, saying the public sector
institutions had outgrown the special role they played in helping to rebuild
the German economy after the Second World War. The only part of Germany
which needed state-owned banks now was eastern Germany, he argued.
Mr Neuber, the WestLB chief and most prominent public sector banker in
Germany, rejected these arguments in forthright terms, saying the fabric of
society and the stability of the German banking system would be damaged if
it was tampered with.
He added that those who called for privatisation were in fact goaded by the
state sector's steadily improving competitiveness: 'This has not found
favour with everyone,' he said.
Indeed, WestLB's aggressive expansion in recent years has angered the
private sector banks.
The Dusseldorf-based institution is formally house-bank to the state of
North Rhine/Westphalia, responsible for innocuous public sector tasks such
as managing the state's finances, paying its civil servants' salaries and
doling out subsidised loans to support local industry.
But Mr Neuber has a broader concept of the role of a state bank. He has
built up alliances with other, smaller Landesbanken to diversify beyond its
Ruhr-heartland, he has built up an international presence and he has muscled
into corporate banking business which for decades was the preserve of the
private sector. He has also put together a large portfolio of share stakes
in industrial companies.
WestLB says the strategy is designed to support the Ruhr-area's regional
economy. But to critics it is empire-building on the part of an arm of the
Social Democrat controlled state of North Rhine/Westphalia - particularly
inappropriate at a time when Bonn has accepted the need to roll back the
frontiers of the state.
But privatisation in Germany has its limits, and those limits have so far
stopped short of the financial sector. The reason is that the state role in
banking goes right to the heart of Germany's 'social market' economy - where
market forces are tempered by social considerations.
Any attempt to tamper with the status quo would unleash powerful forces of
opposition, not least in the Bundesrat, the upper house of the German
parliament which represents the interests of the Lander.
</TEXT>
