<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Opec agrees output ceiling to reverse fall in prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CORZINE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Organisation of Petroleum Exporting Countries agreed a new production
ceiling yesterday which it hopes will reverse declining oil prices and
persuade markets that members are determined to curb severe overproduction.
The 12 oil ministers agreed that output in the fourth quarter of this year
would be 24.5m barrels a day, slightly less than Opec's third-quarter peak,
but well above the present official ceiling of 23.5m b/d.
But they left the difficult issue of individual country quotas to further
talks which yesterday were adjourned overnight.
Oil markets reacted to the news with a modest price increase. Brent blend
for November was about 20 cents higher at Dollars 16.45 in late London
trading.
The higher output ceiling reflects the expected increased demand toward the
end of the year with the onset of the northern hemisphere winter. Analysts
say the ministers also needed to set a higher figure to balance conflicting
demands including:
The need to set a ceiling which accommodated at least some of the demand for
additional output by countries which have been overproducing, such as Iran
and Nigeria.
The desire to bring Kuwait back into the production ceiling mechanism, which
it left earlier this year because it wanted a much higher quota.
The need to send a signal to the markets that Opec has set a realistic
production level at which any cheating could be kept to a minimum.
The agreement on overall output came after Tehran Radio reported that King
Fahd of Saudi Arabia and President Hashemi Rafsanjani of Iran had spoken by
telephone yesterday on the need for higher oil prices.
The two countries have long been at odds over quotas and market shares. But
in common with other Opec states, they are suffering from sharply reduced
revenues and have set a priority on reaching an agreement which the markets
will see as credible.
'We are thinking in dollars and cents rather than in percentages,' said one
Gulf Arab delegate.
But there were signs last night that the task of allocating individual
quotas could prove difficult. Mr Ali Ahmed Al-Baghli, the Kuwaiti oil
minister, said his country had rejected an offer of 1.9m b/d. 'We want to be
re-integrated, but not on any basis,' he said. Iran and Nigeria were also
understood to be holding out for higher quotas.
Saudi Arabia is understood to be sticking to its present output of 8m b/d
while some smaller producers have agreed to a formula in which they receive
only modest quota increases.
Lex, Page 20
Commodities, Page 32
London stocks, Page 42
</TEXT>
