<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / GrandMet surprises City with Pounds 175m restructuring
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES, Consumer Industries Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GRAND Metropolitan, the food, drinks and retailing group, sprang another
surprise on the City yesterday by announcing a Pounds 175m restructuring
provision and issuing an upbeat statement on trading conditions and profits.
The announcement follows Friday's unexpected promotion of Mr George Bull to
the position of chief executive. It was widely applauded as an attempt to
improve communications by a group renowned for its complex accounting
arrangements.
GrandMet said most of its operations were performing well and forecast that
profits before exceptional items and tax for the year to September 30 would
be about 5 per cent higher than last year's figure of Pounds 871m.
The group's shares rose 10p on the news to close at 403p, reflecting relief
among many investors, who had feared a fall in profits. The restructuring
will involve the loss of about 3,000 jobs, many in the US, and is expected
to yield annual savings of about Pounds 80m for two years. Around half the
provision will involve cash outlays, to be completed by the end of next
year.
About Pounds 65m of the restructuring provision will cover the closure of
four plants and the loss of 600 jobs at Green Giant, the frozen vegetable
division of Pillsbury, GrandMet's US food manufacturing subsidiary.
A further Pounds 60m will go towards the closure of unprofitable stores and
asset write-offs by Pearle Vision, the US optical retailer owned by
GrandMet. The remaining Pounds 50m will be used to reduce costs and staff
levels across the group's other operations. GrandMet said that though many
world markets remained weak, IDV, its drinks division, expected double-digit
growth in operating profits this year. IDV had increased market share in the
US and was benefiting from improved conditions in Britain.
Pillsbury's sales volumes remained flat, though pricing pressures on Green
Giant had recently eased. Excluding the restructuring plan, operating
profits in food were expected to be above last year and to show a
'substantial' increase after currency translation.
Burger King, the fast food subsidiary, enjoyed further sales growth, though
sales at Chef &amp; Brewer, the UK pub division, would be down on last year.
GrandMet said it was changing its accounting treatment of results from its
Brazilian drinks business to adjust for hyper-inflation. This would result
in a restatement of last year's pre-tax profits, which would be reduced by
Pounds 12m to Pounds 859m.
