<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / Sutherland warns of farm reforms impasse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER and GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Peter Sutherland, director-general of the General Agreement on Tariffs
and Trade, damped hopes yesterday of any early solution to the critical
dispute between the European Community and the US which threatens world
trade reforms.
Mr Sutherland said an attempt by the EC at French insistence to amend the
Blair House accord reached last November on agriculture between the EC and
the US had created 'an impasse to which a clear solution is not apparent'.
A crucial aspect of the accord envisages a 21 per cent cut in the volume of
subsidised EC food exports over the next six years.
Mr Sutherland, speaking after addressing the International Monetary Fund
interim committee in Washington, said the dispute was among issues that
could wreck the Uruguay Round of trade talks.
Sir Leon Brittan, EC trade commissioner, and Mr Mickey Kantor, US trade
representative, are to discuss the dispute in Washington today. It arose
after France called for further 'clarifications' to the accord.
Mr Sutherland, who called for a renewal of the commitment by 116 countries
involved in the Uruguay Round to cut tariffs, added that 'it is our job' to
find a solution to the Blair House dispute.
Mr Sutherland's remarks came as the World Bank disclosed the findings of a
study which concluded that the partial trade liberalisation envisaged under
the Uruguay Round could add Dollars 213bn a year to world income by 2002.
IMF reports, Pages 2 and 3
Brittan and Kantor to meet, Page 6
