<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / Monday Interview: Society man of action - Tony Blair, UK
shadow home secretary
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The party's 'foremost moderniser' or 'the next Labour leader' are the
epithets most commonly applied by political commentators to Tony Blair.
Kenneth Clarke, the Conservatives' own leader-in-waiting, regards the shadow
home secretary as the most dangerous figure on the opposition frontbenches.
Tory MPs have been caught out offering bewildered applause for Mr Blair's
surprisingly tough plans to tackle the country's crime wave.
But life for the fastest-rising star in British politics - he is 40 years of
age and has been in parliament for barely a decade - has hit a rough patch.
The government is in disarray, Mr John Major's premiership is under threat.
Mr John Smith has an 18-point lead in the opinion polls. So the Labour party
is threatening to lapse into its bad old ways.
Mr Blair, along with Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, has become the
target of a familiar and less-than-subtle whispering campaign.
The 'one-more-heave' tendency, which spent much of the 1980s opposing Mr
Neil Kinnock's attempts to restore Labour's links with electoral reality, is
back in business.
So, too, are the left-wing critics of 'modernisation' who blame Labour's
fourth successive general election defeat not on the voters' fear of high
tax and spending policies but on its refusal to offer a bold, socialist
vision.
Mr Smith's plans to modernise the party's links with the trades unions
through the introduction of one-member-one-vote (OMOV) in the selection of
parliamentary candidates could yet be defeated at this week's Brighton
conference.
Mr Blair is visibly frustrated. Flashes of exasperation show through an
hour-long exposition of why Labour must change if it is not to remain in
permanent opposition.
'One thing is very important for the party to understand. There is always a
great risk in politics of delusion. There are those who say that Labour lost
the last election because it was too cautious and too timid. The notion that
Labour lost because the electorate thought it was too cautious and too timid
is just one of the more alarming political eccentricities of modern times.'
He warms to the theme: 'The voters did not go into the ballot box and say:
'I want something that is going to set my life alight, so I'm voting for
John Major this time'.'
The frustration shows through: 'We must remember what the election in April
1992 was really like and what people really felt, what their real worries
were about Labour, rather than rewrite history.'
He is similarly dismissive of those who believe that the Conservatives are
now so badly wounded that they will lose whatever. Labour has been there
before. And the Tories responded by dumping Lady Thatcher.
'What I find odd is that after four election defeats, and with Labour not
having won over 40 per cent of the popular vote since 1970, that you have to
argue the case for change.'
So does, as his critics charge, this unself-consciously middle-class
barrister want to swap socialism for social democracy? Is he the David Owen
of the 1990s.
No. In Mr Blair's view his opponents are confusing ends with means. It is
perfectly possible to preserve the party's traditional values while
disavowing the policies once used to apply them.
He puts it bluntly: 'The old style-collectivism that sees the notion of
community action simply through a centralised state has had its day. But
that is not to say the notion of community or social action has had its
day.'
This is what Mr Blair is really about. Instead of arguing about whether to
renationalise this or that industry or spend Pounds 1bn or Pounds 2bn more
on the health service he is seeking a new philosophical framework which
would render obsolete the traditional tests of loyalty to the past.
Labour must distill its basic ideology: 'It stands for community. It
believes individuals achieve success not just by their own efforts but
within a strong community. Now that to me is the basic Labour message and
always has been. What I am saying is that you must apply that message to the
world as it is today.'
Here is the core. The dominant phases in British politics during the present
century had been first the collectivism which brought the post-war
settlement and then the reaction against it during the Thatcherite 1980s.
'Now people are searching for, if you like, almost for a new settlement
between community and individual which recognises the importance of social
action but which recognises the aim is to advance the individual. What the
Tories have ended up doing is saying to people you choose between a strong
society and individual fulfilment. What we are saying is it is necessary to
have a strong society for individuals to succeed.'
But what about policies? The voters of southern England whose mistrust of
Labour cost it the 1992 general election will not be much impressed by
ideological frameworks.
Mr Blair admits that his party has not reached the stage of turning the
principles into a new set of policies. But he insists the direction is
obvious.
It points to forsaking grandiose economic intervention in favour of
encouraging regional and community-based economic enterprise and
regeneration. It underscores the importance of decentralisation and the
enhanced local democracy. It signposts an approach to the workplace which
guarantees the rights of individual workers through the law rather than
simply through the collective action of trades unions.
Mr Blair can also claim that the law and order policy which has won him
plaudits this year is drawn directly from his theoretical framework.
By staking out the responsibility of society to deter and prevent crime he
has won himself the room for manoeuvre to demand tough and effective action
against those who flout their responsibility. 'The purpose of social
action,' he says, 'is to allow individuals to take responsibility for
themselves, not to substitute for it.'
Local communities should create partnerships to divert young people from
crime but there must be 'sufficient secure accommodation in the community
that if youngsters are out of control you must have the ability to put them
under lock and key until they do behave'.
But before it can address the electorate Labour must sort out the internal
constitutional wrangle with the unions which has already cast a long shadow
over this week's conference. The vote - on the superficially arcane issue of
just how trades unionists should participate in the selection of Labour's
parliamentary candidates - has become a litmus test of whether the party is
willing to change.
Mr Blair puts it thus: 'It is necessary to advocate change within Labour
before we can win the opportunity to change the country.'
He will not say it, but he is clearly furious with the refusal of many of
the unions to back a relatively modest reform. The union leaders are
clinging on to their institutional levers within the party but forgetting
that real influence comes with government.
Mr Blair leaves the impression that if he were leader, OMOV would be just
the start. In his view, Labour's hope for the future lies in re-establishing
its links with ordinary people by a determined drive to recruit more
individual members.
The model is his own Sedgefield constituency where an experimental
membership scheme has brought the party hundreds of new recruits. He
believes the cut-price membership proposed for union members would further
tilt the balance in local parties away from the internal preoccupations of
their activists towards the concerns of the wider community.
It all sounds pretty convincing stuff, the more so because it is set out
with a calm fluency and coherence all too rare these days in British
politics. It is the sort of programme that might even win Labour a general
election. But, as this week's Brighton conference will remind us, Mr Blair
has as many enemies as friends in his own party.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
PERSONAL FILE
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
1953    Born in Edinburgh. Educated Fettes College, Edinburgh; St John's
        College, Oxford.
1976    Barrister.
1983    Labour MP for Sedgefield.
1984-87 Assistant shadow spokesman on Treasury affairs.
1987-92 Shadow spokesman on trade and industry and then employment.
1992-   Shadow home secretary.
