<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / More Maastricht to come: Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN DAVIDSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Maastricht is not a popular treaty. After so much hassle, disappointment and
interminable argument, many may feel, not unreasonably, that they've already
heard just about as much as they can stand, and wish the politicians would
change the subject.
If so, they are destined to be disappointed. For we are probably on the
threshold of yet another Europe-wide debate about the treaty, which is
likely to inaugurate the biggest and most politically charged discussion on
the future of Europe since the epic struggles of the 1960s.
This debate is unavoidable. The treaty is a ramshackle structure with
disparate pieces tacked together, some of which were improvised in haste in
response to German unification. And the consequence of improvisation and
ambiguity, and of the impact of outside events, is that it does not look
viable as framed. The programme for monetary union obviously needs to be
re-examined, if only because a significant number of member states will not
be able, and some will not be willing, to meet the conditions for a single
currency. The commitment to a common foreign policy looks merely ridiculous
in the light of the Yugoslav disaster.
In theory these treaty imperfections could be side-stepped: those who don't
want a single currency or a single foreign policy could simply stay outside
the integrationist stream, and the Community would gradually diverge on
variable-geometry lines. But there is one new problem facing the Community
which cannot be side-stepped: how far can it expand with new members, and
what will be the institutional consequences? This is the issue which makes
unavoidable the debate now getting under way.
Mr John Major, the British prime minister, has tried to hijack that debate
in advance, so as to pre-empt any attempt by others to press for an
acceleration of the traditional Community integration process. His vision of
the Community, which he has set out in a long article in The Economist, is
of a Europe which is large and loose, inter-governmental rather than
integrated. In place of the old (and discredited) objective of European
Monetary Union, it needs a new agenda, whose immediate priorities should be
the conclusion of the Uruguay trade round, the deregulation of labour
markets and the slimming of welfare costs. The longer objective should be to
include the whole of Europe.
This anti-integrationist vision is a characteristically British recipe. It
is unlikely to prove any more persuasive to the other member states today,
however, than it has in the past. The original six, at least, have been
committed to an integrationist model of the Community for 40 years. They
will not abandon it lightly, least of all to please Britain.
By contrast, a far-reaching integrationist vision has already been marked
out by Germany's ruling Christian Democrat party, in a paper drafted by Mr
Karl Lamers, the party's foreign affairs spokesman. Even if this is not an
official government document, it is likely to indicate where Germany will
stand at next month's Community summit.
Like Mr Major, Mr Lamers insists on the need to reach a successful
conclusion of the Uruguay round. But on almost every other issue his vision
of Europe is diametrically opposed to that of Mr Major. He maintains, for
example, that 'it is essential, despite the problems that have recently
beset the EMS, that the goal of monetary union and the timetable proposed be
adhered to'. In other areas of the Maastricht treaty, the Community must
press ahead with policy integration: asylum and immigration, the fight
against organised crime, and a common foreign policy.
Security policy is an issue of clear divergence of emphasis between the
British and German visions. Mr Major stresses the importance of Nato, within
which 'the Europeans should take on greater responsibility'. But Mr Lamers
says that the Western European Union defence grouping should be strengthened
'and equipped with military forces', as the best way to ensure a continued
American commitment.
The biggest gulf between Major and Lamers concerns the Community's
institutions. They both believe that the Community must eventually take in
the countries of eastern Europe. But whereas Mr Major wants an
intergovernmental Community of nation states, Mr Lamers believes enlargement
requires a strengthening of the integration principle.
'The expansion of the Community . . . must not be allowed to weaken the
degree of integration already achieved by the present core; on the contrary
this must be strengthened. Otherwise the European Union will not be able to
help solve the increasingly life-threatening crises of the nations that make
it up . . . For that reason, institutional reforms of the Community must be
undertaken in parallel to the membership negotiations currently in hand with
the Efta countries.'
These institutional reforms should include a radical strengthening of
majority voting in the Council of Ministers, combined with a sharp reduction
in the voting premium currently enjoyed by the small member states. The most
dramatic change would be the abandonment of all unanimous voting, to be
replaced by a 'super-qualified majority': with votes of four-fifths of the
members representing at least four-fifths of the population.
The Lamers vision is obviously overambitious. But if anything like it is put
forward by Germany next month, we can be sure that it will open up a
far-reaching debate about fundamental principles which were left on one side
during the Maastricht negotiations.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
<XX>
