<DATE>930927
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / The Asian miracle that wasn't: America
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
People who believe in a 'third way' - an economic philosophy that offers a
surer path to equitable growth than either market capitalism or socialism -
often find themselves looking east. Led by Japan a group of dynamic East
Asian economies appears to have flouted the rules of market economics yet
achieved unparalleled economic success.
If these countries have found a new elixir of growth, the rest of the world
needs the formula. If they have not, the world also needs to know because
Asian success is increasingly seen as proof of the obsolescence of
Anglo-Saxon capitalism. Many people in formerly communist countries believe
the 'East Asian model' offers a better prospect than orthodox free-market
prescriptions. To assess these claims, the World Bank undertook a mammoth
research project involving comparative studies of eight leading Asian
economies over several decades. Economists of all ideological persuasions
will find its report, published today, of considerable interest.
The sceptics who argue that East Asia 'did things differently' will be
gratified that the bank now concedes that most of the countries deviated
substantially from free-market doctrines. At least three types of
intervention were ubiquitous: industrial policies designed to promote
particular sectors or companies; government controls on financial markets to
lower the cost of capital and direct credit to favoured sectors; and
policies to promote exports that included extensive protection of domestic
industries.
But do not leap to conclusions. As the bank argues, the principal reason for
the region's success is its adherence to economic fundamentals.
Macroeconomic policies have been consistently prudent: the hallmarks are low
inflation, low or negative budget deficits and modest foreign debts. Workers
have studied longer, worked harder and saved more than their counterparts
elsewhere.
And although the Asian 'stars' certainly deviated from market norms, they
did so less on average than other developing countries. The price of factors
of production such as capital and labour was kept much closer to
market-clearing levels than in less buoyant regions such as Latin America or
sub-Saharan Africa. Since the countries that intervened least grew most
rapidly, it is hard to conclude that the interventions were hugely
important.
In any case, East Asian policies have evolved over the decades. The
heavy-handed interventions occurred in Japan, Korea and, to a lesser extent,
Singapore, from the 1950s to the 1970s when the world was a very different
place. In those days, the rich western democracies also heavily regulated
their financial markets and indulged in all kinds of domestic interventions.
East Asia has tended to keep up with the times. The Asian stars that emerged
during the 1980s - Malaysia, Indonesia and Thailand - have followed more
market-oriented policies than their predecessors. Meanwhile, countries like
Korea have also seen the merits of more liberal policies.
The bank concludes that Asian experiments with industrial policies were
mostly a failure because unaided market forces would have brought about the
desired changes in industrial structure. It concedes that directed credit
and other forms of 'financial repression' did sometimes increase savings and
investment. But it reserves praise for the area's 'export push' strategy
which imposed a powerful competitive discipline on local companies and
accelerated the transfer of technology from more advanced economies.
This leaves would-be imitators of East Asia in a bind. If the bank is to be
believed, industrial policies do not work. Financial repression may work but
is much harder to implement in today's globally integrated capital markets
than decades ago when Japanese and Korean bureaucrats parcelled out credit
like children's presents. Crude attempts to promote exports are equally
problematic because industrial countries (especially the US) are determined
to create a level global playing field in trade. Developing countries can
and should lift artificial barriers to exports but they cannot any longer
combine export promotion with overt protection of home markets.
Should we shed tears because many of the apparent deviations from market
principles pioneered by Japan and Korea no longer seem credible? The answer
is no, for a reason not brought out sufficiently clearly in the bank's
report. These countries never had a long-term alternative to western market
capitalism. It is true that they glorified their producers and suppressed
their consumers. But they only became efficient producers because they
sought instead to serve the interests of a richer, more numerous and
sophisticated group of consumers: the citizens of western democracies who
bought their exports.
Had western consumers (especially Americans) not existed, the East Asian
miracle simply could not have occurred. Without the guiding star of western
consumer preferences their leading companies would have had no more idea of
what to produce, or how, than former Soviet or east European state
enterprises. As they mature the Asian high-fliers will be forced to treat
their own consumers with more respect, in the process completing the
transition to western market capitalism. There is no third way.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XOZ  Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
