<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / European Bonds: Volatility still the name of the game
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CONNER MIDDELMANN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VOLATILITY will remain the name of the game in Europe's bond markets this
week, although most analysts expect fundamental factors to gradually
reassert themselves as the Russian constitutional crisis loses momentum.
Bond prices see-sawed last week on reports of troop movements and civil-war
warnings following President Boris Yeltsin's suspension of Russia's
parliament.
Germany, which is seen as being most vulnerable to upheaval in Russia due to
its close political and economic ties, took the worst beating, with the
currency plunging and yields on 10-year bunds climbing some 10 basis points
on the week. Most continental European markets were dragged lower by
Germany, though lagging its losses slightly.
The main beneficiaries were those bond markets which had already fallen
sharply prior to the Russian turmoil: UK gilts and Italian bonds. Moreover,
US Treasuries saw heavy buying on the US currency's perceived safe-haven
status.
But unless the Russian crisis escalates, many of last week's flows may be
reversed this week, with investors focusing again on Europe's fundamentals:
anaemic growth and weak inflation fuelling hopes of further rate cuts.
Expectations for Danish easing were met earlier than expected when key
interest rates were cut by  1/2 point late on Friday. 'The currency remained
strong after the rate cuts, which indicates Denmark can continue easing in
coming weeks,' said Mr Werner Kramer, bond strategist with DB Research,
Deutsche Bank's analysis subsidiary. 'That will continue supporting the
Danish market.'
Talk of French rate cuts was also rife ahead of the Group of Seven meeting
in Washington, where France was expected to come under pressure to cut its
rates, which have been kept high to protect the franc against the D-Mark.
Moreover, the Bank of France probably took advantage of the franc's relative
strength last week to replenish some of its foreign-currency reserves,
facilitating an easing, said Ms Alison Cottrell, European economist at
Midland Global Markets. The need to shore up its reserves, which were
depleted heavily during the recent European currency crisis, has been seen
as one of the reasons for the central bank's unwillingness to ease.
According to the perverse logic of the currency markets, a rate cut will
probably boost the franc, fuel further easing hopes and support the bond
market.
While German bonds will remain overshadowed by the Russian power struggle,
investors will be cheered by the latest inflation data, which were lower
than expected. On the basis of regional CPI data released on Friday, western
German inflation is likely to be 4 per cent in September, down from 4.2 per
cent in August.
Mr Kramer at DB Research says long-term investors should seize upon bunds'
current weakness to buy. 'The German markets will remain volatile in the
short term, but on a three to six-month horizon we see 10-year yields going
well below 6 per cent.' The 10-year bund yield closed at 6.16 per cent on
Friday.
He also favours UK gilts, where low inflation and economic growth prospects
support the currency and yield outlook. Wednesday's auction of Pounds 3 1/4
bn of 6 3/4 per cent 2004 gilts is likely to meet strong international
demand, he said.
One way for investors to reduce exposure to near-term volatility is to
switch to the short end, said Mr Graham McDevitt, bond strategist at market
analysis firm IDEA. 'The short end of most yield curves is the safest area -
the long end will get whipped around by further unrest in Russia,' he said.
</TEXT>
