<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / US Money and Credit: Fed switches back into neutral
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LATEST minutes from the Federal Reserve's Open Market Committee have
just been released and show a surprising, albeit subtle, shift in opinion
among the members of the central bank's main policy-making body.
The minutes for the August 17 meeting showed that the FOMC voted unanimously
to keep policy unchanged, but also to remove its earlier bias toward
tightening and switch toward a symmetrical directive.
In English, this means that the Fed is no longer so concerned about
inflation, and, therefore, is now less inclined to make the next move in
interest rates an upward one. The explanation for the shift was given in the
minutes, which said: 'Members (of the FOMC) observed that the more
favourable performance of key measures of prices in recent months had tended
to relieve earlier concerns about a possible worsening in inflation.'
The FOMC, however, always on guard against sending the wrong message to the
fixed-income markets, added a big 'but' to the above statement: 'However,
because the recent price indexes probably overstated the improvement in the
trend rate of inflation, it was too early to determine whether they pointed
to renewed disinflation.'
The shift to a symmetrical directive on August 17 is particularly
interesting for two reasons.
It is interesting because senior members of the Fed, and self-appointed
members of the alternative Fed (the Shadow Open Market Committee of
economists that seems to have taken upon itself to act as the Fed's
monetarist conscience) have been warning in recent weeks that if interest
rate policy remains too accommodating, a speculative 'bubble' in stock and
bond prices could inflate, and then burst, with dramatic consequences for
the financial markets and the economy.
The shift in policy is also intriguing because the most recent inflation
data, released just under two weeks ago, appears to justify the Fed's
qualifying statement in the August FOMC minutes. The latest figures showed
that consumer prices rose by 0.3 per cent in August, which was well above
Wall Street's forecast of a 0.1 per cent increase.
Those figures gave the bond market a big shock, and presaged the return of
long yields to back above 6 per cent, where they have stayed stubbornly ever
since. That sell-off, and subsequent declines that were halted only in the
final days of last week, prompted some observers to declare the bond market
rally over.
That could be a bit premature, for longer-dated prices jumped in the final
hours of trading last Friday when the news of the FOMC's new stance was
released.
Yet, if the market reacts so positively to the FOMC's policy shift of August
17, it is just as likely to react negatively when the minutes of the latest
FOMC meeting, held just last week, are released. Given that the most recent
inflation numbers alarmed investors with their robustness, those minutes
could well show that the committee has voted to return to a non-symmetrical
stance with a bias toward tightening.
If there is anything to be learned from the market's reaction to the latest
FOMC minutes it is that investors should be wary of the coming weeks with
the market in such a fragile state. A raft of economic data is due and
several broking houses believe the figures will show a resurgence in
economic activity.
If the data does come in stronger than expected, then bond prices could
tumble. The market has not forgotten the worrying August consumer prices
number, and is likely to speculate much about what the FOMC decided last
week. Against this background, no one is confidently predicting the return
of bond yields to below 6 per cent.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
