<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / Risk and Reward: Hedge fund managers look for change in
Japanese sentiment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CONNER MIDDELMANN and TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONDON's 12 Japanese equity warrant market makers will be joined today by DE
Shaw Securities International, a subsidiary of the New York-based hedge fund
DE Shaw &amp; Co.
After the Tokyo stock market slump in 1990, several London securities houses
pulled out of Japanese equity warrant market-making. The market's stronger
performance this year - with the Nikkei index climbing to around 20,000 from
16,994 at the start of the year - has prompted speculation that the market
may be on the way to recovery. But others are forecasting more sideways
trading as long as political uncertainty lingers and economic recovery
remains sluggish.
This has some market participants wondering whether this is an opportune
time for a new firm to enter the market. However, 'it would be foolish to
ignore the Japanese market,' said Mr Lou Salkind, DE Shaw Securities'
managing director. 'At some stage the switch into stocks has to happen,'
added Mr Steven Fine, the firm's institutional sales manager. Moreover, he
notes that many international investors are heavily underweight Japan but
likely to reverse that stance when sentiment turns.
DE Shaw plans to make markets in some 480 Japanese equity warrants,
including many illiquid warrants in which few houses are willing to make a
market.
By setting up this trading subsidiary, its parent company, which started as
a proprietary trading firm, wants to expand into more traditional investment
banking activities. 'We were founded to do quantitative, low-risk trading
and have a very scientific background, which is unusual in investment
banking,' said Mr Salkind.
The firm's decision to shift from its base as a hedge fund raises some
interesting questions about the evolution of the market. When the Japanese
equity warrants market had its peak year in 1989, the market attracted all
manner of investors, both in the Far East and Europe, and was actively
traded by marketmakers. Even after this year's rally, the Nikkei 225 index
has only reached just over half its peak level of 39,000 at the end of 1989.
In the lean years which followed, it has been the activity of hedge funds
which has kept the market alive.
Most investors abandoned the market in Japanese equity warrants, since the
bulk of them were trading far 'out-of-the-money' - that is the exercise
price of the warrants was substantially above the share price - with little
chance that they would ever be worth exercising into the underlying shares.
In a bear market for Japanese stocks, the market for such warrants was
clearly doomed.
But hedge funds are different because trades are usually market-neutral. In
the equity warrants market a typical hedge trade is based on the purchase of
a basket of warrants which is then neutralised by the simultaneous selling
of index futures. It does not matter whether the market rises or falls: the
out-of-the-money warrants and the stock futures exhibit different types of
price performances, which allows arbitrage profits to be extracted from the
trade.
That, at least, is the theory. The problem has been that, although the Tokyo
stock market has improved in price performance this year, volatility has
been low. For the hedge fund manager it is volatility, rather than price
performance, which affects the performance of the fund.
Nevertheless, in a still uncertain environment for Japanese equities, the
attraction of the hedge fund is that 'the investor does not have to take a
view on which way the market is going to go,' says Mr Michael
Campbell-Birkett, of Cresvale International Asset Management, which runs
several hedge funds.
The signs are that more investors are now prepared to take a view on the
Japanese market, although they remain cautious. As one trader said, 'fund
managers are shifting their asset allocation (in Japanese stocks) from
massively underweight to, at best, neutral.'
If the Japanese market does start to rally, equity warrants, many of which
are trading cheaply according to dealers, could be in demand again. And more
dramatic market movements would also be welcomed by becalmed hedge fund
managers.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>DE Shaw Securities International.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
