<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / International Company News: Alcan Aluminium shuffles board
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR JACQUES BOUGIE, 46, is taking over as chief executive of Alcan Aluminium
in a major senior management shake-up. He succeeds Mr David Morton.
Alcan is also reorganising its operations worldwide into five main groups
headed by five new executive vice-presidents.
Mr Allan Hodgson, who has been chief financial officer for 12 years and a
director, is leaving the company, as is Mr Ian Rugeroni, president of Alcan
Enterprises.
Mr Bougie joined Alcan in 1979 and in 1989 was hand-picked by Mr Morton to
be president and chief operating officer.
Mr Morton then took over as chairman and chief executive officer following
Mr David Culver's retirement. Mr Morton will continue as chairman of the
board.
The two men have led a company-wide retrenchment programme and have reduced
Alcan Aluminium's annual cost base by about USDollars 500m over the past
three years as world metal prices declined steadily with the North American
recession and then heavy CIS exports.
Alcan says it does not see any turnround in view and the organisational
shake-up is clearly designed to cut costs further and improve profitability.
'Alcan can be an even lower-cost producer by focusing on businesses where it
has the competitive edge,' said Mr Morton.
Alcan is studying its worldwide operation and any cutbacks required to meet
new goals will be made at the operating level.
The new executive vice-presidents are: Robert Ball, 47, Northern American
rolled products, Claude Chamberland, 53, smelting and power, Robert Fox, 57,
raw materials, S. Bruce Heister, 55, Asia Pacific, and Everaldo Santos, 54,
fabricated products.
Reinhold Wagner, 61, will be executive vice-president, rolled products,
Europe. Mr Hodgson is succeeded by Suresh Thadhani, 54, now controller.
</TEXT>
