FT  27 SEP 93 / International Company News: LVMH may expand media side
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LVMH, the French company which is one the world's largest luxury goods
groups, may expand its media interests by making further investments in
French newspapers.
Mr Bernard Arnault, chairman of LVMH, said the group was 'ready to examine
other opportunities' having recently ventured into the newspaper field by
buying La Tribune Desfosses, the financial daily.
The chairman said that it would take 'between three and five years' to bring
the loss-making La Tribune to a satisfactory level of profitability.
However, he said the group was ready 'to play its part in ensuring that the
French press stayed in French hands'.
LVMH is under pressure in its traditional luxury market, particularly in its
champagne and cognac businesses. The group has warned that net profits might
fall in 1993 following a 28 per cent decline in profits to FFr935m during
the first half of the year.
Lafarge Coppee, the building materials group, has announced that its
FFr2.7bn share and warrants issue was around three times oversubscribed. The
company issued 6.2m shares at FFr434 each.
