<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / International Company News: Germany seeks US concession on
listings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN and JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GERMANY has called on the US to allow German companies to be listed on
American stock markets on the strength of German style balance sheets and
profit and loss accounts.
Mr Theo Waigel, the German finance minister, told Mr Lloyd Bentsen, the US
treasury secretary, that German companies did not wish to follow
Daimler-Benz and be obliged to produce both German and US accounts to obtain
listings on US exchanges.
In talks over the weekend, Mr Waigel said US companies were able to obtain
listings in Germany. It should be possible for German companies to be quoted
on US markets.
A German banker warned that without a change in US policy, other German
companies were unlikely to follow Daimler-Benz, and no German bank would
publish US accounts to get a US listing.
Mr Jurgen Sarrazin, chairman of Dresdner Bank's managing board, said he
favoured mutual recognition of different countries' accounting rules to
solve the problem. In his talk with Mr Waigel, Mr Bentsen promised to review
the situation and raise the matter with the US Securities and Exchange
Commission but warned that the SEC was an independent organisation.
In a letter last week to the Wall Street Journal, Mrs Mary Schapiro, SEC
commissioner, strongly defended US insistence that foreign companies should
conform with the US Generally Accepted Accounting Principles (GAAP) when
seeking a US market listing. But she underlined that the SEC's adherence to
the standards was not arbitrary and it had accommodated deviations on a
case-by-case basis.
The difference between the standards was highlighted when Daimler-Benz
published two sets of accounts in preparation for a New York Stock Exchange
listing. The US accounts showed it a loss of DM949m in the first half, while
under German rules it reported a profit of DM168m.
</TEXT>
