<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / Amstrad looks for chief executive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A CHIEF executive is being sought for Amstrad, the consumer electronics
group which led the UK personal computer boom in the 1980s but since slipped
into loss.
The move is designed to strengthen the company's day-to-day management and
give Mr Alan Sugar, the Amstrad founder and chairman, greater freedom to
concentrate on company strategy. Mr Sugar, the dominant figure in the
organisation, currently combines the role of chairman and chief executive.
The new appointment will result in his taking a less direct role in the
running of the company, which will be in the hands of the new appointee and
Mr Malcolm Miller, one of Mr Sugar's most trusted lieutenants.
Critics of the company's corporate governance argue too much power rests in
Mr Sugar's hands. They were angry last year when he failed to take the
company private through a 30p a share offer. He has since gone some way to
mollifying them by appointing two non-executive directors and seeking a
third.
Amstrad shares closed at 42p on Friday.
The decision to appoint a chief executive is part of a broad package of
measures to revitalise the company which Mr Sugar will announce with
Amstrad's 1992-1993 results, due next month.
He had already hinted he was planning a shake-up when he announced the
Pounds 6.4m acquisition earlier this month of Dancall Radio, a loss-making
Danish cordless telephone company.
Among changes likely as a result are:
A stronger emphasis on telecommunications, including mobile telephony, to
complement the company's successful drive into satellite communications. The
satellite business now accounts for 30 per cent of revenues, while video
systems accounts for 20 per cent.
Mr Miller is expected to manage the consumer electronics company and will
work with the new chief executive on new ventures and acquisitions.
A move away from personal computers (PCs) as the heart of the company's
business. PCs were at one time Amstrad's most profitable line, accounting
for more than 70 per cent of revenues, but intense price competition and
heavy research and development costs have cut profit margins to the point
where it is hard for groups like Amstrad to compete with US market leaders
like Compaq or Dell.
Now PCs account for less than 40 per cent of turnover. The company lost
Pounds 71m last year and is likely to report a further loss this year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
