<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / Yeltsin at end of political life, says chief rival
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON and JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Boris Yeltsin of Russia is 'part of the old era' as surely as is
the Russian parliament whose defeat he is now overseeing, according to Mr
Grigory Yavlinsky, foremost of the declared challengers for the presidential
elections.
'He is preparing the way for the next generation of politicians - but he
himself is at the end of his political life,' said Mr Yavlinsky, the
prominent economist who last month emerged as Russia's 'most trusted'
politician in a nationwide opinion poll.
His remarks came as the parliament's resistance to its abolition seemed to
be weakening under an onslaught of decrees and orders from Mr Yeltsin
designed to bring it into line.
Mr Yavlinsky, 41, whose popularity does not seem to have been dented by the
events of recent days, declared himself a presidential candidate some months
ago, and has since been selling himself as a reformer, but of a new
political generation.
In an interview with the Financial Times at the end of last week, the
challenger said that in speeding the end of the old regime, President
Yeltsin was also hastening his own demise.
Just as former Soviet president Mr Mikhail Gorbachev brought about the end
of communism and fell with it, so Mr Yeltsin was opening the door for a new
wave of political figures in belatedly pushing through constitutional
reform.
Though other candidates have yet to come forward, Mr Yavlinsky's popularity,
based on a demotic style and a refusal to be aligned with any one group,
gives him an impressive lead.
He cites an opinion poll conducted in St Petersburg the day after Mr Yeltsin
dissolved parliament and convened elections to a bicameral assembly in
December. The poll shows him enjoying the support of 21.7 per cent, ahead of
Mr Yeltsin with just 19.7 per cent, and vice-president Alexander Rutskoi -
installed last week as president by parliament - in third place with 10.7
per cent.
Although he agrees the results are 'very preliminary', he says they show
'that people are sick and tired of this confrontation between parliament and
the president'.
As well as being the only declared opposition candidate with a firm grasp of
market economics, he has done more than any other Russian politician to
develop a coherent vision of the future.
His message to the electorate is based on three promises: the construction
of a genuine federal state, the protection of private property and a sound
currency.
Rebellion starts to fade, Page 4
</TEXT>
