<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / The Lex Column: Schroders
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Schroders never really wanted to join the FT-SE 100 index, and last week's
share performance shows why. A net fall of 5 per cent on minimal turnover
and no news developments makes it an embarrassingly awkward member of such a
prestigious club. Its price is particularly volatile because the founding
family's controlling interest makes the stock chronically illiquid. On top
of that, Schroders' appalling disclosure record leaves the shares impossible
for even professional investors to value.
Changes in EC disclosure rules will force Schroders to deal with the latter
problem next year. Confronting the lack of liquidity is more difficult. It
makes Schroders an unsuitable candidate for the index. Yet exclusion would
smack of unfair discrimination - except as part of a general change to the
index rules on liquidity. At present these simply follow the stock exchange
listing requirement that 25 per cent of a company's shares be freely
tradeable. It would be a bold step for the index committee to depart from
this norm. And there is also the thorny problem of whether large
institutional shareholdings should count as part of the freely traded float.
A more subtle approach would be to exclude non-voting shares when market
capitalisation is calculated for index eligibility purposes. Again, stock
exchange rules do not discriminate in this way. But such an approach would
not only exclude an illiquid issue like Schroders. It would also serve the
socially useful purpose of putting additional pressure on others such as
Whitbread which persist with this archaic form of structure.
</TEXT>
