<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / Observer: Alpine heights
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Another Anglo-Saxon ventures into the higher reaches of the Swiss banking
community, a domain where the climate, for the non-Swiss, is not noted for
its clemency.
Australian-born Phillip Colebatch, who has just been named chief financial
and administrative officer of CS Holding, parent company of the financial
group built around Credit Suisse, has survived since 1984 at CS First Boston
in London, latterly as chief financial officer.
But will he fare better at head office than did, say, Andrew Large? Now
chairman of the Securities and Investments Board, Large stayed for little
more than a year among the Swiss Bank Corporation gnomes in Basle.
Walter Frehner, chief executive of SBC when Large was on the executive
board, later insisted that the bank was open to foreigners, but that they
had to speak German - preferably Swiss German.
CS, being a holding company, may prove easier to penetrate than the banks
themselves. English is spoken at executive board meetings and Colebatch will
have American John Hennessy, chief executive of CSFB, as well as his former
boss in London, German Hans-Jorg Rudloff, for company.
Anyway, despite his exalted title, Colebatch will attend meetings without,
initially, being a board member himself. 'There is a quota for foreigners,
it is not so easy,' explains Rudloff, who was moved to Zurich in March from
his position atop the London operation.
Rudloff judges Colebatch to be progressing well with his German lessons:
'high German; no one learns this little (Swiss ) dialect unless they are
born with it.'
Ach so. And how about the quota? Must one of the foreigners move over before
Colebatch gets his seat?
</TEXT>
