<DATE>930927
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / Observer: Classic route to the investor
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
No one can blame Goldman Sachs for racking its collective brains in search
of inventive arguments with which to back Daimler-Benz as it rides down Wall
Street next week. But could the US investment bank, co-adviser for the New
York Stock Exchange share listing, be working potential investors a mite too
hard?
'The concept of crisis in classical aesthetics from Aristotle to Hegel
represents the turning point of a fateful process,' the 285-page buy note
opens, presumably easing the reader in gently.
'The crisis has the appearance of an objective fate bursting in from
without. In fact the contradiction expressed at the catastrophic moment of
the drama has long been present in the dramatic action and the personalities
of the heroes . . .' the document elaborates.
Forced for the purposes of the listing to drop the veil of German accounting
conventions, under which Daimler had forecast a tidy profit of DM1bn this
year, Germany's leading company drives off the side into the red to the tune
of some DM2bn when its profit and loss account is translated into the lingo
of the American bean-counters.
Enter stage left the deus ex machina, Goldman's London-based German analyst
Timothy Plaut and his chorus.
All of a sudden, Daimler's cleansing begins, with the 'crisis' illuminated
as 'the sole prerequisite for renewal'.
Steeped in the corporate culture of a country where high-flown rhetoric is
far from unusual, Plaut may have overestimated his audience's erudition this
time around.
Or does he believe US fund managers would be safer reading Aristotle's
Poetics than Daimler's accounts?
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Daimler-Benz.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3721 Aircraft.
    P3711 Motor Vehicles and Car Bodies.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>FIN  Share issues.
