<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / Letters to the Editor: Labour law must be simplified
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr TIM JOHNSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, You were right to argue in your editorial, 'UK labour laws' (September
13), that employment law in the UK needs rationalisation, and that
collective labour law is not the main problem. The most pressing need for
reform is in relation to individual rights. Here the law is too difficult to
understand and uneconomic to enforce. The law on everyday matters such as
maternity leave is fully understood only by lawyers specialising in the
field. Employees have to wait many months, sometimes years, for disputes to
be resolved. Hearings last for days because industrial tribunals are bogged
down in legalism and legal fees often far exceed the amount of compensation
awarded.
The problem stems from the policy of keeping statutory employment rights
separate from contractual rights. The motive was to avoid legalism. It was
hoped that by giving industrial tribunals jurisdiction over separate
statutory rights covering matters such as unfair dismissal, redundancy pay,
maternity and discrimination they would be able to dispense speedy, cheap
and efficient justice. It hasn't worked. There is now a complex body of case
law in each of these areas and delay and expense are accepted as a matter of
course.
The answer is not to complicate the law even further by adding
quasi-constitutional rights or additional codes of practice to the present
mix of European Community rights, statutory rights and contractual rights.
The answer must be the opposite; to simplify and rationalise employment law
by returning it to its roots in contract. If legislation simply required
employers to provide minimal rights in the contract of employment, problems
about overlap between contractual and statutory rights would disappear and
whole areas of legalism - for instance much of the case law and unfair
dismissal, redundancy and maternity - would fall away.
Consider how this would work in relation to compensation for unfair
dismissal. The contract would specify the circumstances in which an
individual could be dismissed without compensation. This is, in effect, what
happens at the moment in senior executive contracts. A contract would
specify the amount of compensation to be paid in other cases, or a formula
for calculating it, and, adopting one of your ideas, the employee would be
protected against unreasonable dismissal by a code of practice agreed in the
contract. In a dispute, the issue would simply be whether or not the
employer had broken the contract of employment.
If jurisdiction were given to industrial tribunals to determine such
disputes they might be able to provide the cheap, speedy, effective justice
originally intended.
Tim Johnson,
employment law unit,
Coopers &amp; Lybrand,
3rd Floor, Plumtree Court,
London EC4A 4HT
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9441 Administration of Social and Manpower Programs.
</IN>
