<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / Arts: Say yes to freedom - Architecture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By COLIN AMERY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
I suppose it is inevitable that a critic writing about architecture towards
the end of the 20th century is going to be charged with scepticism,
arrogance or even hostility towards the architectural establishment. Anyone
who questions objectively the value of the achievements of the profession in
the last 50 years will be seen, not as broad minded and catholic, but as
narrow minded and prejudiced.
These thoughts are encouraged, not by resentful letters from architects and
art bureaucrats, but by the broader debate which has been prompted by the
government's decision to 'deregulate' the title of architect and allow fresh
air to blow into the closed shop. In the Queen's Speech opening the next
session of parliament a deregulation bill will propose, in the context of a
wish to scrap as much government red tape as possible, the end of the
statutory protection of the title, 'architect'.
At present only someone registered with the nominally independent Architects
Registration Council of the United Kingdom (Arcuk) can legally call himself
an architect. This body was set up in 1931 to regulate the membership,
conduct and education of the profession. It was necessary because
governments have always questioned the monopolistic powers of the Royal
Institute of British Architects (Riba)  - a body that sets professional
standards and (until recently) established fixed scales of fees. Inevitably
what has happened over the years is that Arcuk has really been run by the
weight of Riba members on its councils, and the sense of an unfair monopoly
remains.
When he was interviewed recently in this newspaper the current president of
the Riba, Frank Duffy - a man of great personal conviction and integrity -
squealed a great deal about the dangers of deregulation. But what is odd is
that the profession does not welcome the freedom it is being offered.
Deregulation will allow the Riba to ensure that its own standards are worth
having because of their merits, not because they are officially protected.
Good architects today are not marginalised by the building process. In a
freer climate it does not follow that only the cheapest and the worst will
thrive.
The nub of this regulation or deregulation problem is that the Riba feels
wrong footed by the government. The profession should have grasped the
nettle a long time ago and taken the lead in setting the highest possible
architectural and environmental standards. Instead, it appears that during
the 1960s a silent majority of salaried architects allowed a managerial
profession to develop which is largely without imagination or awareness of
the client's needs. The Riba's identity crisis has increased recently: is it
a learned society or a trade union?
Deregulation offers freedom - something people often find difficult.
Architectural educational standards will continue to be supervised by the
Riba, so the Institute should take the lead and promote the ideas of
imaginative architecture and sound building. It should welcome a more
competitive climate. If the mediocre architects - and there are lots - go to
the wall, then so be it: they will be no loss.
The chance to open windows to all who build has arrived. How tragic and how
typical of architects to fight a rearguard action instead of offering an
inspiring leadership emphasising quality.
*****
The growing interest of the public in the visual arts and architecture gets
a boost this week with the launch of a new art magazine, Tate - The Art
Magazine, which is published in close association with the Tate Gallery in
London. In the first issue the artist Bridget Riley writes inspiringly about
the need for a new gallery of modern art in London.
This debate has been masterminded to date by the director of the Tate
Gallery, Nicholas Serota, but now it has to become a much more public issue.
In the same way that deregulation of the architectural profession should
make architecture itself much closer to the client and the community the
creation of a major national centre for contemporary art should involve the
public in art in a new way.
Will the Tate rescue the great Giles Gilbert Scott power station on London's
Bankside as its new home and link it to the City with a new bridge? The Tate
debate has just begun but it could bring art and architecture into public
prominence in a positive way.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8621 Professional Organizations.
    P2721 Periodicals.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
