<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Given the obsession with serial killers and ghastly crimes, it was obvious
that TV drama would soon turn to forensic psychology, the glamour profession
of the 1990s. The forensic psychologist is a modern witchdoctor. In a
paranoid society, he offers reassurance that we have mind-readers who can
track down the killers in our midst. Cracker (9.00 ITV), which starts
tonight, is a grim and violent detective series set in Scotland. Robbie
Coltrane stars as a police shrink with uncanny 'profiling' skills and a
conventionally unhappy domestic life.
At this time of year, ashamed by loss of face on holiday, many of us sign up
for language courses and look for subtitled imports on TV. If French has
been your Waterloo, you could start with Prostitute (9.00 C4). But be
warned. In tonight's programme on the bleak lives of two transvestite
prostitutes, the business of gender becomes sorely confused.
If you are looking for laughs, try the new comedy Get Back (8.30 BBC), about
the effect of recession on working-class folk in a particularly tatty area
of north London.
</TEXT>
