<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / Management: Checking out the front line - Sir Alistair
Grant, chairman of Argyll, suggests ways of staying close to staff and
customers / Tips from the top
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Sir ALISTAIR GRANT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Napoleon is popularly credited with responsibility for introducing the
metric system, but the truth is that he tried to suppress it. He wrote of
its proposed introduction: 'Nothing is more contrary to the organisation of
the mind, of memory and of the imagination.' Presumably he thought he was in
touch with the wishes of the common people; in fact, he was surrounded by
advisers, lobbyists and eminent men and women cut off from direct contact
with everyday life.
We all run the risk of becoming petty Napoleons, and none of us has
Napoleon's compensating genius. How can we continue to take the pulse of our
business when we become directors or general managers excluded from direct
contact with front-line staff or with our customers? We can side-step the
problem in two ways: we can rely on market research or, more pompously, we
can suggest that we are responsible for the direction of the business -
strategy, policy, the provision of key resources - rather than its detailed
management.
During the past five years I have introduced a number of practices into
Argyll in an attempt to ensure that directors stay close to the market, and
also to encourage more people throughout the company to think about the
whole business, not just their particular product or store or department.
Our first initiative was the Young Managers' Forum. We selected 24 men and
women from every part of the company - operations, trading, marketing,
finance, distribution, personnel - and split them, more or less randomly,
into four sub-groups. Each group selected a mentor from the Safeway board
and chose a project which they would tackle together over a 12-month period.
One group elected to deal with 'stress and tension among customers and staff
at the supermarket checkout'. By the time they were through they had
re-designed the checkout, eliminated the wires, metal pipes and flashing
lights, introducing a pleasant green colour, creating more space and
introducing a back-to-back module which enabled each checkout operator to
see the face of his or her opposite number at the next checkout instead of
having to stare at the back of a head.
Other groups have looked at projects such as fruit merchandising to avoid
spoilage, at ways of getting to know more about specific customers in each
store, at opportunities for selling to offices and work places - all with
positive results.
Last year I asked each director three questions. Had he ever managed a
store? When did he last manage a store? What was the size of the largest
store he had managed? The results were fairly predictable. Only around a
quarter of us had store management experience, none of us had managed a
store within the past 20 years, the biggest store any of us had managed was
less than half the size of our current average new store.
I invited each director to adopt a store for a year. The brief was to get to
know the store, its customers and its competitors; to assist the store
manager to improve his operations; to become the colleague of management and
staff; and to contribute to Safeway's competence in store operations by
improving our understanding of how 'head office' decisions affect life at
store level.
My own adopted store is in a Midland town and competes with two discount
operators. Sometimes I spend half a day there acting not as a supernumerary
district manager but as a colleague of the store manager. I can take an
interest in any aspect of the store, I can spend a morning talking to
customers, I can assess our specific local strengths and weaknesses against
the competition.
What am I learning? There is too much to recount, but it includes noting
that it takes us too long to make a cup of cappuccino in our cafe, that we
need to improve our in-store pizza operations, that customer problems in a
dry cleaning department can be tough problems for staff to deal with and a
host of other observations that are helpful to me and to the whole business.
The man who said 'Retail is Detail' was only partly right but he was
(partly) very right.
Next Monday: Christopher Haskins of Northern Foods on how to handle the
press.
</TEXT>
<XX>
