<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / Management: Long march to market - State enterprises still
dominate China's economy. A recent study may help foreign investors in their
dealings with them
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALEXANDER NICOLL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
China's remarkable economic growth is driven by non-state industries, yet
state-owned enterprises still account for half of industrial output and 70
per cent of urban workforces. Any company with significant business in China
will have to deal with them, and may even consider them as candidates for a
joint venture.
Research by British and Chinese universities, however, suggests that the
progress of state-owned enterprises towards the adoption of market-oriented
management practices is painfully slow. The findings will be important for
foreign companies whose managers may be trying to find out what makes
Chinese companies tick, or to ascertain whether their own objectives and
those of a local partner are compatible.
The research project, led by Lancaster University Management School,
compared practices at Chinese enterprises with those of British
private-sector companies in similar fields. It particularly examined how
companies made decisions on strategic investments, and management of human
resources.
The researchers found that in Britain the process of winning the support of
colleagues, managers and eventually the board for a new project was similar
to that in China and took just as much time. The efforts of Chinese
managers, however, were mostly directed outside the company. The
relationships they needed to build were with supervisory ministries and
other authorities, with the aim of securing the many approvals needed for a
project to go ahead.
A second conclusion was that Chinese companies inevitably took a far broader
range of considerations into account, including conformity with central
plans, social responsibilities and technological progress. This suggests
that not much has changed yet in the management of state-owned enterprises -
many of which are chronically loss-making - in spite of the 'contract
responsibility' system under which enterprises sign three- to four-year
profit contracts with their supervisory authority.
Caution is necessary. The investment projects analysed were all approved
more than two years ago. Managers interviewed by the researchers indicated
that things were beginning to change. One sign of the new order came from
the director of Nanjing Chemical, who said he had turned down promotion to
positions in ministries because he wanted to be chairman if shareholder
ownership was introduced.
Still, it will take years for the market-place to break down the uniformity
which the research team found in the approaches of the Chinese companies.
Standardised behaviour - which does at least help the foreigner to know what
to expect - derives from the structure of ministries which draw senior staff
from the enterprises, and from a system designed to manage the entire
country from the top down.
The communist party's role in the management of companies helps to
perpetuate a common approach. The party secretary within an enterprise forms
a balance of power with its director - though there are signs that the
former's role is tending to be limited to monitoring personnel decisions,
and that professional managers are on the rise.
At Beijing Yanshan Petrochemicals the researchers found the party secretary
to be more important than the director, whose appointment he had
recommended. But in Nanjing Chemical the director had worked his way up over
30 years, had strong links with the supervising ministry and controlled all
business decisions including personnel, while the party secretary's role was
limited.
Although there has been some devolution of authority, the researchers found
that all important investment decisions had to be approved by the state or
national government. Once the nod came from the minister concerned,
approvals would follow in rapid sequence from all other relevant
authorities. One company established an office in Beijing for six months to
lobby for its new chemical plant. Its executives repeatedly telephoned key
officials to ensure they had all the information.
Proposals were still driven less by the sensing of a market opportunity than
by a need identified in central planning - for example, shortage of a
specific petrochemical. Managers said projects were becoming more
market-directed and that proposals needed to contain more detailed market
analysis, particularly as the state had ceased to provide grants and
financing must be negotiated with banks. However, the researchers commented
that 'managers' understanding of the market and, in fact, the market itself,
was still dominated and distorted by the continued strong planning bias of
the system'.
Procedures for individual performance evaluation and promotion, though
sophisticated, are also homogeneous. Under an annual appraisal system,
specialist units within companies interview some 15 to 20 of a manager's
peers and a larger number of subordinates about his or her performance.
Criteria for promotion are, in order: good moral and political practice,
competence and motivation in present job, quality of relationships with
others in the company, and performance record. Senior managers are chosen
from production posts and will have deep knowledge of operations. Dismissals
are rare.
However, changes are beginning to be forced upon companies: graduates are no
longer automatically assigned to their first jobs by ministries, and the
growth of non-state industry means that a large part of the labour market is
outside the planners' control. In the fast-growing province of Guangdong,
directors operate with more autonomy, and have to offer higher salaries and
fringe benefits to attract staff.
It is sometimes suggested that state industries will simply wither in the
face of the dynamic growth of industry not directly owned by the state.
However, their economic role is so central and their losses such a drain on
the national budget that it seems essential for the government to take
direct action if economic reform is to be sustainable.
For information on the research project, contact David Brown or Mark
Easterby-Smith, Lancaster University Management School, Lancaster LA1 4YX,
UK.
</TEXT>
<XX>
