<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / The Week Ahead: Looking for signs of a Japanese upturn -
Economics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEW light may be shed during the week on the degree to which the Japanese
economy is getting back into gear following the long spell of sluggishness.
Those looking for the country to help propel the world economy into a phase
of sustained expansion by the mid 1990s will be hoping for a reasonably
positive number tomorrow when the Japanese government releases latest
estimates of the year on year change in retail sales in August.
However on the back of estimates by international economists, the retail
data will be less than encouraging, showing a 3.8 per cent year on year drop
after one of 5 per cent in July. Other data from Japan will provide the
latest details of consumer price inflation and industrial production.
In the US, revised second quarter gross domestic product data on Wednesday,
August personal income and consumption figures on Thursday and leading
indicators on Friday will be monitored.
The financial markets will also be looking out for news from the
International Monetary Fund annual meeting in Washington. The gatherings may
provide some indications of the latest progress or lack of it in talks on
freeing global trade and also on how Europe should try to re-create some
degree of exchange rate stability after the fiasco of the virtual breakdown
of the exchange rate mechanism.
In the UK, there will be no significant economic data. Attention will focus
on Wednesday's auction of Pounds 3.25bn of 11-year gilts required to help
finance the 1993-94 Pounds 50bn borrowing requirement. The price of the
stock sold in the auction will indicate to what degree overseas institutions
continue their recent fairly strong support for gilt purchases.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, is showing signs of wanting to listen to
the business world for advice on economic strategy. So the publication this
week of reports by the Institute of Directors and Confederation of British
Industry on what they want to see in the chancellor's budget strategy will
attract more than the unusual amount of attention.
Finally, today sees the publication of the latest report on what to expect
in the German economy from the respected economics group IFO.
The main events of the week are as follows. Median market forecasts from the
financial information company MMS International are in brackets.
Today: US, International Monetary Fund and World Bank meetings in Washington
until Thursday; US August home sales.
Germany, business climate report by IFO economics institute.
Tomorrow: France, five-year employment plan due to be discussed in
parliament, Treasury issues 10-year Ecu bond.
Japan, August retail sales (3.8 per cent down on year), July indices of
economic growth.
Finland, July unemployment figures.
US, September index of consumer confidence.
Canada, August industrial production (0.2 per cent up on month), raw
materials price index (up 0.1 per cent on month).
UK, Institute of Directors unveils Budget advice to Mr Kenneth Clarke,
chancellor.
Wednesday: Australia, current account figures for August, August building
data.
US, details of gross domestic product for second quarter and after-tax
corporate profits, export and import price indices for August, September
agricultural prices.
UK, Confederation of British Industry unveils Budget advice to Mr Clarke.
Bank of England auctions Pounds 3.25bn of 6.75 per cent gilts maturing in
2004.
Thursday: Japan, August construction orders, housing and construction
starts. August industrial production (down 1.5 per cent on year.
France, unemployment rate in August (11.8 per cent).
US, initial unemployment claims for week ending September 25, August home
sales and personal income, monetary data for week ending September 20.
Canada, rise in gross domestic product in July (0.2 per cent on month) and
July earnings from employment (up 1.5 per cent on year).
Friday: Germany, Hans Tietmeyer takes over as Bundesbank president.
Japan, September consumer prices index (1.8 per cent up on year, excluding
Tokyo prices, and up 0.9 per cent on year excluding food and other
perishables), August consumer prices index (up 2.1 per cent on year for
whole country, up 1.2 per cent on year excluding food and other
perishables), August unemployment rate.
US, leading indicators for August showing state of economic health, August
factory orders and factory inventories, September figure for the National
Institute of Purchasing Managers index.
During the week: Germany, August import prices and manufacturing output,
industry production.
Denmark, unemployment rate in August (12.3 per cent).
Belgium , September unemployment rate (14.2 per cent).
</TEXT>
