<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / The Week Ahead: Results due
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
SEARS, the retail group, which includes chains such as Olympus, Wallis, Miss
Selfridge and Warehouse, as well as the Selfridges department store, is
expected tomorrow to announce a return to interim profits of about Pounds
30m, after exceptional costs relating to the closure of ter Meulen Post, the
Dutch mail order business. That compares with losses of Pounds 8.8m,
although the figure included an exceptional charge of Pounds 32.5m for the
reorganisation costs of British Shoe Corporation and a Pounds 5.3m loss on
discontinued businesses. Analysts are looking for a strong recovery from
British Shoe, but the performance of the rest of the group is expected to be
patchy.
Dorling Kindersley, the publisher of illustrated reference books floated
last October, is expected to report annual profits of about Pounds 9.5m
tomorrow. Analysts downgraded to that level in March when the group warned
that trading conditions for children's books had become more competitive in
the US. The City will want to hear how that is working out, plus any
progress on multi-media, the futuristic combination of images, words and
music on CD technology, which has made DK such a glamour stock.
Redland, the construction materials group, reports its interim results on
Thursday and is expected to lift pre-tax profits to about the Pounds 100m
mark, against Pounds 88.5m last time. Behind the increase will lie
reductions in the cost base and the German operations, where success is
continuing apace.
Forte, the hotels and restaurants group, also reports interim profits on
Thursday, with expectations of pre-tax profits of between Pounds 42m and
Pounds 45m. News of the progress of the London hotels will be closely noted.
Further word is awaited on progress in selling the Harvester business.
Worries about a rights issue continue, but the balance of City opinion is
that it is unlikely.
</TEXT>
