<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / The Labour Party at Brighton: Smith unsure of backing in
tense battle on reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART and EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AFTER a day of union delegation meetings and the publication of the final
motions on party reform it was still not clear last night whether Mr John
Smith, the Labour leader, would win Wednesday's vital vote on reforming the
union-party link.
One Labour MP compared the tightness of the vote to the battle between Lord
Healey and Mr Tony Benn for the deputy leadership in 1981. 'The atmosphere
in the party is not as divisive as it was then but the outcome of the vote
is just as important in terms of the perception of the party and its
electability,' said Mr Giles Radice, a strong supporter of the Smith
reforms.
The Smith-backed National Executive Committee rule change, which excludes
the unions from voting in the selection of parliamentary candidates, looks
much more likely to scrape through after the delegation of Nupe, the public
services union, decided to back it last night.
Mr Tom Sawyer, deputy general secretary of Nupe, said after a tense
delegation meeting: 'I say to everyone at this conference, do we want to win
the next election? If we want to win it, we want to do it with John Smith as
leader, and that means supporting him now.'
Assuming that two-thirds of constituency parties have also backed the rule
change then it should have just over 50 per cent support.
If fewer than two-thirds of the constituency parties have backed the reform
then the Smith/NEC reform may require the backing of the MSF white-collar
union, or one of the other smaller unions. The MSF last night said it would
decide later in the week.
There are now four main composite motions on offer. Two of them, moved by
the TGWU and GMB general unions, are strongly hostile to the
one-member-one-vote reform. Although they both propose slightly different
alternatives the two unions made clear yesterday they would be supporting
each other.
Nonetheless, neither is expected to win a majority.
A third motion, moved by the loyalist AEEU craft union, is a strong
statement of support for one member one vote and will certainly fail.
A fourth composite, released only yesterday, moved by the RMT rail union and
Nupe, and backed by the NEC, is a complex mixture of positions. It is likely
to be passed - although it will be rejected by the TGWU and GMB.
Speaking at a fringe meeting, Mr Neil Kinnock, the former Labour leader,
appealed to Mr Edmonds not to oppose the switch to one-member-one-vote in
the vital debate on Wednesday.
Mr Kinnock said he was certain the change would be approved and dismissed
the whole idea that the campaign for one-member-one-vote was a plot to
exclude trade unionists from the Labour party as a 'fantasy'.
