<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / Market reforms 'cut BBC costs'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BBC'S controversial producer choice policy has been endorsed by an
evaluation committee including external consultants, Raymond Snoddy writes.
A report to be published next month will conclude that the policy, which
gives producers the freedom to buy services in the outside market, has been
successful in cutting costs.
The one criticism is that the new trading units in the corporation, which
has a licence fee income of about Pounds 1.5bn a year, have generated too
much paperwork. In future producers will be encouraged to rationalise
transactions.
The study shows that there has not been a large exodus to the outside market
by BBC producers.
Before the scheme was implemented on January 1, BBC management forecast that
an average of 15 per cent of BBC work would go to outside suppliers. The
total has been lower. Producers of long-running programmes, for example,
have tended to negotiate long-term deals covering use of BBC studios.
