<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / Council review to speed up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR John Gummer, the environment secretary, is expected this week to announce
plans for accelerating the review of local government's structure in England
and Wales.
The review will be completed by the end of next year, it is hoped, in line
with the wishes expressed by Sir John Banham, chairman of the local
government commission for England, in an address to the annual conference of
the Association of Metropolitan Authorities last week.
Sir John has accepted a full-time job as chairman of Tarmac, the
construction company, but has not announced plans to leave the commission.
Provisional plans for restructuring four groups of English counties -
Derbyshire; Cleveland and Durham; North Yorkshire, Humberside and
Lincolnshire; and Somerset, Avon and Gloucestershire - have come up against
strong opposition from local authorities and business leaders.
Counties and districts have so far offered contradictory proposals. But
authorities that have not already been visited by the commission have
started to agree plans to put to the commission. Cambridgeshire district
councils last week agreed estimates of the transition costs involved in six
alternative new structures. All the options would cost at least Pounds 11.7m
initially.
There are complaints that the process, currently scheduled to last until
1997, is too lengthy.
</TEXT>
