<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / Firefighters split on strike ballot
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WATCH at Southwark fire station in central London is divided about how
to vote in the strike ballot that starts next Monday.
'I can't afford to go on strike,' said Mr Bill Horlock, coming off his
Saturday all-night duty. 'But there is a good cause for one.'
The majority of firefighters at Southwark, as elsewhere in the capital, are
not in a militant mood. 'We don't want to go out of the door,' explained one
of them. 'There is a feeling of despondency here.'
A recent straw poll taken among all the London brigades found a majority
against strike action, though this was less overwhelming a verdict than
earlier in the summer when as many as 70 per cent said they opposed possible
industrial action.
'The real doubt is what will happen to our pay formula next year,' says Mr
Ted Ciplinksi. 'Our employers say we will have it in full but many
firefighters don't trust the government to allow this to happen.
'I've no doubt we would have voted against a strike call before Kenneth
Clarke (the chancellor) announced a second year of public sector wage
restraint. Now we are not so sure.' Mr Horlock agrees. 'We would have
swallowed the pay formula's suspension for a year but we wonder whether the
local authorities will be able to afford to meet the award in 1994 without
borrowing from the government.'
Another Southwark firefighter says: 'Our motto is we will never be rich but
we will also never be poor.' With pay linked to the upper quartile of male
manual earnings since 1978, the fire service is not a pace-setter in pay.
Awards are a catch-up with the private sector. Pay averages just over Pounds
300 a week and firefighters' labour costs make up 2 per cent of local
government's.
But firefighters fear that if they do go on strike, even just for 24 hours,
they will be locked out by their employers.
</TEXT>
