<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / Lloyd's corporate launch
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE QUARTER of the shares in a corporate capital fund designed for the
Lloyd's of London insurance market will be aimed at individuals, it has
emerged.
The CLM Insurance Fund, which today becomes the first Lloyd's corporate
capital fund to issue a 'pathfinder' prospectus, plans to target wealthy
individuals as well as institutions.
The emphasis on individual investment comes in spite of the disenchantment
of many Names - the individuals whose assets underwrite the market - who
have lost large sums of money in the past few years.
About 70 Lloyd's syndicates have expressed interest in offering Pounds 250m
in underwriting capacity for the fund, and institutions have so far
tentatively offered to invest up to Pounds 150m to the fund, which will be
in the form of a quoted investment trust. The minimum investment for
individuals will be about Pounds 1,000.
The CLM Fund prospectus says its investments initially will concentrate on
reinsurance, aviation, energy and the motor business.
CLM will invest its money in equities designed to track the overall
performance of the FT-SE index, based on advice from BZW asset management.
The money will also be pledged on Lloyd's syndicates, allocated on advice
from Instrat and Syndicate Analysis Services, both within the Sedgwick
group.
Lloyd's will be able to approve the fund if Names agree to permit the
introduction of corporate capital with limited liability at an extraordinary
general meeting on October 20. The fund also still needs to resolve some tax
issues with the Revenue.
The fund will be chaired by Lord Rees, chairman of Lasmo.
</TEXT>
