<PROFILE>_AN-DI0BZABTFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930927
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / Public-sector tenders rule may ease
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TREASURY may relax its insistence on competition in the awarding of
public-sector contracts in a bid to kick-start the government's private
finance initiative.
This is one of three steps ministers are considering to overcome companies'
reluctance to devise schemes for the initiative, which seeks to involve
private capital in public-sector projects.
Companies have been unwilling to commit resources to devising new proposals
as, once adopted, they are required to go to competitive tender for
implementation.
This means that the tender to implement one company's innovation could be
won by a competitor. This partly explains why the initiative has had a slow
start since it was announced in the Autumn Statement.
Under a tentative framework to be set out today by Mr Stephen Dorrell,
financial secretary to the Treasury, the competition requirement may be
relaxed in 'exceptional' cases where a contract cannot proceed without
access to the physical and intellectual property of a contractor and the
contractor is not willing to grant this to competitors.
This could be done only in cases not covered by European Community
procurement rules requiring competition. A string of conditions would apply,
including that the terms of the contract be published 90 days before it came
into force.
Other steps under consideration by ministers include the offering of
design-only contracts and the partial reimbursement of tendering costs.
This would be limited to no more than half an unsuccessful bidder's expenses
and the bidder would then be required to let others use its intellectual
property.
The Treasury's framework is to be published in the form of a consultation
note, with comments invited by October 29.
The Treasury also suggests that government departments should consider
setting up independent panels of experts to advise on the value of
particular types of intellectual property.
Today's move comes less than three weeks after Mr Kenneth Clarke, the
chancellor, announced the formation of a taskforce representing both public
and private sectors to identify suitable projects and willing investors.
Mr Clarke also promised more guidance for businesses that wanted to invest
in the public sector.
</TEXT>
