FT  27 SEP 93 / Wholesale food markets alert
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
WHOLESALE food markets were warned yesterday that they must improve hygiene
standards and quality control if they are to survive competition from
supermarkets buying direct from producers.
Markets such as New Covent Garden and Smithfield in London are under
pressure to cut costs amid intense competition from food retailers employing
their own farmers.
Opening the annual congress of the World Union of Wholesale Markets, Mr
Geoffrey John, chairman of Food From Britain, the UK farming industry's
promotional agency, said the future of such markets depended on meeting
consumer demands for better hygiene and food quality.
