<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / Crescent Petroleum
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
On March 8 and 11 of this year, the Financial Times reported that Mr Robin
Cook, the shadow spokesman on trade and industry, had raised parliamentary
questions calling for Crescent Petroleum Company International, the
Gulf-based oil company, to be investigated on account of alleged improper
links with the State of Iraq.
In fact, Mr Cook raised no such questions, and the Financial Times was
mistaken to state that he had.
It was not the intention of the Financial Times to suggest in any way that
the company had breached sanctions against Iraq, or that it had any improper
links whatsoever with Iraq. The Financial Times now recognises that a
contrary impression might have been conveyed, and apologises unreservedly to
Crescent Petroleum for any damage or inconvenience caused by its report.
</TEXT>
