<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / Brittan starts hunt for concessions: Sir Leon has to get
some sort of deal for France on farm trade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR Leon Brittan, the EC's chief trade negotiator, will be in an unenviable
position when today in Washington he meets Mr Mickey Kantor, US trade
representative, to try to agree on a compatible EC-US agenda for concluding
the seven-year-old Uruguay Round world trade reform talks.
Sir Leon has to get some sort of deal for France on farm trade, in the
knowledge that failure to deliver apparent US concessions may well sink the
Gatt round and embroil the EC in a profound internal crisis. But US
flexibility on farm trade, if at all possible, will very likely come at the
expense of EC settling for less in other areas of the trade talks, such as
access to the US financial services market.
So what margin for manoeuvre does Sir Leon have?
First, it lies in American willingness to be flexible on some of the details
of Blair House.
Second, political presentation of any eventual deal will depend on the fact
that the details of Blair House are not widely known - especially, Paris
appears to be assuming, in France.
Paris demands that food aid should be exempt from the 21 per cent cut over
six years in subsidised food exports prescribed by Blair House, which is
France's main concern about the agreement. Food aid, however, is already
exempt from the Blair House curbs.
Whether Sir Leon can get any concessions at all, however, is far from
assured.
France's overall aim is to ensure that the 21 per cent cuts on subsidised
food exports never have to be made. Last year's reform of the EC's Common
Agricultural Policy introduced big price cuts and restraints on
overproduction. The European Commission maintains that by around mid-way
through the Gatt/Blair House timetable, EC prices will as a result dip to
around world market levels - making export subsidies and therefore the Blair
House cuts superfluous, and EC prices competitive not only abroad but
against imports.
The US and other agri-exporters do not take these estimates on faith, and
nor does France, although it signed up to CAP reform in May 1992. Although
France could not then, and can not now, say this publicly, French officials
privately admit that their main concern was that the CAP reform did not cut
prices enough. If EC prices are still above world level when the CAP reform
cuts have run their course (at the end of 1996) and a Gatt deal on farm
trade comes on stream (probably around mid-1995) French subsidised exports
will be hit.
The alternatives would be to dispense with the export subsidies anyway, or
drop EC prices further. Blair House allows full compensation to farmers for
price cuts, but Paris appears politically unwilling to risk either of these
options, much less proclaim them as solutions to France's militant farmers.
What the French therefore appear to want Sir Leon to concentrate on with the
Americans is so-called 'front-loading' and food stocks. There may just be
room for settlement on these two issues.
On 'front-loading,' the Uruguay Round draft agreement or 'final act' calls
for the 21 per cent export volume curbs to be made evenly, at about 3.5 per
cent a year, over the six years. But the 'final act' is still a draft, open
to some modification. France wants to be able to shift the cuts to the end
of the timetable, in the hope they will not have to be made at all. France's
attempt to get the EC's food mountains exempted from the curbs is directly
linked to this. Flexibility on timing would allow the EC to get rid of its
stocks without running into the export curbs.
Blair House was originally vague on this problem. But EC negotiators have
told the FT that a subsequent EC-US memorandum established a formula,
requiring full cuts in the first and sixth years of the accord, with freedom
to postpone cuts during intervening years, provided these are 'paid back'
within no more than a year. Interpretations of this vary.
One of the main negotiators of Blair House says 'it really means equal
amounts' to be cut each year. Another says 'if the Americans want to be
helpful, that is an area in which we can resolve this.'
If Sir Leon can get some movement in this area, the Commission and France's
partners must also work to help Paris dress up any eventual deal.
It is not widely appreciated, for instance, that Blair House will require
the US to cut its wheat exports from 19.7m tonnes to 14m tonnes.
Moreover, both US and EC negotiators of Blair House believe that it 'gives
less access to the Community market than was the case last year,' as one
European negotiator put it.
On stocks, the underlying rise in EC grain stockpiles is running at about
half the level prior to CAP reform; French officials are at the moment
choosing to dramatise the stocks figures by ignoring seasonal trends and
developments since CAP price and output cuts started to bite this summer.
One of the EC architects of Blair House maintains, furthermore, that the
'worst case scenario' drawn up by independent economists - premised on
annual 1 per cent grain yield increases nullifying part of the CAP reform
restraints - 'still leaves us on the wrong side of the Gatt limits for
(exporting subsidised) bread-making wheat by only 1m to 1.5m tonnes - and
that can be given out as food aid.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
