<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / French foreign minister warns against protectionist
responses to problems of recession and rising unemployment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
France must avoid protectionist responses to the problems of recession and
rising unemployment, Mr Alain Juppe, foreign minister, warned at the
weekend, John Ridding reports from Paris.
Speaking at a conference of parliamentarians from the RPR party, the
dominant partner of the ruling centre-right coalition government, Mr Juppe
described protectionism as one of the main threats to jobs in France.
Unemployment, currently at 11.7 per cent of the workforce, is expected to
exceed 12 per cent by the end of the year.
The French government has been accused of a protectionist stance by
international trading partners as result of its position on agricultural
trade. In particular, France is demanding changes to an EC-US agricultural
deal which is crucial to completing an agreement on the Uruguay Round of
international trade negotiations. At their weekend meeting at the western
port of La Rochelle, RPR lawmakers voted unanimously in support of a motion
calling on the government to veto any agricultural agreement which damaged
French interests.
