<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / Taiwan company to clone Intel chip
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TAIPEI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TAIWAN's top semiconductor manufacturer plans to launch a clone of the top
selling Intel microprocessor chip, the brains of most personal computers. A
legal battle, which may take on nationalistic tones, seems likely to ensue.
United Microelectronics, Taiwan's flagship chipmaker formed in 1980 with
government support, says it will introduce a 486SX microprocessor chip next
month, with a higher performance 486DX chip to follow next year. UMC plans
to sell the chips only to non-US customers to avoid legal problems with
Intel, which is vigorously defending its intellectual property rights
against other efforts to clone its microprocessors by Advanced Micro Devices
and Cyrix , both of the US.
Avoiding the US market may not, however, protect UMC if Intel determines
that UMC has copied its technology. Intel holds world patents and copyrights
protecting all its products the US company said.
UMC's move reflects Taiwan's ambitions to become a fully-fledged producer of
computers and other electronics product, rather than an assembly site for
US, Japanese and European-branded PCs using components manufactured mainly
in the US and Japan.
Encouraged by the Taiwan government, UMC is attempting to reduce the
dependence of the country's fast-growing electronics industry on foreign
component suppliers. Already the company produces memory chips and several
other semiconductor devices for the PC market. Some 75 per cent of its chips
are sold to Taiwan-based companies although most are ultimately exported in
finished goods or sub-assemblies.
UMC is not expected to put a serious dent in Intel's microprocessor sales.
The company has limited production capacity and is forecasting revenues of
about Dollars 350m (Pounds 227m) this year, up from an estimated Dollars
250m in 1992, but a far cry from Intel's Dollars 5.8bn 1992 revenues.
However, the Taiwanese company is about to begin building a manufacturing
facility that will more than double its output when completed in about two
years. Moreover, UMC is well placed to usurp Intel's near monopoly of the
world PC microprocessor market.
Over the past five years Taiwan's production of PCs and the main circuit
boards that power them has expanded rapidly. Taiwan now produces almost 70
per cent of all PC circuit boards, making it Intel's biggest market. If UMC
succeeds in the microprocessor market, others might be encouraged to follow
suit.
Intel's response to UMC's introduction of 486-clones could also be critical
to the development of Taiwan's electronics industry, the highest growth
segment of its economy. The US company's ownership of the core technology
for PCs represents a serious barrier to Taiwan's ambitions to 'move up the
value chain' in the information technology industry.
This objective - established by the government as a central element of its
industrial policy - has been backed by heavy government spending on research
and development. Taiwan's Information Technology Research Institute has an
annual budget of Dollars 450m.
Thus a legal challenge aimed at UMC by Intel would amount to an attack on
Taiwan's industrial development in the eyes of many Taiwanese. Emotions are
fuelled by the resentment that already exists among Taiwan's PC circuit
board producers towards the US company, which they charge has bullied them
into paying high prices and threatened to cut off supplies of critical
components if they purchase microprocessor 'clones'.
These feelings have been exacerbated by a trade complaint, filed in the US
by Intel against one of Taiwan's PC producers. Intel charges that Twinhead
of Taiwan which makes PCs based on AMD's clone microprocessors, is selling
PCs in the US that infringe its intellectual property rights. ITRI has
stepped in to help defend Twinhead.
A legal battle between Intel and UMC could also undermine Taiwan's efforts
to prove that it has made significant progress in implementing new laws to
protect intellectual property rights as it seeks membership of the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
Intel executives are sceptical that UMC can actually produce 486-compatible
chips.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
