<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / Spain prepares for austerity budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER BRUCE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SPAIN'S minority socialist government will this week present to parliament
the country's most restrictive budget in a decade, in a clear signal to the
trades unions that efforts to trim the state's runaway deficits are being
given priority over any quick fixes for Spain's record number of unemployed.
The cabinet approved the draft 1994 budget at the weekend and officials were
later insisting, despite scepticism from the opposition, that it was not
alterable.
This means that, after three weeks of fruitless talking to the unions on the
terms of a 'social pact' - an effort to develop a common front on pulling
the country out of recession - the government has had to impose a series of
budgetary targets it had initially hoped to reach by negotiation.
Officials say three measures being negotiated with the unions - a freeze in
civil service pay for 1994, a limit of 3.5 per cent in state pension
increases for next year and cuts in the budget of the employment benefits -
are now set in stone. Almost Pta300bn (Pounds 1.52bn) has been trimmed from
Inem, the national employment institute which funds benefits.
The unions, which last year called an unsuccessful strike in protest at
earlier cuts in benefits, appear to have miscalculated again. 'The unions
only hear what they want to hear,' said Mr Pedro Solbes, the finance
minister, after Friday's cabinet meeting. 'We have been telling them since
August that we had until now, today, to solve our deficit problems.'
Nevertheless the government hopes to resume taking to the unions, and
employers, early next week about a wider pay agreement. Madrid is looking
for a three-year wage moderation pact (under which employers would restrict
dividend payments and raise investment) crucial to the credibility of the
recovery programme it is trying to construct.
These broader talks will be made more difficult by the budget and the
realisation by the unions that they may have been outsmarted. 'The unions
thought that if they promised to talk to us later about a global (private
and public sector) wages deal, we would be prepared to give way on pension,
benefits and the civil service freeze in the budget,' said a senior Finance
Ministry official.
'But we were saying the opposite. If we go on now and get a global
three-year agreement to moderate wages by the end of November, we are saying
that we may ease some of our criteria. But only after 1994.'
On the surface at least, the government is being uncommonly tough. Once the
budget is presented, the upper and lower houses of parliament have until the
end of the year to debate it and sceptics will be watching not the unions
but the Catalan party, the CiU, to dent the government fiscal resolve.
Mr Gonzalez needs CiU support to pass the budget but the Catalans are
balking.
Primarily, the Catalans want agreement from Madrid that 15 per cent of the
income tax raised by the central government should be given to the
government of the region in which it was raised. Madrid agrees but there are
arguments about how. Poor regions claim Catalonia will become progressively
richer. The CiU, not without cause, worries about the speed at which Madrid
would implement this new system.
In reality the CiU should have little problem supporting the budget. Mr
Solbes has tried to present a more realistic set of targets than had become
common under his more ebullient predecessor, Mr Carlos Solchaga, even though
his 1994 growth forecast of 1.3 per cent may look optimistic after an
expected decline in GDP this year of 0.8 per cent. Even at 1.3 per cent
growth, though, Spain will not create jobs.
Mr Solbes has also committed himself to an annual inflation target of 3.5
per cent for next year though this probably had more to do with fixing next
year's pension increases to the expected rate of inflation than to what is
seriously achievable.
The government is being very cautious on how quickly it can draw down its
deficits. Mr Solchaga had planned a central government deficit (the social
security system included) of 3 per cent of GDP for 1993. Mr Solbes said it
would turn out closer to 6.2 per cent and his target for 1994 is 5.7 per
cent.
By last August the central deficit was Pta1,000bn higher than planned.
Conservative new targets will appeal to the CiU, who are also likely to be
attracted by an annex to the budget containing a slew of tax breaks designed
to help small businesses and stimulate industrial activity.
CiU support comes from small business and the party could anger its grass
roots if, in the end, it were not to come in behind Mr Gonzalez and give him
his budget.
That would leave only the unions on the outside. Government officials know
they cannot force private employers to moderate pay but warn that, in the
absence of a wages pact, they will punish overgenerous employers. Officials
do, however, say they have the power to implement a series of labour market
reforms which are to be negotiated along with the global wages deal from
next week. The more reluctant the unions are to commit themselves to pay
restraint, the tougher the labour market reforms will be.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ESZ  Spain, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
