<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / Belgium to seek air passenger quotas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS and DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BELGIUM will today seek at a meeting of EC aviation ministers in Brussels
the re-introduction of passenger capacity quotas to help financially
strapped European airlines. The move will be firmly opposed by the UK.
The meeting has been called by Belgium, which currently holds the EC
presidency, and whose government has come under increasing pressure to
support Sabena, the financially troubled Belgian flag carrier.
Belgium is expected to present a paper at the meeting which raises the
possibility not only of re-introducing capacity-sharing arrangements between
airlines, but also floats the idea of EC funding for airlines in trouble. In
response, Mr John MacGregor, the UK transport minister, is expected to make
a strong plea against further government subsidies to support the EC's
state-owned flag carriers.
The UK is particularly concerned that the EC does not backtrack on its air
transport liberalisation policy because of the current difficulties faced by
the airline industry.
However, a number of other EC countries, led by France, consider the UK
position as 'hypocritical.
Mr Bernard Attali, the chairman of Air France, argued that UK carriers were
the 'most protected' in the world through the existing bilateral aviation
agreement between the UK and the US.
'Apostles of British liberalism carefully close the doors to London Heathrow
and continue to reap the easy profits of the Anglo-American air traffic
agreement, Bermuda 2, signed in 1977,' he said.
The agreement was tantamount to a state subsidy, he claimed.
The meeting of aviation ministers also coincides with a series of hearings
held this month by an EC group of 'wise men' set up to analyse and propose
cures for the European airline industry which lost Dollars 700m (Pounds
466m) last year.
Several EC countries and their national carriers have argued for the
re-introduction of some capacity controls scrapped under the EC airline
liberalisation package in the face of continuing over capacity in the
airline market.
At the same time, a number of state carriers, including Aer Lingus, Air
France, Sabena and Iberia, have been seeking additional cash injections from
their governments to support them during the current, prolonged industry
recession.
But the UK government and UK airlines argue that additional government
financial support would simply distort even more competition in the market
and that troubled airlines must launch restructuring programmes to make
themselves more efficient by sharply reducing their heavy level of unit
costs.
Attali interview, second section
</TEXT>
