<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / Parliament rebellion starts to fade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE RUSSIAN parliament's struggle against its abolition by President Boris
Yeltsin appeared last night to be waning, after a weekend of cold, dark and
increasingly hungry isolation behind cordons of riot troops and police.
Mr Yeltsin and his government have kept up a momentum of decrees and orders
designed to bring rebels in the provinces into line, and to tackle economic
problems previously frozen by the gridlock between the presidential and
parliamentary powers.
The official Tass news agency reported last night that talks had begun
between the rebel parliament and representatives of the Interior Ministry
and the procurator's office on the handing over of the weapons still held by
guards and supporters in the parliament's 'White House'.
Tass said General Alexander Rutskoi, former vice president designated acting
president by the parliamentary deputies, agreed to the handover on condition
that the usual military protocols on handing over weapons were observed.
However, last night Gen Rutskoi and Mr Ruslan Khasbulatov, parliamentary
speaker, remained in the White House, which has had its light and heat shut
off, and both continued to express a determination to fight to the end. A
forage party of some 500 deputies and supporters left the building early in
the evening, saying they were 'looking for food' - amid some speculation
from the police who let them out on their intentions to return.
Early this morning armed guards patrolling the White House began
strengthening barricades amid rumours of an imminent attack. Mr Khasbulatov
said he had information that a raid was being prepared, although there was
no sign of this among government troops ringing the building.
Meanwhile, Mr Valery Zorkin, head of the constitutional court, is shuttling
between Gen Rutskoi and Mr Mikhail Poltaranin, a close Yeltsin aide, in an
attempt to get a compromise on which the siege could end. Mr Zorkin said he
had proposed a 'zero option' - of a return to the status quo before
parliament was abolished coupled with early and simultaneous presidential
and parliamentary elections - and claimed Gen Rutskoi 'is inclined to accept
one of these options'.
But the weekend saw a blaze of confidence by the president's side, the apex
of which was a concert yesterday, attended by Mr Yeltsin and his senior
aides, at which the emigre cellist Mr Mstislav Rostropovich conducted a
performance of the 1812 Overture in a packed Red Square. The cannons and
bells which are part of the overture - rejoicing at Napoleon's retreat from
Moscow - were provided by the Kremlin.
Mr Yeltsin admits the regional councils are evenly split on support for him.
Those few regional administrators who had 'reacted badly' would be fired -
Mr Yuri Lodkin, the governor of Bryansk region, already has been.
Mr Yeltsin has also adopted a decree holding all officials and serving
officers responsible for the carrying out of his decree on constitutional
reform, signed last Tuesday - though the decree also forbids the arrest of
those demonstrating against him.
The government has passed a decree stipulating that the central bank must
stop advancing low-interest credits, limiting its lending to loans at the
new, 180 per cent per annum interest rate - a rate which is even higher than
it appears, because the bank divides the annual rate by 12 to set a monthly
rate, then compounds up the monthly rate.
A constitutional assembly bringing together representatives of parties,
associations, enterprises and unions has started work on a draft
constitution and on an election law for a new federal assembly, which Mr
Yeltsin has decreed will be elected on December 12.
But sentiment is growing for simultaneous parliamentary and presidential
elections, instead of the six-month gap he has decreed between the federal
assembly elections and the June 12 presidential elections.
Mr Sergei Filatov, Mr Yeltsin's chief of staff, said at the weekend the gap
was needed to give stability, especially important in a nuclear state.
However, simultaneous elections have centrist and liberal support from a
range of prominent figures including Mr Grigor Yavlinsky, the main declared
challenger for the presidency, Mr Mikhail Gorbachev, the last Soviet
president, Mr Nikolai Fyodorov, the former Russian justice minister, and Mr
Nikolai Ryzhkov, the former Soviet prime minister.
</TEXT>
