<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / Yeltsin plans visit to Tokyo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RUSSIAN President Boris Yeltsin is planning to visit Tokyo in the middle of
next month, in spite of the continuing turmoil in Moscow, according to
Japanese government officials, writes Robert Thomson in Tokyo. Mr Yeltsin
has cancelled Tokyo visits twice in the past year, but Japanese officials
say Mr Andrei Kozyrev, the Russian foreign minister, indicated that the
president will visit Japan for a 'few days' from October 12.
Mr Kozyrev met Mr Tsutomu Hata, Japan's foreign minister, in New York, where
the two agreed that a Russian delegation should be sent to Japan to finalise
details of Mr Yeltsin's visit.
Japanese officials said Mr Yeltsin apparently wants to send a signal to
opponents that he is confident enough of his hold on power to make the trip.
The Russian president, they said, also did not want to damage relations with
Japan by cancelling again.
The previous cancellations arose from a territorial dispute between Japan
and Russia over the Kurile Islands at Japan's northern tip, occupied by
Soviet troops at the end of the second world war.
Japanese officials said Mr Kozyrev indicated that the Kurile dispute would
be discussed during the Russian president's visit.
The assurances by Mr Kozyrev about the visit next month have come as a
surprise to the Japanese government, which had begun to think that a
postponement was inevitable, given the conflict in Moscow over the past
week.
Mr Eduard Shevardnadze, the Georgian leader, last night rejected a plea by
his government to be evacuated by the Russians from the besieged city of
Sukhumi, a source close to the government said, agencies report from
Tbilisi.
His refusal came as Abkhazian soldiers tightened their grip on the regional
capital of the breakaway region of western Georgia, which has been cut off
from the rest of the country after separatists broke a seven-week-old
ceasefire 11 days ago.
Mr Shevardnadze's chief of staff, Mr Vazha Lortkipanidze, said although the
former Soviet foreign minister had been cut off by the Abkhazians he had not
yet been cornered.
</TEXT>
