<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / German coalition falls into disarray
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ATTEMPTS by Germany's governing coalition to elect Mr Steffen Heitmann as
president were thrown into disarray at the weekend when the Free Democrats,
the junior coalition partner, implicitly rejected him as a candidate, writes
Judy Dempsey in Berlin.
Without support by the FDP, Chancellor Helmut Kohl's governing Christian
Democratic Union and the Christian Social Union, its sister party in
Bavaria, could not gain a majority of votes in a special congress convened
next May to chose a successor to Mr Richard Von Weizsacker. The opposition
Social Democrats have already nominated Mr Johannes Rau, prime minister of
the state of North Rhine-Westphalia.
Mr Klaus Kinkel, foreign minister and FDP leader, said in an interview at
the weekend that 'Heitmann is not our man.' Mr Heitmann is justice minister
of the eastern state of Saxony. The FDP, backed by many women deputies in
the Bundestag or Lower House, is increasingly swinging behind Ms Hildegard
Hamm-Brucher, the author and former secretary of state at the foreign
ministry. The party had earlier asked Mr Hans-Dietrich Genscher, the former
foreign minister, but he refused.
Although Ms Hamm-Brucher, 72, is not from eastern Germany, she is seen as
someone who would help the psychological integration of the two Germanies in
Europe.
The FDP's reluctance to support the government stems from Mr Heitmann's
views over Europe, in which he criticised the way in which the Maastricht
Treaty has been imposed on the member states of the EC. The party is also
deeply sceptical about his views on German unification.
Mr Kohl had chosen Mr Heitmann because he is from eastern Germany. But
officials in Saxony conceded it was a mistake. 'This is a token gesture for
the east Germans, who increasingly feel bitter about how they are being used
in this campaign,' a Saxon government official said.
</TEXT>
