FT  27 SEP 93 / World Bank/IMF Meeting: Appeal on Trinidad terms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the UK chancellor, yesterday called for a further
strengthening of the Trinidad terms for giving debt relief to the poorest
developing countries, writes Peter Norman.
In a speech to the policy-making interim committee of the International
Monetary Fund, Mr Clarke said the waiting period during which countries
qualified for a reduction of their stock of official debt should be cut from
the present three to four years. He later suggested that 12 months might be
sufficient for countries with a good record of economic reform.
Mr Clarke also said the rate of debt reduction should be increased to two
thirds, from 50 per cent.
