<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / World Bank/IMF Meeting: Gatt chief warns of impasse on farm
talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER and GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Peter Sutherland, director-general of the General Agreement of Tariffs
and Trade, damped hopes yesterday of any early solution to the critical
dispute between the European Community and the US which threatens world
trade reforms.
He said an attempt by the EC at French insistence to amend the Blair House
accord on agriculture, reached last November between the EC and the US, had
created 'an impasse to which a clear solution is not apparent'.
A crucial aspect of the accord envisages a 21 per cent cut in the volume of
subsidised EC food exports over the next six years.
Mr Sutherland, speaking after addressing the IMF interim committee in
Washington, warned the dispute was among issues that could wreck the Uruguay
Round of trade talks due to finish by December 15. He said he could not
foresee the deadline being extended.
Sir Leon Brittan, EC trade commissioner, and Mr Mickey Kantor, US trade
representative, are to discuss the dispute in Washington today. It arose
after France called for further 'clarifications' to the accord.
Mr Sutherland's remarks came as the World Bank disclosed findings of a study
which concluded the partial trade liberalisation envisaged under the Uruguay
Round could add Dollars 213bn (Pounds 138.3bn) a year to world income by
2002.
Brittan and Kantor to meet, Page 6
</TEXT>
