<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / World Bank/IMF Meeting: Schlesinger firesparting shots
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Helmut Schlesinger was in feisty mood when he met the press in Washington
at the weekend.
Making one of his last media appearances before stepping down as Bundesbank
president at the end of this week, he lashed out at critics of Bundesbank
policy, the European exchange rate mechanism, and particularly at the IMF's
latest World Economic Outlook.
The document was wrong to suggest that German unification had decisively
hindered global recovery by forcing high short-term interest rates on other
countries, he said.
German union had not prevented countries with floating currencies such as
the US from cutting their interest rates. It was the European exchange rate
mechanism that was at fault.
He gave short shrift to suggestions that German interest rates were too
high. Capital market rates had fallen to their lowest levels in many years.
But he reserved special scorn for the unknown author of the IMF outlook who
had omitted to include any reference to money supply in its 200 pages. This,
he said, was an extraordinary philosophical lapse for a monetary body such
as the IMF.
</TEXT>
