<HEADLINE>
FT  27 SEP 93 / World Bank/IMF Meeting: Russia hopes to stabilise budget
soon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RUSSIA has told the Group of Seven leading industrial nations that it hopes
to stabilise its budget position this year so it can qualify for more
financial aid from the IMF.
At a meeting on Saturday with G7 finance ministers and central bank
governors, Mr Boris Fyodorov, the Russian finance minister, described
Russian plans to cut subsidies on grain and bread production, change taxes
and remove indexation with the aim of cutting the budget deficit and
inflation by late this year.
At that time the IMF might be able to release a second Dollars 1.5bn (Pounds
1bn) loan to Russia under its systemic transformation facility to help
Russia's difficult move towards a market economy, G7 officials said.
At the end of Saturday's meeting, the finance ministers from the US, Japan,
Germany, France, Britain, Italy and Canada 'expressed their very strong
hope' that the political developments of the past week 'will help Russia
achieve a decisive breakthrough on the path of market reform'.
The ministers praised President Boris Yeltsin's commitment to pursue the
path of market-oriented reform, which they saw as right for creating a
better future for the Russian people and integrating Russia into the world
economy.
But before meeting Mr Fyodorov, the G7 ministers decided among themselves
that new financial support should not be given to Russia before it had
brought its economic reform programme back on the track laid down by the IMF
during the summer.
'There was a general sense among G7 officials that the provision of
stabilisation support has to be measured with the progress of reform,' a US
Treasury official said.
'It must be help for self-help,' declared Mr Theo Waigel, the German finance
minister, who said Mr Fyodorov had made no request for an easing of the
economic policy conditions on which the IMF support has been based.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
